{"title_page": "International availability of McDonald's products", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{more citations needed|date=December 2008}}\n{{original research|date=December 2008}}\n{{primary sources|date=August 2015}}\n}}\n'''McDonald's Corporation''' ({{nyse|MCD}}) is the world's largest chain of [[fast food]] restaurants, serving around 68 million customers daily in 119 countries.<ref name=daily>{{cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/McDonald-Momentum-Delivers-prnews-2702110553.html?x=0 |title=McDonald's Momentum Delivers Another Year of Strong Results for 2011 |publisher=Yahoo Finance |year=2012 |accessdate=2012-01-25 }}{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.burgerbusiness.com/?p=9168 |title=McDonald\u2019s Answers the Doubters |publisher=BurgerBusiness |date=2012-01-25}}</ref> [[McDonald's]] traces its origins to a 1940 restaurant in [[San Bernardino, California]]. After expanding within the United States, McDonald's became an international corporation in 1967, when it opened a location in [[Richmond, British Columbia|Richmond, British Columbia, Canada]]. By the end of the 1970s, McDonald's restaurants existed in five of the Earth's seven continents; an African location came in 1992 in Casablanca, Morocco.\n\nIn order to cater to local tastes and [[Cuisine|culinary traditions]], and often in respect of particular laws or religious beliefs, McDonald's offers regionalized versions of its [[McDonald's products|menu]] among and within different countries. As a result, [[List of McDonald's products|products]] found in one country or region may not be found in McDonald's restaurants in other countries.\n\n==Africa==\n===Egypt===\nIn 2001, McDonald's introduced the [[Falafel|McFalafel]] sandwich in its Egypt locations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://adage.com/article/news/mcdonald-s-mcfalafel-a-hit-egyptians/15353/|accessdate=2 August 2012|newspaper=Advertising Age|date=19 June 2001|title=McDonald's McFalafel a hit with Egyptians}}</ref> These restaurants also offer a Chicken [[Big Mac]] and Fish Mac, variations on the standard Big Mac which substitute breaded chicken or fish, respectively, for the usual beef patties. In the summer of 2008, McDonald's introduced fish fingers with tartar dipping sauce as a side in Egyptian restaurants. Early 2010 saw the introduction of Egyptian cookies to the [[Cairo]] location. McDonald's has almost 70 locations throughout the country.\n\n===Morocco===\nThe [[McArabia]], a grilled chicken sandwich from [[Morocco]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcdonaldsarabia.com/oman/en/product_nutrition_details.A%20la%20Carte.12.html|accessdate=1 August 2012|title=McArabia Chicken|publisher=McDonald's}}</ref> In 2005, a product called the McSahara was briefly sold. In late 2006, the Chicken Mythic, ''Petit Plaisirs'' (\"small pleasures,\" a sandwich usually made from chicken or beef), and a 280-gram Recette Moutarde (\"mustard burger\") were released. During the [[Islam]]ic holy month of [[Ramadan]], a special menu is offered for the breaking of the fast, including local specialties such as dates, milk, and [[harira]].\n\n==Asia==\n<!---please do not again take out countries for a region called \"Middle East\". It is NOT a continent and erodes the spatial integrity of both Africa and Asia. Inserting it between the continents is POV and OR.--->\n\n===Bahrain===\nAs in all McDonald's locations in the Islamic Middle East, food in Bahraini locations is [[halal]].<ref name=halal>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcdonaldsarabia.com/bahrain/en/the_truth/see_what_we_are_made_of/halal.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130128082940/http://www.mcdonaldsarabia.com/bahrain/en/the_truth/see_what_we_are_made_of/halal.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=28 January 2013|accessdate=3 August 2012|publisher=McDonaldsArabia|title=McDonald's commitment to halal}}</ref> In addition to the McArabia, Bahraini locations offer, beginning in March 2009, the McCrispy, a meal consisting of up to four chicken fingers with a choice of barbecue, ketchup, sweet and sour, or garlic sauce.\n\n=== China ===\n[[File:McDonald's Chinese New Year set meal.jpg|thumb|150px|McDonald's [[Chinese New Year]] meal, grilled chicken sandwich and twisted French fries. Tray liner has an image of the [[Chinese zodiac]].]]\nIn China, [[Chicken McNuggets]] can come with the traditional barbecue, sweet and sour, honey and hot mustard sauces; or even a special chili garlic sauce, which is popular in China. Chinese menus also include crispy spicy chicken wings, called McWings. All chicken burgers offered in Chinese McDonald's use thigh fillet (e.g., Premium Grilled Thigh Fillet Burger, Hot and Spicy Grilled Thigh Fillet Burger), rather than breast meat, which is preferred in [[Western world|western countries]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2012-05-29/news/31890938_1_mcdonalds-hong-kong-china|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=29 May 2012|title=McDonald's in China serves 'Prosperity Burger'|first=Afp|last=Relaxnews}}</ref>\n\nUnique ice cream flavors such as Matcha Green Tea ice cream is available.\nPies come in two standard flavors: pineapple or taro, although special flavors including chocolate, apple, banana, and azuki bean have also been offered on a limited basis.\n\nThere is a seasonal [[Chinese New Year]] meal available, including the Grilled Chicken Burger and curly fries, with a [[horoscope]] of the twelve zodiac animals of [[Chinese astrology]] and traditional [[red envelope]]s.\n\n====Hong Kong====\nHong Kong hosts some of the world's busiest McDonald's with many operating 24 hours a day. Breakfasts include pasta soups with sausage or chicken.<ref>{{cite web|author=SirJman |url=http://www.travellingmcds.com/2011/10/twisty-pasta-breakfast-hong-kong.html |title=McDonald's Around the World: Twisty Pasta Breakfast \u2013 Hong Kong \u2013 Various Dates |publisher=Travellingmcds.com |date=2011-10-27 |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> Locations offer cups of corn as substitutes for French fries or \u00e0 la carte. Desserts include soft serve ice cream in azuki bean and mung bean flavors; pineapple or red bean sundaes are sometimes offered.\n\nA selection of seasonal or other limited-time foods is available, such as spicy French fries, the Shogun Burger (a [[teriyaki]] pork patty with lettuce served on a sesame seed bun), salads, soups such as tomato and pumpkin,<ref>{{cite web|author=SirJman |url=http://www.travellingmcds.com/2012/02/pumpkin-soup-hong-kong-february-2012.html |title=McDonald's Around the World: Pumpkin Soup \u2013 Hong Kong \u2013 February 2012 |publisher=Travellingmcds.com |date=2012-02-15 |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> taco flatbreads, the Rice Fantastic (a burger-like entree with rice patties instead of buns). Other such specialties have included shrimp burgers, [[Wasabi]] Filet O' Fish, onion rings,<ref>{{cite web|author=SirJman |url=http://www.travellingmcds.com/2012/04/onion-rings-hong-kong-april-2012.html |title=McDonald's Around the World: Onion Rings \u2013 Hong Kong \u2013 April 2012 |publisher=Travellingmcds.com |date=2012-04-12 |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> and Shake Shake fries, flavored French fries in flavors such as seaweed, chargrill, French onion, and salt and pepper. During the local [[Cheung Chau Bun Festival|Bun Festival]], restaurants on the island of [[Cheung Chau]] sell mushroom burgers instead of hamburgers and other meat products.\n\nToys,<ref name=\"happymeal\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mcdonalds.com.hk/en/food/meals-and-value-explorer-view/happy-meals-explorer-view.html|title=Happy Meal}}</ref> gifts, and other non-food promotional items are offered from time to time.\n\n===India===\n[[File:McDonald's meal in India.jpg|thumb|McSpicy Chicken, [[McChicken]], Pizza McPuff, [[Chicken McNuggets]] and French fries sold by McDonald's in India.]]\nIndian McDonald's serve the Chicken Maharaja Mac, a grilled chicken double patty with habanero sauce<ref name=\"McDonald's Chicken Maharaja Mac - McDonald's India\">{{cite web | url=http://www.mcdonaldsindia.net/burgers/chicken-maharaja-mac.aspx | title=McDonald's Chicken Maharaja Mac \u2013 McDonald's India | publisher=McDonaldsIndia.net | accessdate=3 August 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170327143332/http://www.mcdonaldsindia.net/burgers/chicken-maharaja-mac.aspx | archive-date=27 March 2017 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref> and Veg Maharaja Mac, cheese and corn double patty with cocktail sauce.<ref name=\"McDonald's Veg Maharaja Mac - McDonald's India\">{{cite web | url=http://www.mcdonaldsindia.net/burgers/veg-maharaja-mac.aspx | title=McDonald's Veg Maharaja Mac \u2013 McDonald's India | publisher=McDonaldsIndia.net | accessdate=3 August 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807233156/http://www.mcdonaldsindia.net/burgers/veg-maharaja-mac.aspx | archive-date=7 August 2016 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Apart from these, the McSpicy burgers/wraps, McGrill and Pizza McPuff are sold in India. Mc Aloo Tikki, Mc Veggie, Mc Chicken, Mc Egg, Filet-o-fish burger, chicken wraps, veg wraps, chicken kebab burger are very popular in India. The latest addition in India being rice bowls, biriyani and naan wraps.\n\nPast promotional items have included the McPaneer and Grilled Chicken Royale,<ref name=\"McDonald's launches Royale Range premium burgers - Times of India\">{{cite web | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/McDonalds-launches-Royale-Range-premium-burgers/articleshow/33787842.cms | title=McDonald's launches Royale Range premium burgers \u2013 Times of India | publisher=TNN | date=15 April 2014 | accessdate=3 August 2016 | author=Sushma U N}}</ref> Mexican Spice Chicken and Veg, Asian Hot Garlic Dip and African Peri Peri Shake Shake (as part of the Spice Fest)<ref name=\"Spice route\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/spice-route/article3358356.ece | title=Spice route | newspaper=The Hindu | date=27 April 2012 | accessdate=3 August 2016}}</ref> Indi-McSpicy and the McCurry Pan.\n\nMcDonald's in India do not serve beef products, in deference to [[Hindu]] beliefs. McDonald's in India does not sell pork products, in deference to [[Islam]] beliefs.\nVegetarian and meat based meals are prepared in separate areas of the restaurant due to religious laws; cooks preparing vegetarian dishes wear a distinctive green apron and non vegetarian cooks wear a red apron.<ref>{{cite news|author=Mary Vanac |url=http://www.dispatch.com/content/blogs/the-bottom-line/2012/09/mcdonalds-goes-meat-less-in-india.html |title=McDonald's is going meat-less in India |newspaper=The Columbus Dispatch |date=2012-09-04 |accessdate=2013-12-14}}</ref>\n\n===Indonesia===\n[[File:McDonald's Burger Sate Indonesia 1.jpg|thumb|McDonald's Indonesia promo; Burger Sate, McFlurry Rujak Pedas, Markisa soda tea and Fries. Limited in August only, the month of Indonesian Independence.]]\n[[File:Congee at McDonald's.jpg|thumb|[[Bubur ayam]] (chicken congee)]]\nTo accommodate [[Muslim]]-majority population, all McDonald's in [[Indonesia]] are certified [[halal]], which means they do not serve bacon or pork patties, while serving only beef, chicken, and fish.<ref>{{cite web | title  = Sertifikasi Halal | work = McDonald's Indonesia | url = http://mcdonalds.co.id/menu/kualitas-produk/sertifikasi-halal}}</ref> Local items include crispy and spicy [[fried chicken]]; the McRice, a small mound of [[steamed rice]] wrapped in paper and available to supersize; McSoup, a chicken flavored soup with bits of croutons and vegetables; and ''Buryam'' (short for ''[[bubur ayam]]'' or chicken [[congee]]), later renamed as ''Bubur Ayam Spesial'' with the addition of [[fried egg]] topping.<ref>{{cite web | title = Bubur Ayam Spesial | work = McDonad's Indonesia | url = http://www.mcdonalds.co.id/menu/item/55?ref=19}}</ref> ''[[Sambal]]'' chili sauce, an essential component of [[Indonesian cuisine]], and tomato [[ketchup]] are available as condiments.\n\nMcDonald's fried chicken, McRice, and fruit tea are sold together as PaNas (''paket nasi'' or \"rice package\") with an additional sachet of ''sambal'' chili sauce.<ref>{{cite web | title  = PaNas1 | work = McDonald's Indonesia | url = http://www.mcdonalds.co.id/menu/item/64?ref=11}}</ref> This adopts the Indonesians' way of consuming ''[[ayam goreng]]'' (fried chicken) with steamed rice and ''sambal''.\n\nOther than fried chicken with rice and ''bubur ayam'' chicken rice congee, locals' preference of [[rice]]-based food is accommodated further by the introduction of Chicken with Spicy Tomato and Chicken Teriyaki,<ref>{{cite web | title = Chicken with Spicy Tomato & Chicken Teriyaki | work = McDonad's Indonesia | url = http://www.mcdonalds.co.id/promo/75?ref=85}}</ref> which is a bowl of steamed rice topped with strips of fried chicken patty with sauces and vegetables, similar to the Japanese [[donburi]] (rice bowl) fashion of serving.\n\nMcDonald's in Indonesia also promotes some seasonal foods, sold only within a limited certain period of time. Those limited periods include Chinese New Year, Ramadhan, and Independence Day specials.\n\nDuring [[Chinese New Year]], a Beef Prosperity Burger, consisting of two beef patties covered in black pepper sauce and topped with diced onions, is sold.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ta-chan |url=http://jakartalovestory.blogspot.ca/2012/01/mcdonalds-prosperity-burger.html |title=Jakarta Love Story: McDonald's Prosperity Burger |publisher=Jakartalovestory.blogspot.ca |date=2012-01-15 |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[Ramadhan]], McDonald's Indonesia has offered BBQ Beef Flatbread (2014), Curry Beef Delight (2015), [[Moroccan cuisine|Moroccan]] Burger (2016), Ayam Kremes (2017 and 2018, with addition of Nasi Uduk), and Ayam Serundeng Sambal Terasi (2019).<ref>{{cite web | title  = Ayam Kremes | work = McDonald's Indonesia | url = http://mcdonalds.co.id/promo/175?ref=85}}</ref>\n\nIn certain periods, such as August (the month of [[Proclamation of Indonesian Independence|Indonesian independence]]), McDonald's Indonesia launched local-inspired dishes such as the [[Satay|Burger Sate]], a hamburger with [[Peanut sauce|satay sauce]] (spicy ground peanut sauce), with Teh Soda Markisa (passion fruit tea soda);<ref>{{cite web | title  = Ini Rasa Kita: Burger Sate | work = McDonald's Indonesia | url = http://www.mcdonalds.co.id/promo/99?ref=85}}</ref> Local-inspired dessert include [[McFlurry]] with ''markisa'' (passion fruit) and ''rujak pedas'' (spicy mango [[rojak|rujak]]) flavour.<ref>{{cite web | title = Ini Rasa Kita: McFlurry Markisa & Rujak Pedas | work = McDonald's Indonesia | url = http://www.mcdonalds.co.id/promo/101?ref=85}}</ref>\n\n===Israel===\n[[File:Kosher McDonalds.JPG|thumb|left|[[Kashrut|Kosher]] McDonald's]]\n{{Main|McDonald's Israel}}\nThe only entirely [[Kashrut|kosher]] McDonald's are in [[Israel]] and [[Argentina]]. In these locations, patties are barbecued on [[charcoal]] rather than [[frying|fried]].<ref name=\"frommers.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.frommers.com/destinations/buenosaires/D55904.html|title=Kosher McDonald's Restaurant Review | location=Buenos Aires | work=Frommers.com<!-- Bot generated title -->}}</ref> Some kosher locations serve milk based desserts, but in separate booths, allowing for full separation of dairy and meat products in food preparation areas. However, most of the McDonald's outlets in Israel are not kosher service, as they serve cheeseburgers, which mix dairy and meat products.\n\nSpecialty items in Israeli McDonald's include the [[Shawarma|McShawarma]] and [[Kebab|McKebab]], both served on flatbread. On January 18, 2011, McDonald's introduced the McFalafel sandwich in Israel, but withdrew the item six months later.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/jul/12/mcdonalds-withdraws-mcfalafel-israeli-restaurants | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Harriet | last=Sherwood | title=McDonald's withdraws McFalafel from Israeli restaurants | date=12 July 2011}}</ref> Within the last few years they have added a vegetarian option, corn sticks (which are bite sized corn shniztels).\n\n===Japan===\n[[File:Idaho Burger - McDonald's jpn.JPG|thumb|Idaho burgers include bacon, beef, onion, cheese and pepper sauce.]]\nRegular menu items in Japanese McDonald's include: the Teriyaki McBurger, with ground pork patties, mayonnaise, lettuce, and teriyaki sauce; Shaka Shaka Chicken, a fried chicken strip served in a paper pouch, with cheese or pepper seasonings to shake in the bag; and the Fillet-O-Ebi (shrimp), with a fried shrimp patty and mustard. Breakfast options include a hot dog with pickle relish, ketchup, and mustard, then for lunch and dinner they serve the Chilli McHotdog with egg and chilli sauce. As well as regular soft drinks (which in Japan include grape flavoured Fanta and iced tea), McDonald's in Japan also serve cartons of milk, Minute Maid orange juice and \"Yassai Seikatsu\", a type of vegetable juice.\n\nSeasonal and limited-time items have included:\n* The Chicken Katsu Burger, a breaded chicken sandwich flavored with soy sauce and ginger.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.japantoday.com/category/new-products/view/cheese-katsu-burger|newspaper=Japan Today|title=Cheese Katsu Burger|date=30 March 2009}}</ref>\n* The Gratin [[Korokke]] Burger, a sandwich with korokke (breaded mashed potatoes) filled with shrimp, macaroni, shredded cabbage, and katsu{{clarify|date=May 2012}} sauce, and optional cheese; served during winter\n*[[File:In Japan, McDonald's (3194818934).jpg|thumb|McDonald counter in Japan]]Green tea-flavored milkshakes\n* The Salsa Burger, a breaded chicken sandwich with salsa\n* The Tamago Double Mac, a hamburger with three beef patties, pepper sauce, bacon, a poached egg, and optional cheese\n* The Teri Tama Burger, a teriyaki burger with egg; served during spring\n* The Tamago Double Mac, a burger with egg, two beef patties, and bacon\n* The [[Tsukimi]] Burger (\"moon-viewing burger\"), a hamburger with one beef patty, fry sauce, bacon, a poached egg (representing the Moon), and optional cheese; served before and during Tsukimi season\n* The Gurakoro Burger, a burger with a croquette patty, lettuce, and sauce, sold during the holiday months\n* Ume Nuggets, Chicken McNuggets with sour ''ume'' (plum) sauce for dipping\n* The Mega Teriyaki, a teriyaki-style Big Mac variant with two pork patties and teriyaki sauce\n* \"Quarter Pounder Jewelry\" burgers : The 'Gold Ring' available on July 6, 2012, the 'Black Diamond' on July 13, 2013 and 'Ruby Spark' on July 20, 2013 only<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsonjapan.com/html/newsdesk/article/103439.php|title=McDonald's Japan to offer 1,000-yen premium burgers|work=newsonjapan.com|accessdate=7 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303220033/http://newsonjapan.com/html/newsdesk/article/103439.php|archive-date=3 March 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2013/07/03/business/mcdonalds-to-offer-1000-burgers|title=McDonald's to offer \u00a51,000 burgers \u2013 The Japan Times|work=The Japan Times|accessdate=7 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn United States military establishments in Japan (like the US Naval Base in Yokosuka), both American and Japanese menus are sold, depending on availability.\n\nJapan has made \"American burgers\". The burgers in Japan are based on imaginations and symbolisms of burgers from different regions of the U.S. Such as Idaho burgers.\n\n===Malaysia===\n[[File:McDonald's Shah Alam.jpg|thumb|McDonald's counter in [[Shah Alam]], Malaysia. In August 2019, the chain also temporary adopted the local pronunciation of \"Mekdi\" as its alternate name, an act on celebrating its local market during the Malaysian National Day.]]\nCorrelating with most [[Muslim world|Muslim-majority markets]], all McDonald's in [[Malaysia]] adhered to the Islamic-dietary law ([[halal]]) under the supervision by the Department of Islamic Development Malaysia.<ref>{{cite web|author=Patrick Lee |url=http://www.thestar.com.my/News/Nation/2013/09/13/Our-food-is-halal-says-McDonalds.aspx |title=Our food says Halal, says McDonald's |publisher=The Star Online |date=2013-09-13 |accessdate=2013-12-14}}</ref>  Two [[Islamic law|Syarie]] experts in Malaysia also being appointed by the country to advised its food preparation.<ref>{{cite web|author=McDonalds Malaysia |url=https://www.mcdonalds.com.my/others/halal_leaflet.pdf|title=Our food says Halal, says McDonald's |publisher=McDonalds Malaysia|date=2018 |accessdate=2018-12-20}}</ref> Thus, meat is slaughtered via the halal technique, while pork and bacon are absent in its Malaysian menu.\n\nAmong the local bestseller in the Malaysian market includes the Ayam Goreng McD, originally branded as McDonald's [[Fried Chicken]], introduced in March 1986. The product's name was changed to Chicken McCrispy in 2000 and again to Ayam Goreng McD in 2002 to complement the country's culture. There are three variants of the fried chicken: Regular, [[Pungency#In food|Spicy]] and Extra Spicy. In 2017, a very successful marketing campaign has catapulted fried chicken as one of the local Malaysian bestseller.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nThe Malaysian McDonald's first approach on embracing the local tastebuds commenced in July 2002 by the debut of Bubur Ayam McD (\"McD's Chicken Porridge\"), chicken strips in rice [[congee]] with scallions, sliced ginger, fried shallots, and diced chilies;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sixthseal.com/2005/04/mcd-chicken-porridge-bubur-ayam-mcd/|title=McD Chicken Porridge (Bubur Ayam McD)|work=sixthseal.com|accessdate=8 October 2015}}</ref> The success of Bubur Ayam McD has spread the porridge to be introduced into the regional McDonalds markets in Indonesia and Thailand. A close spin-off of the product, the Bubur Ikan McD (\"McD's Fish Porridge\") also led suit, albeit the latter was only served as a periodical offer.\n\nAmong other popular menu items distinct to the Malaysian market includes the Spicy Chicken McDeluxe, a burger with crispy marinated chicken [[thigh]], lettuce and special sauce in a [[cornmeal]] bun; the GCB (\"Grilled Chicken Burger\"), [[grilling|grilled]] chicken thigh, with iceberg lettuce and chargrilled sauce, served in a toasted sesame seed bun; Nasi Ayam McD, [[rice]] set served with traditional [[sambal]] sauce, fried chicken, cucumber slices and [[Fried egg|sunny side up]];<ref>{{cite web|author=McDonalds Malaysia |url=https://www.mcdonalds.com.my/nasimcd|title=Nasi McD Baharu|publisher=McDonalds Malaysia|date=2018 |accessdate=2018-12-20}}</ref> and iced [[Milo (drink)|Milo]] drink. Local morning favourites, such as the [[Teh Tarik]] drink and [[Youtiao|Cakoi]] fried bread are also included in the Breakfast McSavers lineup. Concurrently, some of the items that are commonly available in the international market has since being discontinued in the Malaysian outlet, including [[Big N' Tasty]] and [[Quarter Pounder]], the latter has been reintroduced following the successful McD Election campaign in June 2019.\n\n[[File:Nasi McD.jpg|thumb|Nasi McD (lit. \"McD's Rice\"), a [[Malaysia]]nized McDonald's Menu. Rice served together with Fried Chicken, spicy [[Malay people|Malay]]-styled [[sambal]] sauce with some vegetables; a [[fried egg]] is also served as an optional add-on item with the meal.]]\nSimilar to McDonalds business design worldwide, periodical and limited-time offers also generally included in the menu, specialties inspired from local, international and fusion menus have ushered the arrival of [[Nasi Lemak]] Burger, Thai Fish Burger with Green Curry Sauce, Hawaiian Deluxe Burger, Mexicana Chicken Burger, Burger ''Syok'' (A Malaysian-styled Burger), among few. Specialty desserts and drinks have included [[The Hershey Company|Hershey's]] Sundae, D24 [[Durian]] McFlurry Party, [[Cendol]] Sundae, Salted Caramel Pie, [[Coconut]] Pie, Pulut Hitam (Black [[Glutinous rice|Glutinous Rice]]) Pie, [[Bandung (drink)|Bandung]] drink and [[Pie \u00e0 la Mode]]. Some of the temporary food-items also would later occasionally returned on a periodical basis such in the case of Hot & Spicy McShaker [[Fries]], Spicy [[Chicken nugget|Nuggets]], Samurai (Japanese styled Burger), Spicy Korean Burger and Rio (Brazilian inspired Burger); while a few being absorbed to be a common Malaysian McDonald's fixture, as the case of GCB Burger, first available briefly in 2010, it later constitute as a permanent item since 2013.\n\nMcDonalds Malaysia has also introduced seasonal menus to commemorate major festivals and celebration in the [[Demographics of Malaysia|multiracial]] country. Since 1994, McDonalds Malaysia launched Prosperity Burger during the [[Chinese New Year]] festival, the menu was then adopted by its neighbours in Singapore and Indonesia. The burger come in beef and chicken varieties, with black pepper sauce, topped with fresh onions in a sesame seed bun. Additionally, between 2015\u20132018, McDonalds Malaysia has also included Golden Prosperity Burger in the menu, with a slice of hash brown is also added on the burger patties. The Prosperity Burger is usually served together with [[curly fries]]. While during the Muslim holy [[Islamic calendar|month]] of [[Ramadhan]] since 2015, the chain would offer the Foldover (equivalent to the [[McArabia]]) to its customers, there are two variants of the foldover: Lazeez Foldover (Lazeez, which means \"delicious\" in Arabic) chicken patties with garlic sauce; and the Mashwi Foldover (Mashwi, meaning \"food\" in standard Arabic) is grilled beef topped with hot sauce.\n\n===Pakistan===\nAll McDonald's in Pakistan are certified halal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcdonalds.com.pk/faqs |title=McDonald's \u00bb Faqs |publisher=Mcdonalds.com.pk |date= |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> Pakistani menus resemble those of Middle Eastern and South Asian locations. McArabias and Spicy Chicken Burgers are popular in Pakistan.{{citation needed|date=May 2012}} A Chicken Big Mac is also available. In addition to apple pie, McDonald's Pakistan serves choco-orange pie and blueberry custard pie, which is fried. In March 2019, McDonald's launched Bun Kebab(a local variation of Anday Wala Burger). All McDonald's Pakistan menu items with the exception of ice cream cones are also available for delivery.\n\n===Philippines===\nMost Filipinos colloquially refer to McDonald's as \"McDo\" (equivalent to \"Mickey D's\"), and the term has been adapted by McDonald's Philippines, even naming most of their products after the term. (However, the use of \"McDo\" has been discontinued by the end of 2019 and it is now referred to its full form, McDonald's, except in item names.) Menu items in McDonald's in the [[Philippines]] include McSpaghetti, Chicken McDo, Burger McDo and Crispy Chicken Sandwich, in order to compete with the country's largest fast food retail [[Jollibee]]. From 2001 to 2006 the McRice, steamed rice formed into buns, was available as a replacement for bread buns on beef and chicken sandwiches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/Article.aspx?articleId=365232&publicationSubCategoryId=81 |title=A handy rice meal \u2013 The Philippine Star \u00bb Lifestyle Features \u00bb Food and Leisure |publisher=Philstar.com |date=2006-10-26 |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> Breakfast menus include [[longaniza]], a [[Philippine cuisine|Philippine]] sausage, served with rice and a fried egg, and the Hamdesal, a [[Pandesal]] bun with pineapple glaze syrup, mayonnaise, and Canadian bacon served with scrambled eggs, cheese, or both.\n\nSome pies come in pineapple and [[taro]] flavors, although the McDonald's Apple Pie is served in all locations. Only select locations serve milkshakes. Twister Fries is also served seasonally, as well as Shake Shake Fries, which are McDonald's French Fries that come in a paper bag and served with a packet of flavored powder (Barbeque, Cheesy Butter, Sour Cream, Ketchup, and Pizza flavors); customers must administer the flavoring to the bag of fries themselves, shaking the bag until the powder is evenly distributed among the fries. They are available annually.\n\nMcDonald's in the Philippines also promotes movie tie-in products seasonally, such as the Banana-Oreo McFlurry and Banana McFloat during the release of ''[[Minions (film)|Minions]]'' in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inquisitr.com/294827/mcdonalds-curly-fries-they-exist-but-probably-not-in-your-neighborhood/ |title=McDonald\u2019s Curly Fries\u2026 They Exist, But Probably Not In Your Neighborhood |publisher=Inquisitr.com |date=2012-08-07 |accessdate=2014-04-08}}</ref>\n\n===Saudi Arabia===\nAll McDonald's in [[Saudi Arabia]] are certified halal.<ref name=halal/> Saudi locations serve the Spicy McChicken, McArabia, and the Big Tasty, the latter of which is also available in some European locations.\n\n===Singapore===\nAll McDonald's in Singapore are certified halal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mcdonalds.com.sg/eatsmart_faq.html |title=Welcome &#124; McDonald's Singapore |publisher=Mcdonalds.com.sg |accessdate=2012-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130418104608/http://www.mcdonalds.com.sg/eatsmart_faq.html |archivedate=2013-04-18 }}</ref> Singaporean locations offer the McSpicy, a spicy chicken burger.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcdonalds.com.sg/eatsmart_menu_mcspicy.html |title=Welcome &#124; McDonald's Singapore |publisher=Mcdonalds.com.sg |accessdate=2012-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120927085810/http://www.mcdonalds.com.sg/eatsmart_menu_mcspicy.html |archivedate=2012-09-27 }}</ref> A 24-hour McDelivery service is available in all locations on [[Pulau Ujong|the island]].\n\nThe curry sauce is a dip unique to Singapore and is the favourite complementary dip to Chicken McNuggets.\n\nIn 2011, due to congestion at the United States' West Coast ports, the popular chicken nugget dip was unavailable for a period of time,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Yeo|first1=Miranda|title=McDonald's curry sauce returns today|url=http://news.asiaone.com/news/soshiok/mcdonalds-curry-sauce-returns-today|accessdate=3 August 2016|publisher=asiaone|date=18 June 2015}}</ref> causing a public outcry. A similar crisis happened in 2015.\n\nIn July 2016, McDonald's launched a limited edition take-home bottle of the curry sauce (375ml), which was limited to four purchases per single receipt.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.todayonline.com/lifestyle/mcdonalds-curry-sauce-available-limited-edition-take-home-bottle-july-21|title=McDonald\u2019s Curry Sauce available in limited edition take-home bottle from July 21|publisher=TODAY|date=15 July 2016}}</ref> The product was overwhelmingly popular and several outlets ran out of stock on the item extremely quickly.\n\nMcDonald's has also introduced several special additions to the Singapore menu, such as the Salted Egg York Chicken Burger in 2016, coupled with salt & pepper shaker fries and Gula Melaka McFlurry.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/mcdonald-s-singapore/2915700.html|title=McDonald's Singapore launches menu inspired by local flavours|publisher=ChannelNewsAsia|date=29 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nMcDonald's also introduced new and upgraded products related to Singapore's National Day and public holidays (e.g. Lunar New Year, SG50).\n\n===South Korea===\n[[File:Bulgogi burger.jpg|thumb|McDonald's Bulgogi burger in South Korea]]\nMcDonald's locations in South Korea serve a shrimp burger as well as a Bulgogi Burger, a pork patty in [[bulgogi]] marinade. The bulgogi-flavored sauce was developed by [[Ottogi]], a large South Korean food manufacturer that provides all of the condiments to the country's McDonald's.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2902414 |title=Can tteokbokki rescue rice industry? |date=2009-03-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405232757/http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2902414 |archivedate=2012-04-05 }}</ref> A 24-hour [[McDelivery]] service was launched in 2007 and now is available across South Korea.<ref>{{cite web|title = 16 McDonald\u2019s Vehicles We Doubt You\u2019ve Ever Seen|url = http://www.lifedaily.com/story/16-mcdonalds-vehicles-we-doubt-youve-ever-seen/10/|website = lifedaily|accessdate = 15 February 2017|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170216054413/http://www.lifedaily.com/story/16-mcdonalds-vehicles-we-doubt-youve-ever-seen/10/|archive-date = 2017-02-16|url-status = dead}}</ref>  McDelivery also has an app available on both Google Play and the Apple Store.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.mwos2.mcdelivery |title=(\uacf5\uc2dd) \ub9e5\ub3c4\ub0a0\ub4dc \ub9e5\ub51c\ub9ac\ubc84\ub9ac \ubc30\ub2ec|publisher=Google Play |accessdate=15 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/mcdelivery-korea/id1027699629 |title=McDelivery Korea|publisher=Apple Store |accessdate=15 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nDessert options include [[affogato]]. Former options included a green tea [[McFlurry]]<ref>{{cite web|author=SirJman |url=http://www.travellingmcds.com/2011/12/green-tea-mcflurry-seoul-korea-january.html |title=McDonald's Around the World: Green Tea McFlurry \u2013 Seoul, South Korea \u2013 January 2009 |publisher=Travellingmcds.com |date=2011-12-07 |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref>  and the McBingsu, a seasonal option similar to [[patbingsu]].\n\n===Taiwan===\nMcDonald's in Taiwan serve ''kao fan'' (\u70e4\u98ef, ''k\u01ceo f\u00e0n'') (literally \"baked rice\"), a burger-like entr\u00e9e with rice patties instead of buns.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/food/article-1126655/The-hotlist-10-unusual-items-McDonalds-menus-world.html | location=London | work=Daily Mail | title=The hotlist: 10 unusual items on McDonald's menus around the world}}</ref> It is modelled on the eponymous product of McDonald's Japanese rival, [[MOS Burger]]. McDonald's locations in Taiwan sell fried chicken legs to compete with [[KFC]]. Additionally, [[corn soup]] is available as a substitute for French fries or \u00e0 la carte.\n\n===Thailand===\n[[File:McDonalds Meal.JPG|thumb|right|[[McChicken]], Filet-O-Fish, Chicken McNuggets, French fries and fried chicken sold by McDonald's in [[Bangkok]].]]\n\nIn [[Thailand]], McDonald's serves the [[Samurai]] Pork Burger, with teriyaki sauce, lettuce, and mayonnaise.<ref>{{cite web|author=JetSetCD |url=http://www.jaunted.com/story/2011/10/17/221250/07/travel/Munching+McDonald%27s+Exotic+%27Samurai+Pork+Burger%27+in+Phuket |title=Munching McDonald's Exotic 'Samurai Pork Burger' in Phuket |publisher=Jaunted |date= |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> As in other Asian markets, Thai McDonald's sell fried chicken and spicy chicken wings. Chilli sauce is available as a condiment, along with [[ketchup]]. Other Thailand-specific items include rice patties made with [[jasmine rice]], the [[Caribbean cuisine|Caribbean]] Shrimp Burger, and a salad shaker based on ''som tam'' [[Carica papaya|papaya]] salad. McDonald's restaurants in Thailand also serve the Mega animals  Mac (known as the Double Big Mac) all year long.\n\nBetween October 1 and 13, 2013, or until supplies ran out, McDonald's offered a \"McVeggie\" burger to coincide with the tradition of many people of Chinese descent only eating vegetarian food during the annual \"[[Nine Emperor Gods Festival|Kin J]]\" period. The McVeggie is an all vegetable fried patty consisting of potatoes, beets, peas and carrot topped with lettuce and teriyaki sauce.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=10151874944932866&set=a.100032547865.89349.100023357865&type=1&theater|title=McDonald's \u2013 New Promotion October 2013 \u2013 Facebook|work=facebook.com|accessdate=8 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Turkey===\nAll McDonald's meat in [[Turkey]] are certified [[halal]] by Pinar, a Turkish company. Restaurants offer the Turkish drink [[ayran]] and the McTurco, a type of [[kebab]] with chicken or beef.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.travellingmcds.com/2012/09/mcturko-istanbul-turkey-august-2012.html|title=McDonald's Around the World: McTurko \u2013 Istanbul, Turkey \u2013 August 2012|work=travellingmcds.com|accessdate=8 October 2015}}</ref> Turkish locations also serve onion rings, the Mega Mac (known as the Double Big Mac) and the Kofteburger, with a spiced mincemeat patty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brandeating.com/2010/04/whats-on-menu-mcdonalds-turkey.html |title=What's on Menu: McDonald's Turkey |publisher=Brand Eating |date=2010-04-18 |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref>\n\n===United Arab Emirates===\nIn the United Arab Emirates, as of 2016, McDonald's standard ''a-la-carte'' menu include the hamburger (marketed as \"beefburger\"), cheeseburger, double cheeseburger, chicken burger, veggie burger, [[Quarter Pounder|Quarter Pounder with Cheese]], [[Big Mac]], Mega Mac, [[Big N' Tasty|Big Tasty]], McRoyale, [[McChicken]], Spicy McChicken, Chicken Mac, Chicken Mega Mac, [[Grand Chicken]] (Classic, Deluxe, Special, and Spicy variants), [[McArabia|McArabia Chicken]], [[Chicken McNuggets]], and [[Filet-O-Fish]] sandwiches. In some outlets, the Indian-inspired Mc [[Aloo tikki|Aloo Tikki]] burger is also served as part of the McSavers and [[Happy Meal]] lines.\n\nThe McArabia initially was available as both a chicken and beef [[kofta]] variants, but only the chicken remained as standard, although the kofta and [[sujuk]] variants are sometimes reintroduced in limited promotional runs. Other limited edition sandwiches included The Asian, The Mexican, The French, and The Turkish. The standard menu formerly carried other McDonald's staples such as the Chicken Fillet, the Spicy Chicken Fillet, and the McWings.\n\nMcDonald's in the U.A.E. is a certified halal chain.<ref name=halal/>\n\n===Vietnam===\nVietnam serves broken rice also known as C\u01a1m t\u1ea5m, named simply as c\u01a1m. The dish consists of [[broken rice]], grilled pork and various other sides that come at an extra price. \nB\u00e1nh m\u00ec(General term for bread) is also served and looks very similar to a [[Subway sandwich]].\nThey also sell fried chicken, besides grilled pork.\n\n==Europe==\n===Belgium===\nBelgian McDonald's serve the Croque McDo, consisting of two slices of [[Emmental (cheese)|Emmental cheese]] and a slice of ham toasted between two hamburger buns. This is a variation of the traditional [[croque-monsieur]] sandwich found in France and Belgium.<ref name=nile>{{cite web|url=http://www.nileguide.com/blog/2010/06/09/strange-mcdonalds-menu-items-around-the-world/|accessdate=3 August 2012|publisher=NileGuide|title=Strange McDonald's Menu Items around the world|author=Resnik, Alex|date=9 June 2010}}</ref> The \"Belgo\" burger is a hamburger with bacon, Belgian [[Maredsous Abbey#Maredsous cheese|Maredsous cheese]], roasted onions, and [[cocktail sauce]].\n\nSpain\n\nThe country serves a Big Chicken MAC and Also Beer at their McDonald\u2019s along with the Fish McBites\n\n===Croatia===\nThe McCountry sandwich is a regular menu item in Croatian McDonald's restaurants, consisting of two pork sausage patties on a bun with cheese, lettuce, tomato, onion, and a special sauce. Another regular menu item is the McToast, a ham and cheese sandwich on toast. The Maestro Burger can also be found which is normally seen in the Netherlands. Seasonal and promotional offers include [[Greek cuisine|Greek]] and Italian offerings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcdonalds.hr/ponuda/mccountry/ |title=Mcdonalds |publisher=Mcdonalds |date= |accessdate=2015-09-02}}</ref>\n\n===Cyprus===\nMcDonald's in [[Cyprus]] sells the Greek Mac, a Big Mac variant with pita bread and [[tzatziki]] sauce, and the Greek Chicken, a Greek Mac with chicken patties instead of beef.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mcdonalds.com.cy/Menu.html |title=Mcdonalds |publisher=Mcdonalds |accessdate=2012-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120427042501/http://www.mcdonalds.com.cy/Menu.html |archivedate=2012-04-27 }}</ref> A shrimp burger is also sold during the period of [[Great Lent|Lent]] when [[Church of Cyprus|Orthodox Christians]] don't eat meat. This only applies to the Republic of Cyprus, and not the northern [[Northern Cyprus|Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus]], where due to the lack of international recognition, McDonald's does not exist.\n\n===Czech Republic===\nThe McCountry sandwich served in Croatia is also available in the [[Czech Republic]].\n\nIn 2012, McDonald's added McSma\u017e\u00e1k, a variation on [[sma\u017een\u00fd s\u00fdr]], a type of [[cheese sandwich]].<ref>{{cite web|author=LetsEat |url=http://letseatcyprus.blogspot.ca/ |title=LetsEat.Com.Cy |publisher=Letseatcyprus.blogspot.ca |date=2012-06-05 |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> It is similar to the Slovak McSyr.\n\nIn 2019, McDonald's removed [[Big N' Tasty|Big Tasty]] sandwich from its menu.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcdonalds.cz/ochutnej/denni-menu/|title=Denn\u00ed menu|date=2016-02-29|website=McDonald's CZ|language=cs-CZ|access-date=2019-05-22}}</ref> It was brought back in June 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcdonalds.cz/novinky/neodolatelna-chut-big-tasty/|title=Denn\u00ed menu|date=2019-06-17|website=McDonald's CZ|language=cs-CZ|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref>\n\n===Denmark===\nOne item sold in McDonald's restaurants in Denmark, that tries to imitate classic Danish food is the Pommes Frites Sauce that somewhat resemble [[remoulade]]. This also for a long period from the opening of the first restaurant replaced mayonnaise dip and where the only condiment available besides [[ketchup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcdonalds.com/dk/da-dk/product/pommes-frites-dip.html|title=McDonald's Denmark - Pommes Frites Dip|work=mcdonalds.com|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Denmark]], every McDonald's serves a small size chicken burger called \"Chicken Salsa Cheese\". Also following its other Scandinavian cousins, Danish McDonald's serve a Daim McFlurry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.travellingmcds.com/2012/09/daim-mcflurry-copenhagen-denmark-august.html|title=McDonald's Around the World: Daim McFlurry \u2013 Copenhagen, Denmark \u2013 August 2012|work=travellingmcds.com|accessdate=8 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn Denmark you can buy chilli cheese tops, which is also served in other Nordic countries like Sweden and Norway.\n\n===Finland===\nIn [[Finland]], most McDonald's hamburgers can be ordered with a [[Rye bread|rye]] bun, based on the success of the promotional \"McRuis\" (McRye) burger.<ref>{{cite web|author=Published: May 17, 1999 |url=http://adage.com/article/news/mcdonald-s-patent-rye-bread-burger/13813/ |title=McDonald's tries to patent rye bread burger &#124; News \u2013 Advertising Age |publisher=Adage.com |date=1999-05-17 |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> ''El Maco'' is a burger with salsa and [[sour cream]] sauce. The El Maco meal is served with a barbecue spice mixture and a paper bag in which the fries and the spice mixture are poured, similar to Japan's Shaka Shaka Chicken. In 2018 McDonald's released the [[Big Mac]] with bacon. Also same as in Sweden, they are offering McVegan patty for vegans in wraps, salad or as a burger. [[Macarons]] are also served as a [[McCafe]] product. In early 2018 they released [[Valio]] [[Oltermanni]] Juustonapit that is basically small cheese nuggets filled with the famous Finnish cheese.\n\n===France===\nIn France, McDonald's offers donuts for breakfast and [[Kronenbourg Brewery|Kronenbourg 1664]] beer in 25 or 33&nbsp;cl measures. The Croque McDo and various ''Petit Plaisir'' items are available, as in Belgium and Morocco, respectively.<ref name=nile/> In 2016, McDonald's launched a summer menu, called the \"American Summer\" Menu, with one burger containing crispy peppers. Also they have the 280 burger with Beef, Cheese, Tomatoes on a Cibatta Bread Bun.\n\n===Germany===\n[[Image:McDonald\u2019s-Wirtshausschild.jpg|thumb|Inn sign in an [[Altstadt]] area]]\nStandard menu items at German McDonald's include the Hamburger Royal TS, [[Caesar salad]]s, one Veggieburger called Veggie Clubhouse,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcdonalds.de/produkte/alle-produkte|title=McDonald's \u2013 Alle Produkte|publisher=mcdonalds.de|accessdate=12 August 2016|language=de}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcdonalds.de/produkte/produkt-profil?productName=veggie_clubhouse|title=McDonald's veggie clubhouse at the German McDonald's homepage |publisher=Mcdonalds.de |date= |accessdate=2016-02-08}}</ref> and Caesar, [[honey mustard]], and [[Ranch dressing|Ranch]] chicken wraps.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcdonalds.de/produkte/alle-produkte |title=Permanent German Menu |publisher=Mcdonalds.de |date= |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> The [[McRib]] sandwich, a seasonal item in most countries, is a permanent menu item in Germany.<ref>{{cite news |last=Feder |first=Barnaby J. |title=A McDonald's Burger of the Garden Variety |date=December 9, 1992 |newspaper=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/12/09/business/a-mcdonald-s-burger-of-the-garden-variety.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219143213/http://www.nytimes.com/1992/12/09/business/a-mcdonald-s-burger-of-the-garden-variety.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm |archivedate=December 19, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=McRib product information at mcdonalds.de |url=http://www.mcdonalds.de/produkte/produkt-profil?productName=mcrib|accessdate=24 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nAs of Mid-February 2013 (valentines day), McDonald's Germany started selling the Mc[[Currywurst]] with [[bread roll]] or Fries, a hot sausage with tangy tomato sauce and [[Curry]] powder in mild and spicy.<ref>{{cite web|title=McCurrywurst product information at mcdonalds.de |url=http://www.mcdonalds.de/produkte/produkt-profil?productName=mccurrywurst|accessdate=17 February 2013}}</ref> The item is no longer sold (September 2016). There is currently a special event where they are selling the McCurrywurst again with a new name: McCurrywurst Chicken. This time it is made out of chicken and there are 3 Monopoly-Stickers on the box. The event started on November the 14th and will end on the 24th of November.<ref>{{cite web|title=McCurrywurst Product information at mcdonalds.com/de|url=https://www.mcdonalds.com/de/de-de/product/mccurrywurst-mit-chicken-6212.html|accessdate=14 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe German McDonald's Breakfast does provide Br\u00f6tchen, a crispy bread roll; McCroissant, a [[Croissant]] stuffed with [[Ham]] and Cheese; [[Scrambled Eggs]] with [[Bacon]] and \"Classic Breakfast\", a choice of bread rolls with sweet spreads resembling a very common German breakfast choice.<ref>{{cite web|title=Breakfast product information at mcdonalds.de |url=http://www.mcdonalds.de/produkte/fruehstueck|accessdate=17 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nBeer is no longer sold at all locations. It is still served in older outlets owned by German brewers with leases allowing the serving of beer.<ref>\"Behind the Arches\" by John Love, page 433-434</ref>\n\n===Greece===\nMcDonald's in [[Greece]] currently sells the Greek Mac, a Big Mac variant on [[pita]] bread with [[tzatziki]] sauce.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://surveyforcustomers.com/www-mcdvoice-com/ |title=Mcdonalds McDVoice Survey |publisher=Mcdonalds |date= |accessdate=2018-09-07 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150712203102/http://mcdonalds.gr/en/products/ta-burger-mas/greek-mac |archivedate=2015-07-12 |df= }}</ref> Other regular menus include the McToast,<ref name=\"Mcdonalds\">{{cite web |url=http://mcdonalds.gr/el/products/finger-food/veggie-snackers |title=Mcdonalds |publisher=Mcdonalds |date= |accessdate=2016-04-24 }}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> a ham and cheese sandwich on toast, Deluxe fries<ref name=\"Mcdonalds\"/> ([[potato wedges]]), and [[onion rings]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mcdonalds.gr/en/products/finger-food/onion-rings |title=Mcdonalds |publisher=Mcdonalds |accessdate=2016-04-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160507001122/http://mcdonalds.gr/en/products/finger-food/onion-rings |archivedate=2016-05-07 }}</ref> [[Heineken]] beer is also served in all locations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mcdonalds.gr/en/products/cold-drinks/beer |title=Mcdonalds |publisher=Mcdonalds |accessdate=2016-04-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160507002130/http://mcdonalds.gr/en/products/cold-drinks/beer |archivedate=2016-05-07 }}</ref>\n\nDuring the period of [[Great Lent|Lent]] when [[Church of Greece|Orthodox Christians]] abstain from eating meat, McDonald's also offers the McVeggie burger,<ref name=\"Mcdonalds\"/> a Shrimp Burger,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mcdonalds.gr/el/products/ta-burger-mas/shrimp-burger |title=Mcdonalds |publisher=Mcdonalds |accessdate=2016-04-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409172659/http://mcdonalds.gr/el/products/ta-burger-mas/shrimp-burger |archivedate=2016-04-09 }}</ref> a McWrap Shrimp,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mcdonalds.gr/el/products/wraps/mcwrap-shrimp |title=Mcdonalds |publisher=Mcdonalds |date= |accessdate=2016-04-24 }}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> fried veggie snackers,<ref name=\"Mcdonalds\"/> [[spring rolls]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mcdonalds.gr/el/products/finger-food/spring-rolls |title=Mcdonalds |publisher=Mcdonalds |accessdate=2016-04-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170417012147/http://mcdonalds.gr/el/products/finger-food/spring-rolls |archivedate=2017-04-17 }}</ref> and fried shrimp with dipping sauce.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mcdonalds.gr/el/products/finger-food/garides |title=Mcdonalds |publisher=Mcdonalds |accessdate=2016-04-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085233/http://mcdonalds.gr/el/products/finger-food/garides |archivedate=2017-04-24 }}</ref>\n\n===Hungary===\nHungarian McDonald's sell the McFarm, once available in Greece. Limited-time products available only in Hungary have included McDonald's version of the popular Hungarian breakfast food [[l\u00e1ngos]], and a \"Hungarian flavors\" menu.<ref>{{cite web |author=\u2014&nbsp;08/10/31 |url=http://www.chew.hu/all_hell_breaks_loose_as_mcdon/ |title=All Hell Breaks Loose as McDonalds Hungary Goes \"McMagyar\" |publisher=Chew.hu |accessdate=2012-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115013952/http://www.chew.hu/all_hell_breaks_loose_as_mcdon/ |archivedate=2013-01-15 }}</ref>\n\n===Italy===\nItalian McDonald's offers, since 2000, Crispy McBacon, composed of two beef patties, one slice of cheddar, bacon and a special sauce. In 2014 a variation with chicken has been offered in a limited way.\nIt also began offering \"McItaly\" items from 2010 to 2017 in a limited period. Products include burger with \"100 percent made-in-Italy meat\" and various typical Italian ingredients. The company advertises burgers in several European countries as using Italian beef, because Cremonini provides it also in various locations.<ref name=\"marchetti20100529\">{{cite news | url=http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/business/news/mcitaly-menu-merges-buy-local-with-fast-food-248805/?print=1 | title=McItaly menu merges 'buy local' with fast food | work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette | date=2010-05-29 | agency=GlobalPost | accessdate=May 31, 2012 | author=Marchetti, Silvia}}</ref> On May 24, 2013 McDonald's Italia in cooperation with [[Barilla Group|Barilla]] began offering for a limited period a [[pasta salad]].<ref name=Guardian52313>{{cite news|title=McDonald's joins forces with 136-year-old pasta firm in Italy Fast-food chain will sell pasta salad from Friday in attempt to Italianise menu after deal with Parma-based Barilla|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/may/23/mcdonalds-joins-forces-pasta-italy-barilla|accessdate=May 24, 2013|newspaper=The Guardian|date=May 23, 2013|author=Lizzy Davies|quote=pennette pasta with \"a balanced and skilful mix of tuna, tomatoes, peppers, capers and olives, seasoned with a pinch of oregano and salt\"}}</ref>\nMcCaf\u00e8, launched in 2005, has also been adapted to Italian taste.\nFrom May 2015 the menu included for a limited time the vegetarian burger McVeggie, offered here with no cheese.\n\nA [[Nutella]] burger called Sweety debuted in 2016.<ref>{{cite news|author=Sternitzky-Di Napoli, Daniela|url=http://www.chron.com/life/food/article/McDonald-s-introduces-new-a-burger-Nutella-10610517.php|title=http://www.chron.com/life/food/article/McDonald-s-introduces-new-a-burger-Nutella-10610517.php|newspaper=[[Houston Chronicle]]|date=2016-11-12|accessdate=2018-11-05}}</ref>\n\nSince 2018, McDonald's replaced McItaly with \"My selection\", special limited offer burgers with high quality Italian and foreign ingredients, selected by MasterChef judge [[Joe Bastianich]].\n\n===Malta===\nIn [[Malta]], McDonald's sell mozzarella sticks and chicken wings as side dishes. The Big Tasty is a variant to the Big N' Tasty while chicken nuggets come with an array of sauces, such as BBQ, sweet and sour, ketchup or mayonnaise. The McCafe was also first introduced in Malta, more specifically on its sister island Gozo, where the only McDonald's and McCafe on the island are found in the Arcadia shopping centre in the capital city of Victoria.<ref name=\"gozonews.com\">{{cite web|url=http://gozonews.com/645/mcdonald%E2%80%99s-new-mccafe-in-victoria/|title=Gozo News.Com|work=Gozo News.Com|accessdate=8 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304035919/http://gozonews.com/645/mcdonald%E2%80%99s-new-mccafe-in-victoria/|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=dead}}</ref>\nIt is also the place where the McFtira was sold, a beef or chicken burger with the addition of goat cheese and served in traditional Maltese bread.\n\n===Netherlands===\nIn the [[Netherlands]], McDonald's sells the McKroket, a deep-fried roll containing beef [[ragout]], similar to the Dutch \"kroket\" or also the much smaller \"bitterballen\" sold in virtually all snack bars.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://money.cnn.com/galleries/2008/fortune/0805/gallery.royale.fortune/3.html | work=CNN | title=Beyond 'Royale with Cheese' | date=8 May 2008 | access-date=2012-08-03 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012034813/http://money.cnn.com/galleries/2008/fortune/0805/gallery.royale.fortune/3.html | archive-date=2012-10-12 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Dutch McDonald's serve frite sauce or \"American Sauce,\" a yellow mayonnaise-like sauce not eaten in the United States with French fries. The ChickenSat\u00e9 burger was also offered, consisting of fried chicken with peanut sauce; this popular food is inspired by the Netherlands' historical connection to Indonesia. The Joppie Burger was also available using Joppie sauce, popular in the Netherlands. Since 2015, the Maestro Burger menu has been available. The Maestro Burger is a large burger with sesameseed bread, 2 Angus beef patties, onion, lettuce, bacon and mustard. The Chicken Maestro Burger, and the Maestro Burger Egg, a version of the regular burger with an added egg, have been made available since the original burger's launch. Also included in the menu is \"Boerenfriet\", which are thick, large fries, as commonly found in burgerbars, as well as regular mayonnaise. The introduction of the Maestro Burger is part of the revamp McDonald's is going through in the Netherlands since change of directors, focussing more on customers that seek higher quality burgers and that who would usually visit burgerbars. \nSpecial Dutch drinks include Fristi (a yogurt drink) and Chocomel (a chocolate milk drink).\nAlso available in the Netherlands are ''[[stroopwafel]]'' McFlurries.\n\n===Norway===\nAs in Finland, Norwegian McDonald's serve the El Maco (on a seasonal basis) and offer gluten free buns without an extra cost. They also serve a Laksewrap, deep-fried fish with salad and a mango slice in a tortilla.<ref name=nile/>\n\nAnother popular burger option available in Norway is the Chicken Salsa.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.mcdonalds.com/no/nb-no/produkt/chicken-salsa.html | title=Chicken Salsa (Norway)}}</ref> Chicken Salsa is a chicken burger with crispy lettuce, salsa sauce, sour cream and nachos.\n\nIn 2002, the [[McAfrika]] burger was introduced in [[Norway]], coinciding with major famines in Southern Africa. The name of the burger drew much negative publicity as being highly insensitive.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.delish.com/food-fun/mcdonalds-mcafrika-fast-food-flops#slide-8 | title=We're Not Lovin' It! Fast Food's Most Famous Flops | accessdate=2013-06-07 | author=Borja, Sahara}}</ref> The burger with vegetables were placed in pita bread.<ref>*{{cite web|last=McGrath|first=Jane|title=5 Failed McDonald's Menu Items: McAfrica |url=http://money.howstuffworks.com/5-failed-mcdonalds-menu-items1.htm#page=5|publisher=HowStuffWorks, Inc|accessdate=March 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Poland===\nOfferings in Polish McDonald's restaurants include: the Wie\u015bMac (\"Country Mac\"), a quarter-pound beef patty with onions, lettuce, cheese, mustard, and [[horseradish sauce]] on a sesame seed bun;<ref>{{cite web |author=David K. Israel |url=http://www.mentalfloss.com/blogs/archives/94251 |title=McDonald\u2019s Menu Items From Around The World |publisher=Mental Floss |date=2011-07-20 |accessdate=2012-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120826112323/http://www.mentalfloss.com/blogs/archives/94251 |archivedate=2012-08-26 }}</ref> the Pikantny Kurczakburger (\"Spicy Chickenburger\"), a chicken sandwich with lettuce and hot [[Mexican cuisine|Mexican]]-style sauce; McWrap \u2013 tortilla with chicken available in two versions: Classic (mayonnaise, mild-Mexican sauce, lettuce, rucola, shredded cheese, two slices of tomato and chicken patty) and Honey-Mustard (honey-mustard sauce, lettuce, shredded cheese, two slices of tomato, two strips of bacon and chicken patty). During winter period you can get Kanapka Drwala (\"The Lumberjack's Sandwich\") \u2013 a big bun with pork rinds instead of sesame, a quarter pounder, bacon, big piece of deep-fried cheese, sauce and vegetables. There is a free apple in every Happy Meal.\n\n===Portugal===\nPortuguese McDonald's offers a variety of soups, including their national dish of kale soup ([[caldo verde]]) and cream of carrot, white bean and spinach.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcdonalds.pt/ementa/categorias/sopas/|title=Sopas|work=mcdonalds.pt}}</ref>  These are offered as add-ons to Happy meals as well. There is also a McBifana and a McPrego on a ciabatta roll. The Portugal-specific mixed salad contains olives, corn, onions and tomatoes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcdonalds.pt/ementa/categorias/saladas/|title=Saladas|work=mcdonalds.pt}}</ref> In November 2016 McDonald's Portugal introduced a vegetarian burger option called McVeggie (made from [[quinoa]], bell peppers, wheat flour, wheat protein, vegetable oil, wheat bran, eggs, vegetable starch, spices, salt, onion, garlic, green peas, sugar and mixed herbs).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcdonalds.pt/campanhas/mcveggie/|title=McVeggie|work=mcdonalds.pt|access-date=2017-05-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180115124727/https://www.mcdonalds.pt/campanhas/mcveggie/|archive-date=2018-01-15|url-status=dead}}</ref> For dessert there are Portugal-specific fresh pineapple chunks, apple cinnamon sundae and a sandwich-shaped apple pie. In 2018 McDonald's released a limited-time edition of the Big Mac Bacon, essentially a Big Mac with added bacon.<ref>{{cite web |author=McDonald's |url=https://www.mcdonalds.pt/ementa/categorias/menus/ |title=McMenu |publisher=McDonald's |date=2018-08-20 |accessdate=2018-09-17}}</ref>\nBeer is available in all restaurants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcdonalds.pt/ementa/categorias/sobremesas/|title=Sobremesas|work=mcdonalds.pt}}</ref> In October of the same year, Chicken Country has been introduced as a cheap option (EuroPoupan\u00e7a) to purchase, considered as a side with any menu, like many other products.\n\nMcDonald's Portugal launched a loyalty scheme under the name ''MLovers'', in the form of an app. This scheme allows adherents to collect points on purchased products and exchange them for products and / or experiences.<ref>{{cite web |author=McDonald's |url=https://www.mcdonalds.pt/mlovers |title=McDonalds's - MLovers |publisher=McDonald's |date=2018-01-01 |accessdate=2018-12-21}}</ref>\n\n===Russia===\nIn Russia, McDonald's started selling special burgers with ingredients 100% made in the Russian Federation such as cheese, bread, tomatoes, beef, bacon, lettuce in 2015 under the \"\u0411\u0438\u0444 \u0410-\u043b\u044f \u0420\u0443\u0441 (Beef \u00e0 la Russe)\" name, designed to be an authentic Russian native hamburger.<ref>{{in lang|ru}} [http://mcdonalds.ru/new-products    /\u041c\u0430\u043a\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u0434\u0441 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043d\u043a\u0438 \u041c\u0435\u043d\u044e].  Retrieved 14 February 2015.</ref> McDonald's restaurants in Russia serve chicken wings<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mcdonalds.ru/product/chicken-wings|title=\u041a\u0443\u0440\u0438\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043a\u0440\u044b\u043b\u044b\u0448\u043a\u0438 - \u043a\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0439\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c, \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0430 \u0438 \u0434\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u043a\u0430 \u2013 \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u0434\u0441 \u0432 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438|website=mcdonalds.ru|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref> and shrimps. McZavtrak (McBreakfast) menu offers cheesecake rolls, [[blini]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mcdonalds.ru/product/pancakes|title=\u0411\u043b\u0438\u043d\u044b - \u043a\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0439\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c, \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0430 \u0438 \u0434\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u043a\u0430 \u2013 \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u0434\u0441 \u0432 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438|website=mcdonalds.ru|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref> and the oatmeal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mcdonalds.ru/product/oatmeal|title=\u041e\u0432\u0441\u044f\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043a\u0430\u0448\u0430 - \u043a\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0439\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c, \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0430 \u0438 \u0434\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u043a\u0430 \u2013 \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u0434\u0441 \u0432 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438|website=mcdonalds.ru|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref>\n\n===Serbia===\nIn Serbia, McDonald's offers the McBaguette sandwich. The sandwich is available in two varieties including chicken or ham & cheese.  The restaurants throughout the country offer [[Alcoholic beverage|alcoholic]] and [[energy drinks]]. They also offer orange juice and apple juice for the junior menus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcdonalds.rs/cenovnik/|title=Cenovnik|work=McDonald's|accessdate=8 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160109080450/http://mcdonalds.rs/cenovnik/|archive-date=9 January 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Slovakia===\nIn Slovakia, McDonald's offers the McSyr, a sandwich containing breaded fried cheese and tartar sauce which emulates the Slovak dish [[vypr\u00e1\u017ean\u00fd syr]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcdonalds.sk/sk/novinky/fajnovky.shtml|title=Novinky|work=mcdonalds.sk|accessdate=8 October 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130922161520/http://www.mcdonalds.sk/sk/novinky/fajnovky.shtml|archivedate=22 September 2013}}</ref> It is similar to the Czech McSma\u017e\u00e1k. Also, like in the United Kingdom, McDonald's restaurants in Slovakia serve donuts, which are named McDonuts. McDonuts can be served with either vanilla or chocolate frosting.\n\n===Slovenia===\nThe McCountry sandwich served in Croatia is also available in [[Slovenia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcdonalds.si/ponudba/glavne-jedi/mccountry/ |title=Mcdonalds |publisher=Mcdonalds |date= |accessdate=2015-09-02}}</ref>\n\n===Sweden===\n[[Sweden|Swedish]] McDonald's offer gluten free buns at no extra cost, and occasionally, when there is a time-limited campaign, serve the El Maco. Since 2018 McDonald's in Sweden also serve an all vegan burger called the McVegan. This burger is served with a vegan patty made out of soy, salad, tomatoes, cucumber, onions and vegan McFeast Sauce. Swedish McDonalds's also serve a garlic sauce.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://slymarketing.com/i-thought-i-hated-mcdonalds/ |title=I Thought I Hated McDonalds |publisher=Slymarketing.com |date=2010-08-14 |accessdate=2012-08-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318191652/http://slymarketing.com/i-thought-i-hated-mcdonalds |archive-date=2012-03-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== Switzerland ===\nSwiss McDonalds serve \"The Prime\" Burger, a beef burger with bacon, Gruy\u00e8re cheese and special sauces created by Swiss Chef Ren\u00e9 Schudel. With a current price of CHF 10.90 (approx. USD 12.00) for the burger alone, it is one of the most expensive McDonald's burgers worldwide.\n\n===Ukraine===\nUkraine features the [[McLavash]] sandwich on its menus in the southern part of the country, which is served in flatbread. It has two spicy beef patties, some greens, onion and tomato. The McLavash is also served in some other nearby countries.\n\n===United Kingdom and Ireland===\nBritish and Irish McDonald's serve the Chicken Legend, a chicken breast coated in seasoned batter either spicy tomato salsa, BBQ Sauce or mayonnaise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcdonalds.co.uk/content/ukhome/product_nutrition.chicken.243.chicken-legend-with-bacon-cool-mayo.html |title=Product Nutrition |publisher=McDonalds.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> In June 2011, [[Deli Choices]], a line of sandwich rolls with fillings, was released in the UK. [[Curry]] flavoured sauce is available for McNuggets in British and Irish restaurants. From 2003 to 2005, menus included the [[Quorn (food product)|Quorn]] Premiere, a vegetarian burger with sweet chilli sauce, light [[Hellmann's and Best Foods|Hellmann's]] mayonnaise, tomato, and lettuce in a [[focaccia]] bun. In 2015, McDonald's released a limited edition burger in the Republic of Ireland called the McM\u00f3r. In 2016, this burger was brought back for six weeks. It features Ballymaloe Relish, Charleville cheddar and a potato bun.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcdonalds.ie/iehome/food/full_menu/beef/mc-mor.html |title=McM\u00f3r burger |publisher=McDonalds.ie |date= |accessdate=2016-04-20}}</ref> In 2016, McDonald's launched the brand new BBQ Smokehouse Range of burgers. The two burgers that were launched contained chicken and beef with bacon, cheese and BBQ Sauce.\n\nPast promotional items have included the Apple Pie Sundae, [[Mozzarella sticks|Mozzarella Dippers]], ''Cheese Melt Dippers'', the ''Summer Chorizo Supreme'', BBQ Chicken Premiere with Bacon, the ''1955 burger'', Apple and Blackberry Pie and the ''Festive Pie'', with [[mincemeat]] and [[custard]]. A series of burgers intending to represent various American locales has been released under the ''Great Taste of America'' range. These burgers have represented New York City, Chicago, [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]], [[Texas]], [[Arizona]], Miami, California and [[New Orleans]]. Not all of these burgers resemble their respective local cuisines.<ref>{{cite news |title=McDonald's Introduces the UK to Incorrect Tastes of America |last=Wheeler |first=Robin |url=http://blogs.riverfronttimes.com/gutcheck/2011/06/mcdonalds_introduces_the_uk_to.php |newspaper=[[The Riverfront Times]] |date=6 June 2011 |accessdate=5 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120527012859/http://blogs.riverfronttimes.com/gutcheck/2011/06/mcdonalds_introduces_the_uk_to.php |archive-date=2012-05-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref> British and Irish McDonald's also released a series of burgers representing several different countries in the world. These have included Australia, South Africa, Canada and Mexico. Several Summer and Winter menus have been launched. Also, McDonald's has launched several kinds of McFlurrys over the years, such as [[Cornetto (ice cream)|Cornetto]], [[Cadbury]] brands like Dairy Milk (which is available all year around) and the [[Creme Egg]], which is only available around [[Easter]].\n\nIn 2019 McDonald's released a limited-time edition of the Big Mac called the ''Grand Big Mac Bacon'', which is essentially a larger Big Mac with added bacon.<ref>{{cite web|title=Grand Big Mac Bacon|date=2019-01-28|accessdate=2019-01-31|url=https://www.mcdonalds.com/gb/en-gb/product/grand-big-mac-bacon.html}}</ref>\n\nMcDonald's UK also offers a range of premium burgers known as the ''Signature Collection'', consisting of three burgers: ''The Classic'', ''The Spicy'' and ''The BBQ''. Each comes with a thicker patty made from higher quality beef which takes longer to cook and is served on a brioche bun.\n\n==North America==\n===Canada===\n{{Main|McDonald's Canada}}\nFrench fries may be substituted with McDonald's version of [[poutine]]. Previously, McDonald's poutine was available widely only in Francophone Canada (Quebec and parts of New Brunswick) and available elsewhere on a more limited basis; however, in December 2013, McDonald's formally announced the nationwide availability of poutine at all of its Canadian restaurants, due to popular demand.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/mcdonald-s-poutine-hitting-menus-across-canada-1.2454323 \"McDonald's poutine hitting menus across Canada\"], CBC News, 06 December 2013.</ref> Quebec also saw the release of the limited-time 1967 Burger, commemorating Canada's first McDonald's franchise. Deli Choices were introduced throughout Canada in 2006. Unique to Canadian McDonald's locations is the McMini, miniature sandwiches with grilled or crispy chicken; flavors include [[Pesto]] Chicken (later replaced by Zesty [[Mango]]) and Spicy Thai.<ref>{{cite web|author=SirJman |url=http://www.travellingmcds.com/2011/11/mcmini-thai-chilli-chicken-and-pesto.html |title=McDonald's Around the World: Chicken McMini Thai Chilli and Pesto \u2013 Lasalle, Canada \u2013 May 2010 |publisher=Travellingmcds.com |date=2011-11-05 |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> As in the United States, the McRib periodically appears on the menu for limited runs.  The crispy chicken patty used in the McChicken sandwich sold in Canada uses both white and dark meat \u2013 it is essentially the same size and taste as the original McChicken that first appeared in the US in 1980.\n\nSeasonal items previously available in McDonald's in Canada include the McLobster, a [[lobster roll]], available in the [[Maritime Provinces]], called ''McHomard'' in French.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-biz-mcdonalds-mchomard-canada,0,4348743.photo | work=Chicago Tribune | title=McHomard \u2013 Canada}}</ref> Regionally a blueberry-shortbread McFlurry is also available.  Discontinued items in Canadian McDonald's include pizzas, including a [[calzone]]-style \"McPizza.\"\nThe McFlurry Originated in New Brunswick.\n\n===Mexico===\nMexican McDonald's locations do not serve fish, except during the period of Lent. Special items at these locations have included the Flaming Hot [[Doritos]] Quarter Pounder and the BBQ Double Burger. For breakfast, Mexican McDonald's locations serve the McMollete, which is made on an English muffin spread with beans, topped with a slice of melted cheese and pico de gallo.<ref name=johnson>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/mcdonalds-caters-to-local-palettes-2011-1?op=1|accessdate=3 August 2012|title=Check out the awesome meals you can buy at McDonald's around the world|author=Johnson, Robert|date=22 January 2011|work=Business Insider}}</ref> Mexican locations also serve a version of the McSkillet burrito known as the \"McBurrito\".\n\n===United States===\nMcDonald's restaurants in the United States of America offer various types of [[shellfish]] dishes on a regional basis, such as seasonal [[lobster]] rolls in [[New England]] and [[crab cakes]] in the [[Mid-Atlantic states]]. Parts of the [[Upper Midwest]] sell [[Johnsonville Foods|Johnsonville Brats]], a toasted hot dog bun with a Johnsonville [[bratwurst]] topped with spicy mustard and onions. Other regional variations include the [[Texas]] Homestyle Burger, and traditional [[Cuisine of the Southern United States|Southern]] breakfast items, such as a [[country ham]] biscuit and [[biscuits and gravy]].  Locations in the Southwest regularly offer burgers topped with [[New Mexico chile]].\n\nHawaii locations offer [[saimin]] on their regular menu,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tastyislandhawaii.com/2010/06/26/mcdonalds-saimin/ |title=McDonald\u2019s Saimin &#124; The Tasty Island |publisher=Tastyislandhawaii.com |date=2010-06-26 |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> and include [[Spam (food)|Spam]], [[lingui\u00e7a|Portuguese sausage]] and [[rice]] as a breakfast option. Pineapple and taro pies, as regularly sold in some Asian countries, have been occasionally offered on the regular menu, along with [[haupia]] pies; pineapple is also sometimes available as a topping on burgers. In [[Waikiki]] locations, small trays of pineapple can be ordered as a side dish. Except for saimin, Hawaiian and selected Asian specialty items can also be found in McDonald's in the US territories of [[Guam]] and the [[Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands|Northern Mariana Islands]]. During Easter time, Hawaii, Guam and the CNMI all feature the Double Filet-O-Fish meal due to having a heavy concentration of Catholics (mostly people who immigrated from the Philippines) in that region.\n\n====Puerto Rico====\nUnlike Mexico, several Puerto Rican McDonald's restaurants serve fish products, although fish is not listed on McDonald's Puerto Rico's official website. Puerto Rican restaurants also serve the McCriollo (with eggs and cheese) for breakfast. Criollo is a Puerto Rican bread, like a baguette, but bigger and softer. Basically, the McCriollo is a sandwich with ham, cheese, and egg on a Criollo roll.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sandwichreviews.com/2010/06/mccriollo-puerto-rican-egg-mcmuffin.html |title=It's What's Between: McCriollo: The Puerto Rican Egg McMuffin |publisher=Sandwichreviews.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref>\n\n==Oceania==\n===Australia===\nA popular Australian McDonald's menu item is the McOz Burger. Previous products have included: Shaker Fries, similar to Japan's Shaka Shaka Chicken, and has had many variants of seasoning ranging from Cheeseburger, Big Mac and Spicy; a [[BLT]]; the Mc[[Beefsteak]], promoted by [[country music]] singer [[Lee Kernaghan]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PL3WCXJOpv4 |title=McDonalds Commercial \u2013 McBeefsteak |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> the Big [[Kahuna]] Burger, served with pineapple; the Romano Burger, a chicken patty with Italian sauce and mozzarella served on an herbed focaccia bun; the [[Tandoor]]i Burger, a chicken patty with lettuce and mint yogurt sauce served on flatbread; and a [[Chive]] [[Omelette]] Roll.\n\nCurrent products have included: Chicken Mcbites, Classic Angus and Aussie BBQ Angus.\n\nEvery so often (typically once a year) the McOz is sold for a limited time.  The McOz is a quarter-pounder burger with lettuce, tomato, cheese, mustard, ketchup and the so-called Australian ingredients of [[beetroot]] and cooked onion served on a sesame seed bun.\n\nThe El Maco burger, offered in other markets, was released for a limited time offer last on the 27th of November 2019. These burgers launch alongside Mozzarella Sticks served with El Maco Salsa and an El Maco variant Shaker Fries.\n\n===New Zealand===\n{{Main|McDonald's New Zealand}}\n[[File:McDonald's Kiwiburger.jpg|thumb|200px|Kiwiburger]]\nMany McDonald's menu items in New Zealand are similar to those in Australia. Some unique items include the [[Kiwiburger]], a beef patty with McMuffin egg, tomato, lettuce, cheese, onion, beetroot, ketchup, and mustard.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bestadsontv.com/ad/38826/McDonalds-Kiwiburger |title=TV ad: McDonald's: Kiwiburger |publisher=Bestadsontv.com |date=2011-08-19 |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> In 2011, a special \"Kiwi Menu\" was featured to promote the country's hosting of the [[2011 Rugby World Cup]].\n\nIn April 2012, McDonald's re-released the El Maco, a variant of the product of the same name offered in other markets, such as Scandinavia. El Maco had previously been sold in New Zealand in the early 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|title=McDonald's NZ (maccasnz) on Twitter|url=https://twitter.com/MaccasNZ/status/189864932047720448|publisher=McDonald's New Zealand, Twitter|accessdate=11 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, the New Zealand affiliate bought out failing local fast food chain [[Georgie Pie]], which based itself around [[meat pie (Australia and New Zealand)|Australian and New Zealand meat pies]]. McDonald's trialed a partial relaunch of the Georgie Pie brand in May 2013 with one pie flavor sold through eleven of its restaurants. In October 2013, the affiliate announced it would expand the sale of Georgie Pie to 107 of its 161 restaurants by the end of 2013.<ref name=\"NZHreturn\">{{cite news|last=Adams|first=Christopher|title=Georgie Pie now to be sold across NZ|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/business/news/article.cfm?c_id=3&objectid=11132811|accessdate=1 October 2013|newspaper=[[New Zealand Herald]]|date=1 October 2013}}</ref> As of January 2017, two pie flavors are available: Steak Mince 'n' Cheese and Bacon 'n' Egg.\n\n==South America==\n===Argentina===\nMcN\u00edfica is served. McDonald's Argentina serves Big Tasty Angus Burger, made with premium Argentinean Angus Beef.\nArgentina is the only country besides Israel in which McDonald's has full kosher locations.<ref name=\"frommers.com\"/> These are the only places in the world where McDonald's burgers are barbecued on charcoal rather than fried.<ref name=oddee>{{cite web|url=http://www.oddee.com/item_96970.aspx |title=10 of the Strangest Mc Donald's Meals \u2013 Oddee.com (mcdonalds meals) |publisher=Oddee.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref>\nCroissants are served for breakfast and afternoon tea.\n\n===Brazil===\n[[File:McVeggie in Brazil 2018 01.jpg|thumb|right|A McVeggie in Brazil]]\nIn [[Brazil]], McDonald's offers the Cheddar McMelt, a beef burger with creamy cheddar cheese and grilled onions, flavored with soy sauce on a whole-wheat bun.\n\nBanana-flavored pies are served in Brazilian McDonald's.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nasr |first=Susan L. |url=http://money.howstuffworks.com/10-items-from-mcdonalds-international-menu9.htm |title=HowStuffWorks \"10 Unusual Items from McDonald's International Menu\" |publisher=Money.howstuffworks.com |date=2009-04-13 |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref>\n\nA vegetarian burger started being available, on a trial basis, on 8 November 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mcdonald's vegetariano: McDonald\u2019s lan\u00e7a in\u00e9dito veggie burger no Brasil {{!}} EXAME |url=https://exame.abril.com.br/marketing/mcdonalds-lanca-veggie-burger-no-brasil/ |accessdate=31 October 2018 |work=exame.abril.com.br |language=pt-BR}}</ref> This followed a trial of a vegan burger in October/November 2017.<ref>{{cite news |title=McDonald\u2019s lan\u00e7a o seu primeiro hamb\u00farguer vegetariano {{!}} EXAME |url=https://exame.abril.com.br/marketing/mcdonalds-primeiro-hamburguer-vegetariano/ |date=9 October 2017 |work=exame.abril.com.br |language=pt-BR}}</ref>\n\n===Chile===\nIn Chile, cheese [[empanada]]s are sold at all McDonald's locations in Chile as side dishes. Also, customers can add [[avocado]] paste to any sandwich, other than the McPalta ([[Chilean Spanish]] for ''McAvocado''),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unitednationsoffood.com/2010/07/chilean-food-nyc/ |title=Chilean Food NYC &#124; United Nations of Food (NYC) |publisher=United Nations of Food |date= |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> whose basis is avocado paste along burger as current '''Cuarto Palta''' (''Avocado Quarter Pounder'')<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4c64uVJl05s |title=McDonald's Chile \u2013 Cuarto Palta  |publisher=YouTube |date=2013-08-16 |accessdate=2013-10-12}}</ref> and '''McWrap Palta with [[Fuze Beverage|Fuze Tea]]''', sliced fried chicken with lettuce, tomatoes and purple onion in a tortilla.\n\nCelebrating the 200-year anniversary of the founding of Chilean republic, in 2010 McDonald's offered '''Combo Bicentenario''',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chile.com/secciones/ver_seccion.php?id=122810 |title=McDonald's pone pebre a Combo Bicentenario |publisher=Chile.com |date=2010-09-04 |accessdate=2013-10-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131015084111/http://www.chile.com/secciones/ver_seccion.php?id=122810 |archivedate=2013-10-15 }}</ref> a beef burger with [[pebre]], a Chilean condiment made of coriander, chopped onion, olive oil, garlic and ground spicy chili pepper, and [[merk\u00e9n]], a smoked chili pepper. Recently, celebrating Chile's 2013 National Day in September, the fast food restaurant served [[empanadas]] de pino<ref>{{cite web|url=https://foursquare.com/stark/checkin/5227c19211d2e9590a1ee0cc?s=dSrQkEnkwdhXSqb8LGpJDTiZcdY&ref=tw |title=desde ma\u00f1ana, vas a poder pedir empanadas de pino en @mcdonalds_cl! |publisher= |date=2013-09-04 |accessdate=2013-10-12}}</ref> (stuffed with beef, olives, onions, raisins, and boiled eggs) as special side dishes.\n\nFor breakfast, McDonald's serves [[croissant]]s, also known in Chile as '''Medialuna''' and local versions of two Chilean sandwiches: '''Barros Jarpa''', whose basis is ham and molten cheese on bread, and '''Lomo Palta''',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mcdonalds.cl/sub-secciones/nutricion/include/img/imgpdf/desayuno.jpg |title=Tabla nutricional de productos McDonald's |publisher=McDonalds.cl |date=2013-05-24 |accessdate=2013-10-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014114559/http://www.mcdonalds.cl/sub-secciones/nutricion/include/img/imgpdf/desayuno.jpg |archivedate=2013-10-14 }}</ref> an avocado paste along a slice pork.\n\n===Colombia===\nColombian McDonald's restaurants serve the McCriollo breakfast combo, which includes a sausage patty, two traditional Colombian [[arepa]]s, scrambled eggs and sweetcorn, a hashbrown, coffee, butter, and [[Fruit preserves|jam]].<ref>{{cite web|author=SirJman |url=http://travellingmcds.blogspot.com/2011/11/mccriollo-breakfast-bogota-colombia.html |title=McDonald's Around the World: McCriollo Breakfast \u2013 Bogota Colombia \u2013 March 2011 |publisher=Travellingmcds.blogspot.com |date=2011-11-29 |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref>\n\n===Ecuador===\nIn [[Ecuador]], McDonald's started selling cheese empanadas, burgers with cheese sausage or guacamole, blackberry sundae and nuggets with spicy sausage in 2012 under the \"Nuestros sabores\" campaign, aimed at providing a more local cuisine.<ref>{{in lang|es}} [http://www.elemprendedor.ec/mcdonalds-empanadas-de-queso/ La cadena de comida r\u00e1pida pretende ampliar su oferta insertando un men\u00fa de \u201cgastronom\u00eda ecuatoriana\u201d]. Retrieved 1 July 2013.</ref>\n\n===Peru===\nIn Peru, McDonald's offers [[Aj\u00ed dulce|aj\u00ed]], a spicy sauce made from peppers, as a condiment.<ref name=really>{{cite web |url=http://www.ireallylikefood.com/728110091/mcdonald%E2%80%99s-around-the-world--menu-items-you-may-not-know-so-well/ |title=McDonald\u2019s Around the World: Menu Items You May Not Know So Well |publisher=ireallylikefood |date=2010-06-02 |accessdate=2012-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120701083418/http://www.ireallylikefood.com/728110091/mcdonald%E2%80%99s-around-the-world--menu-items-you-may-not-know-so-well/ |archivedate=2012-07-01 }}</ref> Peruvian locations also serve Pollo Crujiente (\"crunchy chicken\"), which is fried chicken served in a bucket, and [[Inca Kola]]. Now, McDonald's offers \"Peruvian Foods\" and blackberry Sundae.\n\n===Venezuela===\nIn Venezuela, McDonald's offers arepas, [[empanadas]] for breakfast; these are traditional breakfast foods. Venezuelan locations have also served fried [[Cassava|yuca]] sticks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m3190/is_15_39/ai_n13649042/pg_3/ |title=Studying McDonald's abroad: overseas branches merge regional preferences, corporate directives |publisher=Findarticles.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref>\n\n===Dominican Republic===\nIn DR,McDonald's sells the same food as the US and Canada. It sells hamburgers, fries, nuggets (chicken flavored), and soda.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[24 hour McDelivery|McDelivery]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n; Videos\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AT-E_eMiwgk|title=Why McDonald's Failed In Iceland|publisher=[[CNBC]]|date=2019-02-19}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l9pthhpd7So|title=Why McDonald\u2019s Flopped In Vietnam|publisher=[[CNBC]]|date=2018-09-18}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kpHeXMbIy2s|title=Why Is McDonald's Struggling In The Philippines? Jollibee|publisher=[[CNBC]]|date=2018-11-20}}\n{{McDonald's}}\n\n[[Category:Lists by country]]\n[[Category:McDonald's foods| International]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{more citations needed|date=December 2008}}\n{{original research|date=December 2008}}\n{{primary sources|date=August 2015}}\n}}\n'''McDonald's Corporation''' ({{nyse|MCD}}) is the world's largest chain of [[fast food]] restaurants, serving around 68 million customers daily in 119 countries.<ref name=daily>{{cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/McDonald-Momentum-Delivers-prnews-2702110553.html?x=0 |title=McDonald's Momentum Delivers Another Year of Strong Results for 2011 |publisher=Yahoo Finance |year=2012 |accessdate=2012-01-25 }}{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.burgerbusiness.com/?p=9168 |title=McDonald\u2019s Answers the Doubters |publisher=BurgerBusiness |date=2012-01-25}}</ref> [[McDonald's]] traces its origins to a 1940 restaurant in [[San Bernardino, California]]. After expanding within the United States, McDonald's became an international corporation in 1967, when it opened a location in [[Richmond, British Columbia|Richmond, British Columbia, Canada]]. By the end of the 1970s, McDonald's restaurants existed in five of the Earth's seven continents; an African location came in 1992 in Casablanca, Morocco.\n\nIn order to cater to local tastes and [[Cuisine|culinary traditions]], and often in respect of particular laws or religious beliefs, McDonald's offers regionalized versions of its [[McDonald's products|menu]] among and within different countries. As a result, [[List of McDonald's products|products]] found in one country or region may not be found in McDonald's restaurants in other countries.\n\n==Africa==\n===Egypt===\nIn 2001, McDonald's introduced the [[Falafel|McFalafel]] sandwich in its Egypt locations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://adage.com/article/news/mcdonald-s-mcfalafel-a-hit-egyptians/15353/|accessdate=2 August 2012|newspaper=Advertising Age|date=19 June 2001|title=McDonald's McFalafel a hit with Egyptians}}</ref> These restaurants also offer a Chicken [[Big Mac]] and Fish Mac, variations on the standard Big Mac which substitute breaded chicken or fish, respectively, for the usual beef patties. In the summer of 2008, McDonald's introduced fish fingers with tartar dipping sauce as a side in Egyptian restaurants. Early 2010 saw the introduction of Egyptian cookies to the [[Cairo]] location. McDonald's has almost 70 locations throughout the country.\n\n===Morocco===\nThe [[McArabia]], a grilled chicken sandwich from [[Morocco]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcdonaldsarabia.com/oman/en/product_nutrition_details.A%20la%20Carte.12.html|accessdate=1 August 2012|title=McArabia Chicken|publisher=McDonald's}}</ref> In 2005, a product called the McSahara was briefly sold. In late 2006, the Chicken Mythic, ''Petit Plaisirs'' (\"small pleasures,\" a sandwich usually made from chicken or beef), and a 280-gram Recette Moutarde (\"mustard burger\") were released. During the [[Islam]]ic holy month of [[Ramadan]], a special menu is offered for the breaking of the fast, including local specialties such as dates, milk, and [[harira]].\n\n==Asia==\n<!---please do not again take out countries for a region called \"Middle East\". It is NOT a continent and erodes the spatial integrity of both Africa and Asia. Inserting it between the continents is POV and OR.--->\n\n===Bahrain===\nAs in all McDonald's locations in the Islamic Middle East, food in Bahraini locations is [[halal]].<ref name=halal>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcdonaldsarabia.com/bahrain/en/the_truth/see_what_we_are_made_of/halal.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130128082940/http://www.mcdonaldsarabia.com/bahrain/en/the_truth/see_what_we_are_made_of/halal.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=28 January 2013|accessdate=3 August 2012|publisher=McDonaldsArabia|title=McDonald's commitment to halal}}</ref> In addition to the McArabia, Bahraini locations offer, beginning in March 2009, the McCrispy, a meal consisting of up to four chicken fingers with a choice of barbecue, ketchup, sweet and sour, or garlic sauce.\n\n=== China ===\n[[File:McDonald's Chinese New Year set meal.jpg|thumb|150px|McDonald's [[Chinese New Year]] meal, grilled chicken sandwich and twisted French fries. Tray liner has an image of the [[Chinese zodiac]].]]\nIn China, [[Chicken McNuggets]] can come with the traditional barbecue, sweet and sour, honey and hot mustard sauces; or even a special chili garlic sauce, which is popular in China. Chinese menus also include crispy spicy chicken wings, called McWings. All chicken burgers offered in Chinese McDonald's use thigh fillet (e.g., Premium Grilled Thigh Fillet Burger, Hot and Spicy Grilled Thigh Fillet Burger), rather than breast meat, which is preferred in [[Western world|western countries]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2012-05-29/news/31890938_1_mcdonalds-hong-kong-china|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=29 May 2012|title=McDonald's in China serves 'Prosperity Burger'|first=Afp|last=Relaxnews}}</ref>\n\nUnique ice cream flavors such as Matcha Green Tea ice cream is available.\nPies come in two standard flavors: pineapple or taro, although special flavors including chocolate, apple, banana, and azuki bean have also been offered on a limited basis.\n\nThere is a seasonal [[Chinese New Year]] meal available, including the Grilled Chicken Burger and curly fries, with a [[horoscope]] of the twelve zodiac animals of [[Chinese astrology]] and traditional [[red envelope]]s.\n\n====Hong Kong====\nHong Kong hosts some of the world's busiest McDonald's with many operating 24 hours a day. Breakfasts include pasta soups with sausage or chicken.<ref>{{cite web|author=SirJman |url=http://www.travellingmcds.com/2011/10/twisty-pasta-breakfast-hong-kong.html |title=McDonald's Around the World: Twisty Pasta Breakfast \u2013 Hong Kong \u2013 Various Dates |publisher=Travellingmcds.com |date=2011-10-27 |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> Locations offer cups of corn as substitutes for French fries or \u00e0 la carte. Desserts include soft serve ice cream in azuki bean and mung bean flavors; pineapple or red bean sundaes are sometimes offered.\n\nA selection of seasonal or other limited-time foods is available, such as spicy French fries, the Shogun Burger (a [[teriyaki]] pork patty with lettuce served on a sesame seed bun), salads, soups such as tomato and pumpkin,<ref>{{cite web|author=SirJman |url=http://www.travellingmcds.com/2012/02/pumpkin-soup-hong-kong-february-2012.html |title=McDonald's Around the World: Pumpkin Soup \u2013 Hong Kong \u2013 February 2012 |publisher=Travellingmcds.com |date=2012-02-15 |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> taco flatbreads, the Rice Fantastic (a burger-like entree with rice patties instead of buns). Other such specialties have included shrimp burgers, [[Wasabi]] Filet O' Fish, onion rings,<ref>{{cite web|author=SirJman |url=http://www.travellingmcds.com/2012/04/onion-rings-hong-kong-april-2012.html |title=McDonald's Around the World: Onion Rings \u2013 Hong Kong \u2013 April 2012 |publisher=Travellingmcds.com |date=2012-04-12 |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> and Shake Shake fries, flavored French fries in flavors such as seaweed, chargrill, French onion, and salt and pepper. During the local [[Cheung Chau Bun Festival|Bun Festival]], restaurants on the island of [[Cheung Chau]] sell mushroom burgers instead of hamburgers and other meat products.\n\nToys,<ref name=\"happymeal\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mcdonalds.com.hk/en/food/meals-and-value-explorer-view/happy-meals-explorer-view.html|title=Happy Meal}}</ref> gifts, and other non-food promotional items are offered from time to time.\n\n===India===\n[[File:McDonald's meal in India.jpg|thumb|McSpicy Chicken, [[McChicken]], Pizza McPuff, [[Chicken McNuggets]] and French fries sold by McDonald's in India.]]\nIndian McDonald's serve the Chicken Maharaja Mac, a grilled chicken double patty with habanero sauce<ref name=\"McDonald's Chicken Maharaja Mac - McDonald's India\">{{cite web | url=http://www.mcdonaldsindia.net/burgers/chicken-maharaja-mac.aspx | title=McDonald's Chicken Maharaja Mac \u2013 McDonald's India | publisher=McDonaldsIndia.net | accessdate=3 August 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170327143332/http://www.mcdonaldsindia.net/burgers/chicken-maharaja-mac.aspx | archive-date=27 March 2017 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref> and Veg Maharaja Mac, cheese and corn double patty with cocktail sauce.<ref name=\"McDonald's Veg Maharaja Mac - McDonald's India\">{{cite web | url=http://www.mcdonaldsindia.net/burgers/veg-maharaja-mac.aspx | title=McDonald's Veg Maharaja Mac \u2013 McDonald's India | publisher=McDonaldsIndia.net | accessdate=3 August 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807233156/http://www.mcdonaldsindia.net/burgers/veg-maharaja-mac.aspx | archive-date=7 August 2016 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Apart from these, the McSpicy burgers/wraps, McGrill and Pizza McPuff are sold in India. Mc Aloo Tikki, Mc Veggie, Mc Chicken, Mc Egg, Filet-o-fish burger, chicken wraps, veg wraps, chicken kebab burger are very popular in India. The latest addition in India being rice bowls, biriyani and naan wraps.\n\nPast promotional items have included the McPaneer and Grilled Chicken Royale,<ref name=\"McDonald's launches Royale Range premium burgers - Times of India\">{{cite web | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/McDonalds-launches-Royale-Range-premium-burgers/articleshow/33787842.cms | title=McDonald's launches Royale Range premium burgers \u2013 Times of India | publisher=TNN | date=15 April 2014 | accessdate=3 August 2016 | author=Sushma U N}}</ref> Mexican Spice Chicken and Veg, Asian Hot Garlic Dip and African Peri Peri Shake Shake (as part of the Spice Fest)<ref name=\"Spice route\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/spice-route/article3358356.ece | title=Spice route | newspaper=The Hindu | date=27 April 2012 | accessdate=3 August 2016}}</ref> Indi-McSpicy and the McCurry Pan.\n\nMcDonald's in India do not serve beef products, in deference to [[Hindu]] beliefs. McDonald's in India does not sell pork products, in deference to [[Islam]] beliefs.\nVegetarian and meat based meals are prepared in separate areas of the restaurant due to religious laws; cooks preparing vegetarian dishes wear a distinctive green apron and non vegetarian cooks wear a red apron.<ref>{{cite news|author=Mary Vanac |url=http://www.dispatch.com/content/blogs/the-bottom-line/2012/09/mcdonalds-goes-meat-less-in-india.html |title=McDonald's is going meat-less in India |newspaper=The Columbus Dispatch |date=2012-09-04 |accessdate=2013-12-14}}</ref>\n\n===Indonesia===\n[[File:McDonald's Burger Sate Indonesia 1.jpg|thumb|McDonald's Indonesia promo; Burger Sate, McFlurry Rujak Pedas, Markisa soda tea and Fries. Limited in August only, the month of Indonesian Independence.]]\n[[File:Congee at McDonald's.jpg|thumb|[[Bubur ayam]] (chicken congee)]]\nTo accommodate [[Muslim]]-majority population, all McDonald's in [[Indonesia]] are certified [[halal]], which means they do not serve bacon or pork patties, while serving only beef, chicken, and fish.<ref>{{cite web | title  = Sertifikasi Halal | work = McDonald's Indonesia | url = http://mcdonalds.co.id/menu/kualitas-produk/sertifikasi-halal}}</ref> Local items include crispy and spicy [[fried chicken]]; the McRice, a small mound of [[steamed rice]] wrapped in paper and available to supersize; McSoup, a chicken flavored soup with bits of croutons and vegetables; and ''Buryam'' (short for ''[[bubur ayam]]'' or chicken [[congee]]), later renamed as ''Bubur Ayam Spesial'' with the addition of [[fried egg]] topping.<ref>{{cite web | title = Bubur Ayam Spesial | work = McDonad's Indonesia | url = http://www.mcdonalds.co.id/menu/item/55?ref=19}}</ref> ''[[Sambal]]'' chili sauce, an essential component of [[Indonesian cuisine]], and tomato [[ketchup]] are available as condiments.\n\nMcDonald's fried chicken, McRice, and fruit tea are sold together as PaNas (''paket nasi'' or \"rice package\") with an additional sachet of ''sambal'' chili sauce.<ref>{{cite web | title  = PaNas1 | work = McDonald's Indonesia | url = http://www.mcdonalds.co.id/menu/item/64?ref=11}}</ref> This adopts the Indonesians' way of consuming ''[[ayam goreng]]'' (fried chicken) with steamed rice and ''sambal''.\n\nOther than fried chicken with rice and ''bubur ayam'' chicken rice congee, locals' preference of [[rice]]-based food is accommodated further by the introduction of Chicken with Spicy Tomato and Chicken Teriyaki,<ref>{{cite web | title = Chicken with Spicy Tomato & Chicken Teriyaki | work = McDonad's Indonesia | url = http://www.mcdonalds.co.id/promo/75?ref=85}}</ref> which is a bowl of steamed rice topped with strips of fried chicken patty with sauces and vegetables, similar to the Japanese [[donburi]] (rice bowl) fashion of serving.\n\nMcDonald's in Indonesia also promotes some seasonal foods, sold only within a limited certain period of time. Those limited periods include Chinese New Year, Ramadhan, and Independence Day specials.\n\nDuring [[Chinese New Year]], a Beef Prosperity Burger, consisting of two beef patties covered in black pepper sauce and topped with diced onions, is sold.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ta-chan |url=http://jakartalovestory.blogspot.ca/2012/01/mcdonalds-prosperity-burger.html |title=Jakarta Love Story: McDonald's Prosperity Burger |publisher=Jakartalovestory.blogspot.ca |date=2012-01-15 |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[Ramadhan]], McDonald's Indonesia has offered BBQ Beef Flatbread (2014), Curry Beef Delight (2015), [[Moroccan cuisine|Moroccan]] Burger (2016), Ayam Kremes (2017 and 2018, with addition of Nasi Uduk), and Ayam Serundeng Sambal Terasi (2019).<ref>{{cite web | title  = Ayam Kremes | work = McDonald's Indonesia | url = http://mcdonalds.co.id/promo/175?ref=85}}</ref>\n\nIn certain periods, such as August (the month of [[Proclamation of Indonesian Independence|Indonesian independence]]), McDonald's Indonesia launched local-inspired dishes such as the [[Satay|Burger Sate]], a hamburger with [[Peanut sauce|satay sauce]] (spicy ground peanut sauce), with Teh Soda Markisa (passion fruit tea soda);<ref>{{cite web | title  = Ini Rasa Kita: Burger Sate | work = McDonald's Indonesia | url = http://www.mcdonalds.co.id/promo/99?ref=85}}</ref> Local-inspired dessert include [[McFlurry]] with ''markisa'' (passion fruit) and ''rujak pedas'' (spicy mango [[rojak|rujak]]) flavour.<ref>{{cite web | title = Ini Rasa Kita: McFlurry Markisa & Rujak Pedas | work = McDonald's Indonesia | url = http://www.mcdonalds.co.id/promo/101?ref=85}}</ref>\n\n===Israel===\n[[File:Kosher McDonalds.JPG|thumb|left|[[Kashrut|Kosher]] McDonald's]]\n{{Main|McDonald's Israel}}\nThe only entirely [[Kashrut|kosher]] McDonald's are in [[Israel]] and [[Argentina]]. In these locations, patties are barbecued on [[charcoal]] rather than [[frying|fried]].<ref name=\"frommers.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.frommers.com/destinations/buenosaires/D55904.html|title=Kosher McDonald's Restaurant Review | location=Buenos Aires | work=Frommers.com<!-- Bot generated title -->}}</ref> Some kosher locations serve milk based desserts, but in separate booths, allowing for full separation of dairy and meat products in food preparation areas. However, most of the McDonald's outlets in Israel are not kosher service, as they serve cheeseburgers, which mix dairy and meat products.\n\nSpecialty items in Israeli McDonald's include the [[Shawarma|McShawarma]] and [[Kebab|McKebab]], both served on flatbread. On January 18, 2011, McDonald's introduced the McFalafel sandwich in Israel, but withdrew the item six months later.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/jul/12/mcdonalds-withdraws-mcfalafel-israeli-restaurants | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Harriet | last=Sherwood | title=McDonald's withdraws McFalafel from Israeli restaurants | date=12 July 2011}}</ref> Within the last few years they have added a vegetarian option, corn sticks (which are bite sized corn shniztels).\n\n===Japan===\n[[File:Idaho Burger - McDonald's jpn.JPG|thumb|Idaho burgers include bacon, beef, onion, cheese and pepper sauce.]]\nRegular menu items in Japanese McDonald's include: the Teriyaki McBurger, with ground pork patties, mayonnaise, lettuce, and teriyaki sauce; Shaka Shaka Chicken, a fried chicken strip served in a paper pouch, with cheese or pepper seasonings to shake in the bag; and the Fillet-O-Ebi (shrimp), with a fried shrimp patty and mustard. Breakfast options include a hot dog with pickle relish, ketchup, and mustard, then for lunch and dinner they serve the Chilli McHotdog with egg and chilli sauce. As well as regular soft drinks (which in Japan include grape flavoured Fanta and iced tea), McDonald's in Japan also serve cartons of milk, Minute Maid orange juice and \"Yassai Seikatsu\", a type of vegetable juice.\n\nSeasonal and limited-time items have included:\n* The Chicken Katsu Burger, a breaded chicken sandwich flavored with soy sauce and ginger.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.japantoday.com/category/new-products/view/cheese-katsu-burger|newspaper=Japan Today|title=Cheese Katsu Burger|date=30 March 2009}}</ref>\n* The Gratin [[Korokke]] Burger, a sandwich with korokke (breaded mashed potatoes) filled with shrimp, macaroni, shredded cabbage, and katsu{{clarify|date=May 2012}} sauce, and optional cheese; served during winter\n*[[File:In Japan, McDonald's (3194818934).jpg|thumb|McDonald counter in Japan]]Green tea-flavored milkshakes\n* The Salsa Burger, a breaded chicken sandwich with salsa\n* The Tamago Double Mac, a hamburger with three beef patties, pepper sauce, bacon, a poached egg, and optional cheese\n* The Teri Tama Burger, a teriyaki burger with egg; served during spring\n* The Tamago Double Mac, a burger with egg, two beef patties, and bacon\n* The [[Tsukimi]] Burger (\"moon-viewing burger\"), a hamburger with one beef patty, fry sauce, bacon, a poached egg (representing the Moon), and optional cheese; served before and during Tsukimi season\n* The Gurakoro Burger, a burger with a croquette patty, lettuce, and sauce, sold during the holiday months\n* Ume Nuggets, Chicken McNuggets with sour ''ume'' (plum) sauce for dipping\n* The Mega Teriyaki, a teriyaki-style Big Mac variant with two pork patties and teriyaki sauce\n* \"Quarter Pounder Jewelry\" burgers : The 'Gold Ring' available on July 6, 2012, the 'Black Diamond' on July 13, 2013 and 'Ruby Spark' on July 20, 2013 only<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsonjapan.com/html/newsdesk/article/103439.php|title=McDonald's Japan to offer 1,000-yen premium burgers|work=newsonjapan.com|accessdate=7 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303220033/http://newsonjapan.com/html/newsdesk/article/103439.php|archive-date=3 March 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2013/07/03/business/mcdonalds-to-offer-1000-burgers|title=McDonald's to offer \u00a51,000 burgers \u2013 The Japan Times|work=The Japan Times|accessdate=7 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn United States military establishments in Japan (like the US Naval Base in Yokosuka), both American and Japanese menus are sold, depending on availability.\n\nJapan has made \"American burgers\". The burgers in Japan are based on imaginations and symbolisms of burgers from different regions of the U.S. Such as Idaho burgers.\n\n===Malaysia===\n[[File:McDonald's Shah Alam.jpg|thumb|McDonald's counter in [[Shah Alam]], Malaysia. In August 2019, the chain also temporary adopted the local pronunciation of \"Mekdi\" as its alternate name, an act on celebrating its local market during the Malaysian National Day.]]\nCorrelating with most [[Muslim world|Muslim-majority markets]], all McDonald's in [[Malaysia]] adhered to the Islamic-dietary law ([[halal]]) under the supervision by the Department of Islamic Development Malaysia.<ref>{{cite web|author=Patrick Lee |url=http://www.thestar.com.my/News/Nation/2013/09/13/Our-food-is-halal-says-McDonalds.aspx |title=Our food says Halal, says McDonald's |publisher=The Star Online |date=2013-09-13 |accessdate=2013-12-14}}</ref>  Two [[Islamic law|Syarie]] experts in Malaysia also being appointed by the country to advised its food preparation.<ref>{{cite web|author=McDonalds Malaysia |url=https://www.mcdonalds.com.my/others/halal_leaflet.pdf|title=Our food says Halal, says McDonald's |publisher=McDonalds Malaysia|date=2018 |accessdate=2018-12-20}}</ref> Thus, meat is slaughtered via the halal technique, while pork and bacon are absent in its Malaysian menu.\n\nAmong the local bestseller in the Malaysian market includes the Ayam Goreng McD, originally branded as McDonald's [[Fried Chicken]], introduced in March 1986. The product's name was changed to Chicken McCrispy in 2000 and again to Ayam Goreng McD in 2002 to complement the country's culture. There are three variants of the fried chicken: Regular, [[Pungency#In food|Spicy]] and Extra Spicy. In 2017, a very successful marketing campaign has catapulted fried chicken as one of the local Malaysian bestseller.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nThe Malaysian McDonald's first approach on embracing the local tastebuds commenced in July 2002 by the debut of Bubur Ayam McD (\"McD's Chicken Porridge\"), chicken strips in rice [[congee]] with scallions, sliced ginger, fried shallots, and diced chilies;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sixthseal.com/2005/04/mcd-chicken-porridge-bubur-ayam-mcd/|title=McD Chicken Porridge (Bubur Ayam McD)|work=sixthseal.com|accessdate=8 October 2015}}</ref> The success of Bubur Ayam McD has spread the porridge to be introduced into the regional McDonalds markets in Indonesia and Thailand. A close spin-off of the product, the Bubur Ikan McD (\"McD's Fish Porridge\") also led suit, albeit the latter was only served as a periodical offer.\n\nAmong other popular menu items distinct to the Malaysian market includes the Spicy Chicken McDeluxe, a burger with crispy marinated chicken [[thigh]], lettuce and special sauce in a [[cornmeal]] bun; the GCB (\"Grilled Chicken Burger\"), [[grilling|grilled]] chicken thigh, with iceberg lettuce and chargrilled sauce, served in a toasted sesame seed bun; Nasi Ayam McD, [[rice]] set served with traditional [[sambal]] sauce, fried chicken, cucumber slices and [[Fried egg|sunny side up]];<ref>{{cite web|author=McDonalds Malaysia |url=https://www.mcdonalds.com.my/nasimcd|title=Nasi McD Baharu|publisher=McDonalds Malaysia|date=2018 |accessdate=2018-12-20}}</ref> and iced [[Milo (drink)|Milo]] drink. Local morning favourites, such as the [[Teh Tarik]] drink and [[Youtiao|Cakoi]] fried bread are also included in the Breakfast McSavers lineup. Concurrently, some of the items that are commonly available in the international market has since being discontinued in the Malaysian outlet, including [[Big N' Tasty]] and [[Quarter Pounder]], the latter has been reintroduced following the successful McD Election campaign in June 2019.\n\n[[File:Nasi McD.jpg|thumb|Nasi McD (lit. \"McD's Rice\"), a [[Malaysia]]nized McDonald's Menu. Rice served together with Fried Chicken, spicy [[Malay people|Malay]]-styled [[sambal]] sauce with some vegetables; a [[fried egg]] is also served as an optional add-on item with the meal.]]\nSimilar to McDonalds business design worldwide, periodical and limited-time offers also generally included in the menu, specialties inspired from local, international and fusion menus have ushered the arrival of [[Nasi Lemak]] Burger, Thai Fish Burger with Green Curry Sauce, Hawaiian Deluxe Burger, Mexicana Chicken Burger, Burger ''Syok'' (A Malaysian-styled Burger), among few. Specialty desserts and drinks have included [[The Hershey Company|Hershey's]] Sundae, D24 [[Durian]] McFlurry Party, [[Cendol]] Sundae, Salted Caramel Pie, [[Coconut]] Pie, Pulut Hitam (Black [[Glutinous rice|Glutinous Rice]]) Pie, [[Bandung (drink)|Bandung]] drink and [[Pie \u00e0 la Mode]]. Some of the temporary food-items also would later occasionally returned on a periodical basis such in the case of Hot & Spicy McShaker [[Fries]], Spicy [[Chicken nugget|Nuggets]], Samurai (Japanese styled Burger), Spicy Korean Burger and Rio (Brazilian inspired Burger); while a few being absorbed to be a common Malaysian McDonald's fixture, as the case of GCB Burger, first available briefly in 2010, it later constitute as a permanent item since 2013.\n\nMcDonalds Malaysia has also introduced seasonal menus to commemorate major festivals and celebration in the [[Demographics of Malaysia|multiracial]] country. Since 1994, McDonalds Malaysia launched Prosperity Burger during the [[Chinese New Year]] festival, the menu was then adopted by its neighbours in Singapore and Indonesia. The burger come in beef and chicken varieties, with black pepper sauce, topped with fresh onions in a sesame seed bun. Additionally, between 2015\u20132018, McDonalds Malaysia has also included Golden Prosperity Burger in the menu, with a slice of hash brown is also added on the burger patties. The Prosperity Burger is usually served together with [[curly fries]]. While during the Muslim holy [[Islamic calendar|month]] of [[Ramadhan]] since 2015, the chain would offer the Foldover (equivalent to the [[McArabia]]) to its customers, there are two variants of the foldover: Lazeez Foldover (Lazeez, which means \"delicious\" in Arabic) chicken patties with garlic sauce; and the Mashwi Foldover (Mashwi, meaning \"food\" in standard Arabic) is grilled beef topped with hot sauce.\n\n===Pakistan===\nAll McDonald's in Pakistan are certified halal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcdonalds.com.pk/faqs |title=McDonald's \u00bb Faqs |publisher=Mcdonalds.com.pk |date= |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> Pakistani menus resemble those of Middle Eastern and South Asian locations. McArabias and Spicy Chicken Burgers are popular in Pakistan.{{citation needed|date=May 2012}} A Chicken Big Mac is also available. In addition to apple pie, McDonald's Pakistan serves choco-orange pie and blueberry custard pie, which is fried. In March 2019, McDonald's launched Bun Kebab(a local variation of Anday Wala Burger). All McDonald's Pakistan menu items with the exception of ice cream cones are also available for delivery.\n\n===Philippines===\nMost Filipinos colloquially refer to McDonald's as \"McDo\" (equivalent to \"Mickey D's\"), and the term has been adapted by McDonald's Philippines, even naming most of their products after the term. (However, the use of \"McDo\" has been discontinued by the end of 2019 and it is now referred to its full form, McDonald's, except in item names.) Menu items in McDonald's in the [[Philippines]] include McSpaghetti, Chicken McDo, Burger McDo and Crispy Chicken Sandwich, in order to compete with the country's largest fast food retail [[Jollibee]]. From 2001 to 2006 the McRice, steamed rice formed into buns, was available as a replacement for bread buns on beef and chicken sandwiches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/Article.aspx?articleId=365232&publicationSubCategoryId=81 |title=A handy rice meal \u2013 The Philippine Star \u00bb Lifestyle Features \u00bb Food and Leisure |publisher=Philstar.com |date=2006-10-26 |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> Breakfast menus include [[longaniza]], a [[Philippine cuisine|Philippine]] sausage, served with rice and a fried egg, and the Hamdesal, a [[Pandesal]] bun with pineapple glaze syrup, mayonnaise, and Canadian bacon served with scrambled eggs, cheese, or both.\n\nSome pies come in pineapple and [[taro]] flavors, although the McDonald's Apple Pie is served in all locations. Only select locations serve milkshakes. Twister Fries is also served seasonally, as well as Shake Shake Fries, which are McDonald's French Fries that come in a paper bag and served with a packet of flavored powder (Barbeque, Cheesy Butter, Sour Cream, Ketchup, and Pizza flavors); customers must administer the flavoring to the bag of fries themselves, shaking the bag until the powder is evenly distributed among the fries. They are available annually.\n\nMcDonald's in the Philippines also promotes movie tie-in products seasonally, such as the Banana-Oreo McFlurry and Banana McFloat during the release of ''[[Minions (film)|Minions]]'' in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inquisitr.com/294827/mcdonalds-curly-fries-they-exist-but-probably-not-in-your-neighborhood/ |title=McDonald\u2019s Curly Fries\u2026 They Exist, But Probably Not In Your Neighborhood |publisher=Inquisitr.com |date=2012-08-07 |accessdate=2014-04-08}}</ref>\n\n===Saudi Arabia===\nAll McDonald's in [[Saudi Arabia]] are certified halal.<ref name=halal/> Saudi locations serve the Spicy McChicken, McArabia, and the Big Tasty, the latter of which is also available in some European locations.\n\n===Singapore===\nAll McDonald's in Singapore are certified halal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mcdonalds.com.sg/eatsmart_faq.html |title=Welcome &#124; McDonald's Singapore |publisher=Mcdonalds.com.sg |accessdate=2012-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130418104608/http://www.mcdonalds.com.sg/eatsmart_faq.html |archivedate=2013-04-18 }}</ref> Singaporean locations offer the McSpicy, a spicy chicken burger.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcdonalds.com.sg/eatsmart_menu_mcspicy.html |title=Welcome &#124; McDonald's Singapore |publisher=Mcdonalds.com.sg |accessdate=2012-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120927085810/http://www.mcdonalds.com.sg/eatsmart_menu_mcspicy.html |archivedate=2012-09-27 }}</ref> A 24-hour McDelivery service is available in all locations on [[Pulau Ujong|the island]].\n\nThe curry sauce is a dip unique to Singapore and is the favourite complementary dip to Chicken McNuggets.\n\nIn 2011, due to congestion at the United States' West Coast ports, the popular chicken nugget dip was unavailable for a period of time,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Yeo|first1=Miranda|title=McDonald's curry sauce returns today|url=http://news.asiaone.com/news/soshiok/mcdonalds-curry-sauce-returns-today|accessdate=3 August 2016|publisher=asiaone|date=18 June 2015}}</ref> causing a public outcry. A similar crisis happened in 2015.\n\nIn July 2016, McDonald's launched a limited edition take-home bottle of the curry sauce (375ml), which was limited to four purchases per single receipt.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.todayonline.com/lifestyle/mcdonalds-curry-sauce-available-limited-edition-take-home-bottle-july-21|title=McDonald\u2019s Curry Sauce available in limited edition take-home bottle from July 21|publisher=TODAY|date=15 July 2016}}</ref> The product was overwhelmingly popular and several outlets ran out of stock on the item extremely quickly.\n\nMcDonald's has also introduced several special additions to the Singapore menu, such as the Salted Egg York Chicken Burger in 2016, coupled with salt & pepper shaker fries and Gula Melaka McFlurry.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/mcdonald-s-singapore/2915700.html|title=McDonald's Singapore launches menu inspired by local flavours|publisher=ChannelNewsAsia|date=29 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nMcDonald's also introduced new and upgraded products related to Singapore's National Day and public holidays (e.g. Lunar New Year, SG50).\n\n===South Korea===\n[[File:Bulgogi burger.jpg|thumb|McDonald's Bulgogi burger in South Korea]]\nMcDonald's locations in South Korea serve a shrimp burger as well as a Bulgogi Burger, a pork patty in [[bulgogi]] marinade. The bulgogi-flavored sauce was developed by [[Ottogi]], a large South Korean food manufacturer that provides all of the condiments to the country's McDonald's.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2902414 |title=Can tteokbokki rescue rice industry? |date=2009-03-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405232757/http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2902414 |archivedate=2012-04-05 }}</ref> A 24-hour [[McDelivery]] service was launched in 2007 and now is available across South Korea.<ref>{{cite web|title = 16 McDonald\u2019s Vehicles We Doubt You\u2019ve Ever Seen|url = http://www.lifedaily.com/story/16-mcdonalds-vehicles-we-doubt-youve-ever-seen/10/|website = lifedaily|accessdate = 15 February 2017|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170216054413/http://www.lifedaily.com/story/16-mcdonalds-vehicles-we-doubt-youve-ever-seen/10/|archive-date = 2017-02-16|url-status = dead}}</ref>  McDelivery also has an app available on both Google Play and the Apple Store.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.mwos2.mcdelivery |title=(\uacf5\uc2dd) \ub9e5\ub3c4\ub0a0\ub4dc \ub9e5\ub51c\ub9ac\ubc84\ub9ac \ubc30\ub2ec|publisher=Google Play |accessdate=15 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/mcdelivery-korea/id1027699629 |title=McDelivery Korea|publisher=Apple Store |accessdate=15 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nDessert options include [[affogato]]. Former options included a green tea [[McFlurry]]<ref>{{cite web|author=SirJman |url=http://www.travellingmcds.com/2011/12/green-tea-mcflurry-seoul-korea-january.html |title=McDonald's Around the World: Green Tea McFlurry \u2013 Seoul, South Korea \u2013 January 2009 |publisher=Travellingmcds.com |date=2011-12-07 |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref>  and the McBingsu, a seasonal option similar to [[patbingsu]].\n\n===Taiwan===\nMcDonald's in Taiwan serve ''kao fan'' (\u70e4\u98ef, ''k\u01ceo f\u00e0n'') (literally \"baked rice\"), a burger-like entr\u00e9e with rice patties instead of buns.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/food/article-1126655/The-hotlist-10-unusual-items-McDonalds-menus-world.html | location=London | work=Daily Mail | title=The hotlist: 10 unusual items on McDonald's menus around the world}}</ref> It is modelled on the eponymous product of McDonald's Japanese rival, [[MOS Burger]]. McDonald's locations in Taiwan sell fried chicken legs to compete with [[KFC]]. Additionally, [[corn soup]] is available as a substitute for French fries or \u00e0 la carte.\n\n===Thailand===\n[[File:McDonalds Meal.JPG|thumb|right|[[McChicken]], Filet-O-Fish, Chicken McNuggets, French fries and fried chicken sold by McDonald's in [[Bangkok]].]]\n\nIn [[Thailand]], McDonald's serves the [[Samurai]] Pork Burger, with teriyaki sauce, lettuce, and mayonnaise.<ref>{{cite web|author=JetSetCD |url=http://www.jaunted.com/story/2011/10/17/221250/07/travel/Munching+McDonald%27s+Exotic+%27Samurai+Pork+Burger%27+in+Phuket |title=Munching McDonald's Exotic 'Samurai Pork Burger' in Phuket |publisher=Jaunted |date= |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> As in other Asian markets, Thai McDonald's sell fried chicken and spicy chicken wings. Chilli sauce is available as a condiment, along with [[ketchup]]. Other Thailand-specific items include rice patties made with [[jasmine rice]], the [[Caribbean cuisine|Caribbean]] Shrimp Burger, and a salad shaker based on ''som tam'' [[Carica papaya|papaya]] salad. McDonald's restaurants in Thailand also serve the Mega animals  Mac (known as the Double Big Mac) all year long.\n\nBetween October 1 and 13, 2013, or until supplies ran out, McDonald's offered a \"McVeggie\" burger to coincide with the tradition of many people of Chinese descent only eating vegetarian food during the annual \"[[Nine Emperor Gods Festival|Kin J]]\" period. The McVeggie is an all vegetable fried patty consisting of potatoes, beets, peas and carrot topped with lettuce and teriyaki sauce.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=10151874944932866&set=a.100032547865.89349.100023357865&type=1&theater|title=McDonald's \u2013 New Promotion October 2013 \u2013 Facebook|work=facebook.com|accessdate=8 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Turkey===\nAll McDonald's meat in [[Turkey]] are certified [[halal]] by Pinar, a Turkish company. Restaurants offer the Turkish drink [[ayran]] and the McTurco, a type of [[kebab]] with chicken or beef.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.travellingmcds.com/2012/09/mcturko-istanbul-turkey-august-2012.html|title=McDonald's Around the World: McTurko \u2013 Istanbul, Turkey \u2013 August 2012|work=travellingmcds.com|accessdate=8 October 2015}}</ref> Turkish locations also serve onion rings, the Mega Mac (known as the Double Big Mac) and the Kofteburger, with a spiced mincemeat patty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brandeating.com/2010/04/whats-on-menu-mcdonalds-turkey.html |title=What's on Menu: McDonald's Turkey |publisher=Brand Eating |date=2010-04-18 |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref>\n\n===United Arab Emirates===\nIn the United Arab Emirates, as of 2016, McDonald's standard ''a-la-carte'' menu include the hamburger (marketed as \"beefburger\"), cheeseburger, double cheeseburger, chicken burger, veggie burger, [[Quarter Pounder|Quarter Pounder with Cheese]], [[Big Mac]], Mega Mac, [[Big N' Tasty|Big Tasty]], McRoyale, [[McChicken]], Spicy McChicken, Chicken Mac, Chicken Mega Mac, [[Grand Chicken]] (Classic, Deluxe, Special, and Spicy variants), [[McArabia|McArabia Chicken]], [[Chicken McNuggets]], and [[Filet-O-Fish]] sandwiches. In some outlets, the Indian-inspired Mc [[Aloo tikki|Aloo Tikki]] burger is also served as part of the McSavers and [[Happy Meal]] lines.\n\nThe McArabia initially was available as both a chicken and beef [[kofta]] variants, but only the chicken remained as standard, although the kofta and [[sujuk]] variants are sometimes reintroduced in limited promotional runs. Other limited edition sandwiches included The Asian, The Mexican, The French, and The Turkish. The standard menu formerly carried other McDonald's staples such as the Chicken Fillet, the Spicy Chicken Fillet, and the McWings.\n\nMcDonald's in the U.A.E. is a certified halal chain.<ref name=halal/>\n\n===Vietnam===\nVietnam serves broken rice also known as C\u01a1m t\u1ea5m, named simply as c\u01a1m. The dish consists of [[broken rice]], grilled pork and various other sides that come at an extra price. \nB\u00e1nh m\u00ec(General term for bread) is also served and looks very similar to a [[Subway sandwich]].\nThey also sell fried chicken, besides grilled pork.\n\n==Europe==\n===Belgium===\nBelgian McDonald's serve the Croque McDo, consisting of two slices of [[Emmental (cheese)|Emmental cheese]] and a slice of ham toasted between two hamburger buns. This is a variation of the traditional [[croque-monsieur]] sandwich found in France and Belgium.<ref name=nile>{{cite web|url=http://www.nileguide.com/blog/2010/06/09/strange-mcdonalds-menu-items-around-the-world/|accessdate=3 August 2012|publisher=NileGuide|title=Strange McDonald's Menu Items around the world|author=Resnik, Alex|date=9 June 2010}}</ref> The \"Belgo\" burger is a hamburger with bacon, Belgian [[Maredsous Abbey#Maredsous cheese|Maredsous cheese]], roasted onions, and [[cocktail sauce]].\n\n===Croatia===\nThe McCountry sandwich is a regular menu item in Croatian McDonald's restaurants, consisting of two pork sausage patties on a bun with cheese, lettuce, tomato, onion, and a special sauce. Another regular menu item is the McToast, a ham and cheese sandwich on toast. The Maestro Burger can also be found which is normally seen in the Netherlands. Seasonal and promotional offers include [[Greek cuisine|Greek]] and Italian offerings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcdonalds.hr/ponuda/mccountry/ |title=Mcdonalds |publisher=Mcdonalds |date= |accessdate=2015-09-02}}</ref>\n\n===Cyprus===\nMcDonald's in [[Cyprus]] sells the Greek Mac, a Big Mac variant with pita bread and [[tzatziki]] sauce, and the Greek Chicken, a Greek Mac with chicken patties instead of beef.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mcdonalds.com.cy/Menu.html |title=Mcdonalds |publisher=Mcdonalds |accessdate=2012-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120427042501/http://www.mcdonalds.com.cy/Menu.html |archivedate=2012-04-27 }}</ref> A shrimp burger is also sold during the period of [[Great Lent|Lent]] when [[Church of Cyprus|Orthodox Christians]] don't eat meat. This only applies to the Republic of Cyprus, and not the northern [[Northern Cyprus|Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus]], where due to the lack of international recognition, McDonald's does not exist.\n\n===Czech Republic===\nThe McCountry sandwich served in Croatia is also available in the [[Czech Republic]].\n\nIn 2012, McDonald's added McSma\u017e\u00e1k, a variation on [[sma\u017een\u00fd s\u00fdr]], a type of [[cheese sandwich]].<ref>{{cite web|author=LetsEat |url=http://letseatcyprus.blogspot.ca/ |title=LetsEat.Com.Cy |publisher=Letseatcyprus.blogspot.ca |date=2012-06-05 |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> It is similar to the Slovak McSyr.\n\nIn 2019, McDonald's removed [[Big N' Tasty|Big Tasty]] sandwich from its menu.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcdonalds.cz/ochutnej/denni-menu/|title=Denn\u00ed menu|date=2016-02-29|website=McDonald's CZ|language=cs-CZ|access-date=2019-05-22}}</ref> It was brought back in June 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcdonalds.cz/novinky/neodolatelna-chut-big-tasty/|title=Denn\u00ed menu|date=2019-06-17|website=McDonald's CZ|language=cs-CZ|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref>\n\n===Denmark===\nOne item sold in McDonald's restaurants in Denmark, that tries to imitate classic Danish food is the Pommes Frites Sauce that somewhat resemble [[remoulade]]. This also for a long period from the opening of the first restaurant replaced mayonnaise dip and where the only condiment available besides [[ketchup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcdonalds.com/dk/da-dk/product/pommes-frites-dip.html|title=McDonald's Denmark - Pommes Frites Dip|work=mcdonalds.com|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Denmark]], every McDonald's serves a small size chicken burger called \"Chicken Salsa Cheese\". Also following its other Scandinavian cousins, Danish McDonald's serve a Daim McFlurry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.travellingmcds.com/2012/09/daim-mcflurry-copenhagen-denmark-august.html|title=McDonald's Around the World: Daim McFlurry \u2013 Copenhagen, Denmark \u2013 August 2012|work=travellingmcds.com|accessdate=8 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn Denmark you can buy chilli cheese tops, which is also served in other Nordic countries like Sweden and Norway.\n\n===Finland===\nIn [[Finland]], most McDonald's hamburgers can be ordered with a [[Rye bread|rye]] bun, based on the success of the promotional \"McRuis\" (McRye) burger.<ref>{{cite web|author=Published: May 17, 1999 |url=http://adage.com/article/news/mcdonald-s-patent-rye-bread-burger/13813/ |title=McDonald's tries to patent rye bread burger &#124; News \u2013 Advertising Age |publisher=Adage.com |date=1999-05-17 |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> ''El Maco'' is a burger with salsa and [[sour cream]] sauce. The El Maco meal is served with a barbecue spice mixture and a paper bag in which the fries and the spice mixture are poured, similar to Japan's Shaka Shaka Chicken. In 2018 McDonald's released the [[Big Mac]] with bacon. Also same as in Sweden, they are offering McVegan patty for vegans in wraps, salad or as a burger. [[Macarons]] are also served as a [[McCafe]] product. In early 2018 they released [[Valio]] [[Oltermanni]] Juustonapit that is basically small cheese nuggets filled with the famous Finnish cheese.\n\n===France===\nIn France, McDonald's offers donuts for breakfast and [[Kronenbourg Brewery|Kronenbourg 1664]] beer in 25 or 33&nbsp;cl measures. The Croque McDo and various ''Petit Plaisir'' items are available, as in Belgium and Morocco, respectively.<ref name=nile/> In 2016, McDonald's launched a summer menu, called the \"American Summer\" Menu, with one burger containing crispy peppers.\n\n===Germany===\n[[Image:McDonald\u2019s-Wirtshausschild.jpg|thumb|Inn sign in an [[Altstadt]] area]]\nStandard menu items at German McDonald's include the Hamburger Royal TS, [[Caesar salad]]s, one Veggieburger called Veggie Clubhouse,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcdonalds.de/produkte/alle-produkte|title=McDonald's \u2013 Alle Produkte|publisher=mcdonalds.de|accessdate=12 August 2016|language=de}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcdonalds.de/produkte/produkt-profil?productName=veggie_clubhouse|title=McDonald's veggie clubhouse at the German McDonald's homepage |publisher=Mcdonalds.de |date= |accessdate=2016-02-08}}</ref> and Caesar, [[honey mustard]], and [[Ranch dressing|Ranch]] chicken wraps.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcdonalds.de/produkte/alle-produkte |title=Permanent German Menu |publisher=Mcdonalds.de |date= |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> The [[McRib]] sandwich, a seasonal item in most countries, is a permanent menu item in Germany.<ref>{{cite news |last=Feder |first=Barnaby J. |title=A McDonald's Burger of the Garden Variety |date=December 9, 1992 |newspaper=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/12/09/business/a-mcdonald-s-burger-of-the-garden-variety.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219143213/http://www.nytimes.com/1992/12/09/business/a-mcdonald-s-burger-of-the-garden-variety.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm |archivedate=December 19, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=McRib product information at mcdonalds.de |url=http://www.mcdonalds.de/produkte/produkt-profil?productName=mcrib|accessdate=24 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nAs of Mid-February 2013 (valentines day), McDonald's Germany started selling the Mc[[Currywurst]] with [[bread roll]] or Fries, a hot sausage with tangy tomato sauce and [[Curry]] powder in mild and spicy.<ref>{{cite web|title=McCurrywurst product information at mcdonalds.de |url=http://www.mcdonalds.de/produkte/produkt-profil?productName=mccurrywurst|accessdate=17 February 2013}}</ref> The item is no longer sold (September 2016). There is currently a special event where they are selling the McCurrywurst again with a new name: McCurrywurst Chicken. This time it is made out of chicken and there are 3 Monopoly-Stickers on the box. The event started on November the 14th and will end on the 24th of November.<ref>{{cite web|title=McCurrywurst Product information at mcdonalds.com/de|url=https://www.mcdonalds.com/de/de-de/product/mccurrywurst-mit-chicken-6212.html|accessdate=14 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe German McDonald's Breakfast does provide Br\u00f6tchen, a crispy bread roll; McCroissant, a [[Croissant]] stuffed with [[Ham]] and Cheese; [[Scrambled Eggs]] with [[Bacon]] and \"Classic Breakfast\", a choice of bread rolls with sweet spreads resembling a very common German breakfast choice.<ref>{{cite web|title=Breakfast product information at mcdonalds.de |url=http://www.mcdonalds.de/produkte/fruehstueck|accessdate=17 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nBeer is no longer sold at all locations. It is still served in older outlets owned by German brewers with leases allowing the serving of beer.<ref>\"Behind the Arches\" by John Love, page 433-434</ref>\n\n===Greece===\nMcDonald's in [[Greece]] currently sells the Greek Mac, a Big Mac variant on [[pita]] bread with [[tzatziki]] sauce.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://surveyforcustomers.com/www-mcdvoice-com/ |title=Mcdonalds McDVoice Survey |publisher=Mcdonalds |date= |accessdate=2018-09-07 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150712203102/http://mcdonalds.gr/en/products/ta-burger-mas/greek-mac |archivedate=2015-07-12 |df= }}</ref> Other regular menus include the McToast,<ref name=\"Mcdonalds\">{{cite web |url=http://mcdonalds.gr/el/products/finger-food/veggie-snackers |title=Mcdonalds |publisher=Mcdonalds |date= |accessdate=2016-04-24 }}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> a ham and cheese sandwich on toast, Deluxe fries<ref name=\"Mcdonalds\"/> ([[potato wedges]]), and [[onion rings]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mcdonalds.gr/en/products/finger-food/onion-rings |title=Mcdonalds |publisher=Mcdonalds |accessdate=2016-04-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160507001122/http://mcdonalds.gr/en/products/finger-food/onion-rings |archivedate=2016-05-07 }}</ref> [[Heineken]] beer is also served in all locations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mcdonalds.gr/en/products/cold-drinks/beer |title=Mcdonalds |publisher=Mcdonalds |accessdate=2016-04-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160507002130/http://mcdonalds.gr/en/products/cold-drinks/beer |archivedate=2016-05-07 }}</ref>\n\nDuring the period of [[Great Lent|Lent]] when [[Church of Greece|Orthodox Christians]] abstain from eating meat, McDonald's also offers the McVeggie burger,<ref name=\"Mcdonalds\"/> a Shrimp Burger,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mcdonalds.gr/el/products/ta-burger-mas/shrimp-burger |title=Mcdonalds |publisher=Mcdonalds |accessdate=2016-04-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409172659/http://mcdonalds.gr/el/products/ta-burger-mas/shrimp-burger |archivedate=2016-04-09 }}</ref> a McWrap Shrimp,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mcdonalds.gr/el/products/wraps/mcwrap-shrimp |title=Mcdonalds |publisher=Mcdonalds |date= |accessdate=2016-04-24 }}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> fried veggie snackers,<ref name=\"Mcdonalds\"/> [[spring rolls]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mcdonalds.gr/el/products/finger-food/spring-rolls |title=Mcdonalds |publisher=Mcdonalds |accessdate=2016-04-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170417012147/http://mcdonalds.gr/el/products/finger-food/spring-rolls |archivedate=2017-04-17 }}</ref> and fried shrimp with dipping sauce.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mcdonalds.gr/el/products/finger-food/garides |title=Mcdonalds |publisher=Mcdonalds |accessdate=2016-04-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085233/http://mcdonalds.gr/el/products/finger-food/garides |archivedate=2017-04-24 }}</ref>\n\n===Hungary===\nHungarian McDonald's sell the McFarm, once available in Greece. Limited-time products available only in Hungary have included McDonald's version of the popular Hungarian breakfast food [[l\u00e1ngos]], and a \"Hungarian flavors\" menu.<ref>{{cite web |author=\u2014&nbsp;08/10/31 |url=http://www.chew.hu/all_hell_breaks_loose_as_mcdon/ |title=All Hell Breaks Loose as McDonalds Hungary Goes \"McMagyar\" |publisher=Chew.hu |accessdate=2012-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115013952/http://www.chew.hu/all_hell_breaks_loose_as_mcdon/ |archivedate=2013-01-15 }}</ref>\n\n===Italy===\nItalian McDonald's offers, since 2000, Crispy McBacon, composed of two beef patties, one slice of cheddar, bacon and a special sauce. In 2014 a variation with chicken has been offered in a limited way.\nIt also began offering \"McItaly\" items from 2010 to 2017 in a limited period. Products include burger with \"100 percent made-in-Italy meat\" and various typical Italian ingredients. The company advertises burgers in several European countries as using Italian beef, because Cremonini provides it also in various locations.<ref name=\"marchetti20100529\">{{cite news | url=http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/business/news/mcitaly-menu-merges-buy-local-with-fast-food-248805/?print=1 | title=McItaly menu merges 'buy local' with fast food | work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette | date=2010-05-29 | agency=GlobalPost | accessdate=May 31, 2012 | author=Marchetti, Silvia}}</ref> On May 24, 2013 McDonald's Italia in cooperation with [[Barilla Group|Barilla]] began offering for a limited period a [[pasta salad]].<ref name=Guardian52313>{{cite news|title=McDonald's joins forces with 136-year-old pasta firm in Italy Fast-food chain will sell pasta salad from Friday in attempt to Italianise menu after deal with Parma-based Barilla|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/may/23/mcdonalds-joins-forces-pasta-italy-barilla|accessdate=May 24, 2013|newspaper=The Guardian|date=May 23, 2013|author=Lizzy Davies|quote=pennette pasta with \"a balanced and skilful mix of tuna, tomatoes, peppers, capers and olives, seasoned with a pinch of oregano and salt\"}}</ref>\nMcCaf\u00e8, launched in 2005, has also been adapted to Italian taste.\nFrom May 2015 the menu included for a limited time the vegetarian burger McVeggie, offered here with no cheese.\n\nA [[Nutella]] burger called Sweety debuted in 2016.<ref>{{cite news|author=Sternitzky-Di Napoli, Daniela|url=http://www.chron.com/life/food/article/McDonald-s-introduces-new-a-burger-Nutella-10610517.php|title=http://www.chron.com/life/food/article/McDonald-s-introduces-new-a-burger-Nutella-10610517.php|newspaper=[[Houston Chronicle]]|date=2016-11-12|accessdate=2018-11-05}}</ref>\n\nSince 2018, McDonald's replaced McItaly with \"My selection\", special limited offer burgers with high quality Italian and foreign ingredients, selected by MasterChef judge [[Joe Bastianich]].\n\n===Malta===\nIn [[Malta]], McDonald's sell mozzarella sticks and chicken wings as side dishes. The Big Tasty is a variant to the Big N' Tasty while chicken nuggets come with an array of sauces, such as BBQ, sweet and sour, ketchup or mayonnaise. The McCafe was also first introduced in Malta, more specifically on its sister island Gozo, where the only McDonald's and McCafe on the island are found in the Arcadia shopping centre in the capital city of Victoria.<ref name=\"gozonews.com\">{{cite web|url=http://gozonews.com/645/mcdonald%E2%80%99s-new-mccafe-in-victoria/|title=Gozo News.Com|work=Gozo News.Com|accessdate=8 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304035919/http://gozonews.com/645/mcdonald%E2%80%99s-new-mccafe-in-victoria/|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=dead}}</ref>\nIt is also the place where the McFtira was sold, a beef or chicken burger with the addition of goat cheese and served in traditional Maltese bread.\n\n===Netherlands===\nIn the [[Netherlands]], McDonald's sells the McKroket, a deep-fried roll containing beef [[ragout]], similar to the Dutch \"kroket\" or also the much smaller \"bitterballen\" sold in virtually all snack bars.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://money.cnn.com/galleries/2008/fortune/0805/gallery.royale.fortune/3.html | work=CNN | title=Beyond 'Royale with Cheese' | date=8 May 2008 | access-date=2012-08-03 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012034813/http://money.cnn.com/galleries/2008/fortune/0805/gallery.royale.fortune/3.html | archive-date=2012-10-12 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Dutch McDonald's serve frite sauce or \"American Sauce,\" a yellow mayonnaise-like sauce not eaten in the United States with French fries. The ChickenSat\u00e9 burger was also offered, consisting of fried chicken with peanut sauce; this popular food is inspired by the Netherlands' historical connection to Indonesia. The Joppie Burger was also available using Joppie sauce, popular in the Netherlands. Since 2015, the Maestro Burger menu has been available. The Maestro Burger is a large burger with sesameseed bread, 2 Angus beef patties, onion, lettuce, bacon and mustard. The Chicken Maestro Burger, and the Maestro Burger Egg, a version of the regular burger with an added egg, have been made available since the original burger's launch. Also included in the menu is \"Boerenfriet\", which are thick, large fries, as commonly found in burgerbars, as well as regular mayonnaise. The introduction of the Maestro Burger is part of the revamp McDonald's is going through in the Netherlands since change of directors, focussing more on customers that seek higher quality burgers and that who would usually visit burgerbars. \nSpecial Dutch drinks include Fristi (a yogurt drink) and Chocomel (a chocolate milk drink).\nAlso available in the Netherlands are ''[[stroopwafel]]'' McFlurries.\n\n===Norway===\nAs in Finland, Norwegian McDonald's serve the El Maco (on a seasonal basis) and offer gluten free buns without an extra cost. They also serve a Laksewrap, deep-fried fish with salad and a mango slice in a tortilla.<ref name=nile/>\n\nAnother popular burger option available in Norway is the Chicken Salsa.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.mcdonalds.com/no/nb-no/produkt/chicken-salsa.html | title=Chicken Salsa (Norway)}}</ref> Chicken Salsa is a chicken burger with crispy lettuce, salsa sauce, sour cream and nachos.\n\nIn 2002, the [[McAfrika]] burger was introduced in [[Norway]], coinciding with major famines in Southern Africa. The name of the burger drew much negative publicity as being highly insensitive.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.delish.com/food-fun/mcdonalds-mcafrika-fast-food-flops#slide-8 | title=We're Not Lovin' It! Fast Food's Most Famous Flops | accessdate=2013-06-07 | author=Borja, Sahara}}</ref> The burger with vegetables were placed in pita bread.<ref>*{{cite web|last=McGrath|first=Jane|title=5 Failed McDonald's Menu Items: McAfrica |url=http://money.howstuffworks.com/5-failed-mcdonalds-menu-items1.htm#page=5|publisher=HowStuffWorks, Inc|accessdate=March 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Poland===\nOfferings in Polish McDonald's restaurants include: the Wie\u015bMac (\"Country Mac\"), a quarter-pound beef patty with onions, lettuce, cheese, mustard, and [[horseradish sauce]] on a sesame seed bun;<ref>{{cite web |author=David K. Israel |url=http://www.mentalfloss.com/blogs/archives/94251 |title=McDonald\u2019s Menu Items From Around The World |publisher=Mental Floss |date=2011-07-20 |accessdate=2012-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120826112323/http://www.mentalfloss.com/blogs/archives/94251 |archivedate=2012-08-26 }}</ref> the Pikantny Kurczakburger (\"Spicy Chickenburger\"), a chicken sandwich with lettuce and hot [[Mexican cuisine|Mexican]]-style sauce; McWrap \u2013 tortilla with chicken available in two versions: Classic (mayonnaise, mild-Mexican sauce, lettuce, rucola, shredded cheese, two slices of tomato and chicken patty) and Honey-Mustard (honey-mustard sauce, lettuce, shredded cheese, two slices of tomato, two strips of bacon and chicken patty). During winter period you can get Kanapka Drwala (\"The Lumberjack's Sandwich\") \u2013 a big bun with pork rinds instead of sesame, a quarter pounder, bacon, big piece of deep-fried cheese, sauce and vegetables. There is a free apple in every Happy Meal.\n\n===Portugal===\nPortuguese McDonald's offers a variety of soups, including their national dish of kale soup ([[caldo verde]]) and cream of carrot, white bean and spinach.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcdonalds.pt/ementa/categorias/sopas/|title=Sopas|work=mcdonalds.pt}}</ref>  These are offered as add-ons to Happy meals as well. There is also a McBifana and a McPrego on a ciabatta roll. The Portugal-specific mixed salad contains olives, corn, onions and tomatoes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcdonalds.pt/ementa/categorias/saladas/|title=Saladas|work=mcdonalds.pt}}</ref> In November 2016 McDonald's Portugal introduced a vegetarian burger option called McVeggie (made from [[quinoa]], bell peppers, wheat flour, wheat protein, vegetable oil, wheat bran, eggs, vegetable starch, spices, salt, onion, garlic, green peas, sugar and mixed herbs).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcdonalds.pt/campanhas/mcveggie/|title=McVeggie|work=mcdonalds.pt|access-date=2017-05-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180115124727/https://www.mcdonalds.pt/campanhas/mcveggie/|archive-date=2018-01-15|url-status=dead}}</ref> For dessert there are Portugal-specific fresh pineapple chunks, apple cinnamon sundae and a sandwich-shaped apple pie. In 2018 McDonald's released a limited-time edition of the Big Mac Bacon, essentially a Big Mac with added bacon.<ref>{{cite web |author=McDonald's |url=https://www.mcdonalds.pt/ementa/categorias/menus/ |title=McMenu |publisher=McDonald's |date=2018-08-20 |accessdate=2018-09-17}}</ref>\nBeer is available in all restaurants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcdonalds.pt/ementa/categorias/sobremesas/|title=Sobremesas|work=mcdonalds.pt}}</ref> In October of the same year, Chicken Country has been introduced as a cheap option (EuroPoupan\u00e7a) to purchase, considered as a side with any menu, like many other products.\n\nMcDonald's Portugal launched a loyalty scheme under the name ''MLovers'', in the form of an app. This scheme allows adherents to collect points on purchased products and exchange them for products and / or experiences.<ref>{{cite web |author=McDonald's |url=https://www.mcdonalds.pt/mlovers |title=McDonalds's - MLovers |publisher=McDonald's |date=2018-01-01 |accessdate=2018-12-21}}</ref>\n\n===Russia===\nIn Russia, McDonald's started selling special burgers with ingredients 100% made in the Russian Federation such as cheese, bread, tomatoes, beef, bacon, lettuce in 2015 under the \"\u0411\u0438\u0444 \u0410-\u043b\u044f \u0420\u0443\u0441 (Beef \u00e0 la Russe)\" name, designed to be an authentic Russian native hamburger.<ref>{{in lang|ru}} [http://mcdonalds.ru/new-products    /\u041c\u0430\u043a\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u0434\u0441 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043d\u043a\u0438 \u041c\u0435\u043d\u044e].  Retrieved 14 February 2015.</ref> McDonald's restaurants in Russia serve chicken wings<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mcdonalds.ru/product/chicken-wings|title=\u041a\u0443\u0440\u0438\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043a\u0440\u044b\u043b\u044b\u0448\u043a\u0438 - \u043a\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0439\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c, \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0430 \u0438 \u0434\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u043a\u0430 \u2013 \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u0434\u0441 \u0432 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438|website=mcdonalds.ru|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref> and shrimps. McZavtrak (McBreakfast) menu offers cheesecake rolls, [[blini]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mcdonalds.ru/product/pancakes|title=\u0411\u043b\u0438\u043d\u044b - \u043a\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0439\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c, \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0430 \u0438 \u0434\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u043a\u0430 \u2013 \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u0434\u0441 \u0432 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438|website=mcdonalds.ru|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref> and the oatmeal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mcdonalds.ru/product/oatmeal|title=\u041e\u0432\u0441\u044f\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043a\u0430\u0448\u0430 - \u043a\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0439\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c, \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0430 \u0438 \u0434\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u043a\u0430 \u2013 \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u0434\u0441 \u0432 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438|website=mcdonalds.ru|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref>\n\n===Serbia===\nIn Serbia, McDonald's offers the McBaguette sandwich. The sandwich is available in two varieties including chicken or ham & cheese.  The restaurants throughout the country offer [[Alcoholic beverage|alcoholic]] and [[energy drinks]]. They also offer orange juice and apple juice for the junior menus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcdonalds.rs/cenovnik/|title=Cenovnik|work=McDonald's|accessdate=8 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160109080450/http://mcdonalds.rs/cenovnik/|archive-date=9 January 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Slovakia===\nIn Slovakia, McDonald's offers the McSyr, a sandwich containing breaded fried cheese and tartar sauce which emulates the Slovak dish [[vypr\u00e1\u017ean\u00fd syr]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcdonalds.sk/sk/novinky/fajnovky.shtml|title=Novinky|work=mcdonalds.sk|accessdate=8 October 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130922161520/http://www.mcdonalds.sk/sk/novinky/fajnovky.shtml|archivedate=22 September 2013}}</ref> It is similar to the Czech McSma\u017e\u00e1k. Also, like in the United Kingdom, McDonald's restaurants in Slovakia serve donuts, which are named McDonuts. McDonuts can be served with either vanilla or chocolate frosting.\n\n===Slovenia===\nThe McCountry sandwich served in Croatia is also available in [[Slovenia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcdonalds.si/ponudba/glavne-jedi/mccountry/ |title=Mcdonalds |publisher=Mcdonalds |date= |accessdate=2015-09-02}}</ref>\n\n===Sweden===\n[[Sweden|Swedish]] McDonald's offer gluten free buns at no extra cost, and occasionally, when there is a time-limited campaign, serve the El Maco. Since 2018 McDonald's in Sweden also serve an all vegan burger called the McVegan. This burger is served with a vegan patty made out of soy, salad, tomatoes, cucumber, onions and vegan McFeast Sauce. Swedish McDonalds's also serve a garlic sauce.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://slymarketing.com/i-thought-i-hated-mcdonalds/ |title=I Thought I Hated McDonalds |publisher=Slymarketing.com |date=2010-08-14 |accessdate=2012-08-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318191652/http://slymarketing.com/i-thought-i-hated-mcdonalds |archive-date=2012-03-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== Switzerland ===\nSwiss McDonalds serve \"The Prime\" Burger, a beef burger with bacon, Gruy\u00e8re cheese and special sauces created by Swiss Chef Ren\u00e9 Schudel. With a current price of CHF 10.90 (approx. USD 12.00) for the burger alone, it is one of the most expensive McDonald's burgers worldwide.\n\n===Ukraine===\nUkraine features the [[McLavash]] sandwich on its menus in the southern part of the country, which is served in flatbread. It has two spicy beef patties, some greens, onion and tomato. The McLavash is also served in some other nearby countries.\n\n===United Kingdom and Ireland===\nBritish and Irish McDonald's serve the Chicken Legend, a chicken breast coated in seasoned batter either spicy tomato salsa, BBQ Sauce or mayonnaise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcdonalds.co.uk/content/ukhome/product_nutrition.chicken.243.chicken-legend-with-bacon-cool-mayo.html |title=Product Nutrition |publisher=McDonalds.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> In June 2011, [[Deli Choices]], a line of sandwich rolls with fillings, was released in the UK. [[Curry]] flavoured sauce is available for McNuggets in British and Irish restaurants. From 2003 to 2005, menus included the [[Quorn (food product)|Quorn]] Premiere, a vegetarian burger with sweet chilli sauce, light [[Hellmann's and Best Foods|Hellmann's]] mayonnaise, tomato, and lettuce in a [[focaccia]] bun. In 2015, McDonald's released a limited edition burger in the Republic of Ireland called the McM\u00f3r. In 2016, this burger was brought back for six weeks. It features Ballymaloe Relish, Charleville cheddar and a potato bun.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcdonalds.ie/iehome/food/full_menu/beef/mc-mor.html |title=McM\u00f3r burger |publisher=McDonalds.ie |date= |accessdate=2016-04-20}}</ref> In 2016, McDonald's launched the brand new BBQ Smokehouse Range of burgers. The two burgers that were launched contained chicken and beef with bacon, cheese and BBQ Sauce.\n\nPast promotional items have included the Apple Pie Sundae, [[Mozzarella sticks|Mozzarella Dippers]], ''Cheese Melt Dippers'', the ''Summer Chorizo Supreme'', BBQ Chicken Premiere with Bacon, the ''1955 burger'', Apple and Blackberry Pie and the ''Festive Pie'', with [[mincemeat]] and [[custard]]. A series of burgers intending to represent various American locales has been released under the ''Great Taste of America'' range. These burgers have represented New York City, Chicago, [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]], [[Texas]], [[Arizona]], Miami, California and [[New Orleans]]. Not all of these burgers resemble their respective local cuisines.<ref>{{cite news |title=McDonald's Introduces the UK to Incorrect Tastes of America |last=Wheeler |first=Robin |url=http://blogs.riverfronttimes.com/gutcheck/2011/06/mcdonalds_introduces_the_uk_to.php |newspaper=[[The Riverfront Times]] |date=6 June 2011 |accessdate=5 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120527012859/http://blogs.riverfronttimes.com/gutcheck/2011/06/mcdonalds_introduces_the_uk_to.php |archive-date=2012-05-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref> British and Irish McDonald's also released a series of burgers representing several different countries in the world. These have included Australia, South Africa, Canada and Mexico. Several Summer and Winter menus have been launched. Also, McDonald's has launched several kinds of McFlurrys over the years, such as [[Cornetto (ice cream)|Cornetto]], [[Cadbury]] brands like Dairy Milk (which is available all year around) and the [[Creme Egg]], which is only available around [[Easter]].\n\nIn 2019 McDonald's released a limited-time edition of the Big Mac called the ''Grand Big Mac Bacon'', which is essentially a larger Big Mac with added bacon.<ref>{{cite web|title=Grand Big Mac Bacon|date=2019-01-28|accessdate=2019-01-31|url=https://www.mcdonalds.com/gb/en-gb/product/grand-big-mac-bacon.html}}</ref>\n\nMcDonald's UK also offers a range of premium burgers known as the ''Signature Collection'', consisting of three burgers: ''The Classic'', ''The Spicy'' and ''The BBQ''. Each comes with a thicker patty made from higher quality beef which takes longer to cook and is served on a brioche bun.\n\n==North America==\n===Canada===\n{{Main|McDonald's Canada}}\nFrench fries may be substituted with McDonald's version of [[poutine]]. Previously, McDonald's poutine was available widely only in Francophone Canada (Quebec and parts of New Brunswick) and available elsewhere on a more limited basis; however, in December 2013, McDonald's formally announced the nationwide availability of poutine at all of its Canadian restaurants, due to popular demand.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/mcdonald-s-poutine-hitting-menus-across-canada-1.2454323 \"McDonald's poutine hitting menus across Canada\"], CBC News, 06 December 2013.</ref> Quebec also saw the release of the limited-time 1967 Burger, commemorating Canada's first McDonald's franchise. Deli Choices were introduced throughout Canada in 2006. Unique to Canadian McDonald's locations is the McMini, miniature sandwiches with grilled or crispy chicken; flavors include [[Pesto]] Chicken (later replaced by Zesty [[Mango]]) and Spicy Thai.<ref>{{cite web|author=SirJman |url=http://www.travellingmcds.com/2011/11/mcmini-thai-chilli-chicken-and-pesto.html |title=McDonald's Around the World: Chicken McMini Thai Chilli and Pesto \u2013 Lasalle, Canada \u2013 May 2010 |publisher=Travellingmcds.com |date=2011-11-05 |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> As in the United States, the McRib periodically appears on the menu for limited runs.  The crispy chicken patty used in the McChicken sandwich sold in Canada uses both white and dark meat \u2013 it is essentially the same size and taste as the original McChicken that first appeared in the US in 1980.\n\nSeasonal items previously available in McDonald's in Canada include the McLobster, a [[lobster roll]], available in the [[Maritime Provinces]], called ''McHomard'' in French.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-biz-mcdonalds-mchomard-canada,0,4348743.photo | work=Chicago Tribune | title=McHomard \u2013 Canada}}</ref> Regionally a blueberry-shortbread McFlurry is also available.  Discontinued items in Canadian McDonald's include pizzas, including a [[calzone]]-style \"McPizza.\"\nThe McFlurry Originated in New Brunswick.\n\n===Mexico===\nMexican McDonald's locations do not serve fish, except during the period of Lent. Special items at these locations have included the Flaming Hot [[Doritos]] Quarter Pounder and the BBQ Double Burger. For breakfast, Mexican McDonald's locations serve the McMollete, which is made on an English muffin spread with beans, topped with a slice of melted cheese and pico de gallo.<ref name=johnson>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/mcdonalds-caters-to-local-palettes-2011-1?op=1|accessdate=3 August 2012|title=Check out the awesome meals you can buy at McDonald's around the world|author=Johnson, Robert|date=22 January 2011|work=Business Insider}}</ref> Mexican locations also serve a version of the McSkillet burrito known as the \"McBurrito\".\n\n===United States===\nMcDonald's restaurants in the United States of America offer various types of [[shellfish]] dishes on a regional basis, such as seasonal [[lobster]] rolls in [[New England]] and [[crab cakes]] in the [[Mid-Atlantic states]]. Parts of the [[Upper Midwest]] sell [[Johnsonville Foods|Johnsonville Brats]], a toasted hot dog bun with a Johnsonville [[bratwurst]] topped with spicy mustard and onions. Other regional variations include the [[Texas]] Homestyle Burger, and traditional [[Cuisine of the Southern United States|Southern]] breakfast items, such as a [[country ham]] biscuit and [[biscuits and gravy]].  Locations in the Southwest regularly offer burgers topped with [[New Mexico chile]].\n\nHawaii locations offer [[saimin]] on their regular menu,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tastyislandhawaii.com/2010/06/26/mcdonalds-saimin/ |title=McDonald\u2019s Saimin &#124; The Tasty Island |publisher=Tastyislandhawaii.com |date=2010-06-26 |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> and include [[Spam (food)|Spam]], [[lingui\u00e7a|Portuguese sausage]] and [[rice]] as a breakfast option. Pineapple and taro pies, as regularly sold in some Asian countries, have been occasionally offered on the regular menu, along with [[haupia]] pies; pineapple is also sometimes available as a topping on burgers. In [[Waikiki]] locations, small trays of pineapple can be ordered as a side dish. Except for saimin, Hawaiian and selected Asian specialty items can also be found in McDonald's in the US territories of [[Guam]] and the [[Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands|Northern Mariana Islands]]. During Easter time, Hawaii, Guam and the CNMI all feature the Double Filet-O-Fish meal due to having a heavy concentration of Catholics (mostly people who immigrated from the Philippines) in that region.\n\n====Puerto Rico====\nUnlike Mexico, several Puerto Rican McDonald's restaurants serve fish products, although fish is not listed on McDonald's Puerto Rico's official website. Puerto Rican restaurants also serve the McCriollo (with eggs and cheese) for breakfast. Criollo is a Puerto Rican bread, like a baguette, but bigger and softer. Basically, the McCriollo is a sandwich with ham, cheese, and egg on a Criollo roll.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sandwichreviews.com/2010/06/mccriollo-puerto-rican-egg-mcmuffin.html |title=It's What's Between: McCriollo: The Puerto Rican Egg McMuffin |publisher=Sandwichreviews.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref>\n\n==Oceania==\n===Australia===\nA popular Australian McDonald's menu item is the McOz Burger. Previous products have included: Shaker Fries, similar to Japan's Shaka Shaka Chicken, and has had many variants of seasoning ranging from Cheeseburger, Big Mac and Spicy; a [[BLT]]; the Mc[[Beefsteak]], promoted by [[country music]] singer [[Lee Kernaghan]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PL3WCXJOpv4 |title=McDonalds Commercial \u2013 McBeefsteak |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> the Big [[Kahuna]] Burger, served with pineapple; the Romano Burger, a chicken patty with Italian sauce and mozzarella served on an herbed focaccia bun; the [[Tandoor]]i Burger, a chicken patty with lettuce and mint yogurt sauce served on flatbread; and a [[Chive]] [[Omelette]] Roll.\n\nCurrent products have included: Chicken Mcbites, Classic Angus and Aussie BBQ Angus.\n\nEvery so often (typically once a year) the McOz is sold for a limited time.  The McOz is a quarter-pounder burger with lettuce, tomato, cheese, mustard, ketchup and the so-called Australian ingredients of [[beetroot]] and cooked onion served on a sesame seed bun.\n\nThe El Maco burger, offered in other markets, was released for a limited time offer last on the 27th of November 2019. These burgers launch alongside Mozzarella Sticks served with El Maco Salsa and an El Maco variant Shaker Fries.\n\n===New Zealand===\n{{Main|McDonald's New Zealand}}\n[[File:McDonald's Kiwiburger.jpg|thumb|200px|Kiwiburger]]\nMany McDonald's menu items in New Zealand are similar to those in Australia. Some unique items include the [[Kiwiburger]], a beef patty with McMuffin egg, tomato, lettuce, cheese, onion, beetroot, ketchup, and mustard.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bestadsontv.com/ad/38826/McDonalds-Kiwiburger |title=TV ad: McDonald's: Kiwiburger |publisher=Bestadsontv.com |date=2011-08-19 |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> In 2011, a special \"Kiwi Menu\" was featured to promote the country's hosting of the [[2011 Rugby World Cup]].\n\nIn April 2012, McDonald's re-released the El Maco, a variant of the product of the same name offered in other markets, such as Scandinavia. El Maco had previously been sold in New Zealand in the early 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|title=McDonald's NZ (maccasnz) on Twitter|url=https://twitter.com/MaccasNZ/status/189864932047720448|publisher=McDonald's New Zealand, Twitter|accessdate=11 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, the New Zealand affiliate bought out failing local fast food chain [[Georgie Pie]], which based itself around [[meat pie (Australia and New Zealand)|Australian and New Zealand meat pies]]. McDonald's trialed a partial relaunch of the Georgie Pie brand in May 2013 with one pie flavor sold through eleven of its restaurants. In October 2013, the affiliate announced it would expand the sale of Georgie Pie to 107 of its 161 restaurants by the end of 2013.<ref name=\"NZHreturn\">{{cite news|last=Adams|first=Christopher|title=Georgie Pie now to be sold across NZ|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/business/news/article.cfm?c_id=3&objectid=11132811|accessdate=1 October 2013|newspaper=[[New Zealand Herald]]|date=1 October 2013}}</ref> As of January 2017, two pie flavors are available: Steak Mince 'n' Cheese and Bacon 'n' Egg.\n\n==South America==\n===Argentina===\nMcN\u00edfica is served. McDonald's Argentina serves Big Tasty Angus Burger, made with premium Argentinean Angus Beef.\nArgentina is the only country besides Israel in which McDonald's has full kosher locations.<ref name=\"frommers.com\"/> These are the only places in the world where McDonald's burgers are barbecued on charcoal rather than fried.<ref name=oddee>{{cite web|url=http://www.oddee.com/item_96970.aspx |title=10 of the Strangest Mc Donald's Meals \u2013 Oddee.com (mcdonalds meals) |publisher=Oddee.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref>\nCroissants are served for breakfast and afternoon tea.\n\n===Brazil===\n[[File:McVeggie in Brazil 2018 01.jpg|thumb|right|A McVeggie in Brazil]]\nIn [[Brazil]], McDonald's offers the Cheddar McMelt, a beef burger with creamy cheddar cheese and grilled onions, flavored with soy sauce on a whole-wheat bun.\n\nBanana-flavored pies are served in Brazilian McDonald's.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nasr |first=Susan L. |url=http://money.howstuffworks.com/10-items-from-mcdonalds-international-menu9.htm |title=HowStuffWorks \"10 Unusual Items from McDonald's International Menu\" |publisher=Money.howstuffworks.com |date=2009-04-13 |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref>\n\nA vegetarian burger started being available, on a trial basis, on 8 November 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mcdonald's vegetariano: McDonald\u2019s lan\u00e7a in\u00e9dito veggie burger no Brasil {{!}} EXAME |url=https://exame.abril.com.br/marketing/mcdonalds-lanca-veggie-burger-no-brasil/ |accessdate=31 October 2018 |work=exame.abril.com.br |language=pt-BR}}</ref> This followed a trial of a vegan burger in October/November 2017.<ref>{{cite news |title=McDonald\u2019s lan\u00e7a o seu primeiro hamb\u00farguer vegetariano {{!}} EXAME |url=https://exame.abril.com.br/marketing/mcdonalds-primeiro-hamburguer-vegetariano/ |date=9 October 2017 |work=exame.abril.com.br |language=pt-BR}}</ref>\n\n===Chile===\nIn Chile, cheese [[empanada]]s are sold at all McDonald's locations in Chile as side dishes. Also, customers can add [[avocado]] paste to any sandwich, other than the McPalta ([[Chilean Spanish]] for ''McAvocado''),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unitednationsoffood.com/2010/07/chilean-food-nyc/ |title=Chilean Food NYC &#124; United Nations of Food (NYC) |publisher=United Nations of Food |date= |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> whose basis is avocado paste along burger as current '''Cuarto Palta''' (''Avocado Quarter Pounder'')<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4c64uVJl05s |title=McDonald's Chile \u2013 Cuarto Palta  |publisher=YouTube |date=2013-08-16 |accessdate=2013-10-12}}</ref> and '''McWrap Palta with [[Fuze Beverage|Fuze Tea]]''', sliced fried chicken with lettuce, tomatoes and purple onion in a tortilla.\n\nCelebrating the 200-year anniversary of the founding of Chilean republic, in 2010 McDonald's offered '''Combo Bicentenario''',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chile.com/secciones/ver_seccion.php?id=122810 |title=McDonald's pone pebre a Combo Bicentenario |publisher=Chile.com |date=2010-09-04 |accessdate=2013-10-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131015084111/http://www.chile.com/secciones/ver_seccion.php?id=122810 |archivedate=2013-10-15 }}</ref> a beef burger with [[pebre]], a Chilean condiment made of coriander, chopped onion, olive oil, garlic and ground spicy chili pepper, and [[merk\u00e9n]], a smoked chili pepper. Recently, celebrating Chile's 2013 National Day in September, the fast food restaurant served [[empanadas]] de pino<ref>{{cite web|url=https://foursquare.com/stark/checkin/5227c19211d2e9590a1ee0cc?s=dSrQkEnkwdhXSqb8LGpJDTiZcdY&ref=tw |title=desde ma\u00f1ana, vas a poder pedir empanadas de pino en @mcdonalds_cl! |publisher= |date=2013-09-04 |accessdate=2013-10-12}}</ref> (stuffed with beef, olives, onions, raisins, and boiled eggs) as special side dishes.\n\nFor breakfast, McDonald's serves [[croissant]]s, also known in Chile as '''Medialuna''' and local versions of two Chilean sandwiches: '''Barros Jarpa''', whose basis is ham and molten cheese on bread, and '''Lomo Palta''',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mcdonalds.cl/sub-secciones/nutricion/include/img/imgpdf/desayuno.jpg |title=Tabla nutricional de productos McDonald's |publisher=McDonalds.cl |date=2013-05-24 |accessdate=2013-10-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014114559/http://www.mcdonalds.cl/sub-secciones/nutricion/include/img/imgpdf/desayuno.jpg |archivedate=2013-10-14 }}</ref> an avocado paste along a slice pork.\n\n===Colombia===\nColombian McDonald's restaurants serve the McCriollo breakfast combo, which includes a sausage patty, two traditional Colombian [[arepa]]s, scrambled eggs and sweetcorn, a hashbrown, coffee, butter, and [[Fruit preserves|jam]].<ref>{{cite web|author=SirJman |url=http://travellingmcds.blogspot.com/2011/11/mccriollo-breakfast-bogota-colombia.html |title=McDonald's Around the World: McCriollo Breakfast \u2013 Bogota Colombia \u2013 March 2011 |publisher=Travellingmcds.blogspot.com |date=2011-11-29 |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref>\n\n===Ecuador===\nIn [[Ecuador]], McDonald's started selling cheese empanadas, burgers with cheese sausage or guacamole, blackberry sundae and nuggets with spicy sausage in 2012 under the \"Nuestros sabores\" campaign, aimed at providing a more local cuisine.<ref>{{in lang|es}} [http://www.elemprendedor.ec/mcdonalds-empanadas-de-queso/ La cadena de comida r\u00e1pida pretende ampliar su oferta insertando un men\u00fa de \u201cgastronom\u00eda ecuatoriana\u201d]. Retrieved 1 July 2013.</ref>\n\n===Peru===\nIn Peru, McDonald's offers [[Aj\u00ed dulce|aj\u00ed]], a spicy sauce made from peppers, as a condiment.<ref name=really>{{cite web |url=http://www.ireallylikefood.com/728110091/mcdonald%E2%80%99s-around-the-world--menu-items-you-may-not-know-so-well/ |title=McDonald\u2019s Around the World: Menu Items You May Not Know So Well |publisher=ireallylikefood |date=2010-06-02 |accessdate=2012-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120701083418/http://www.ireallylikefood.com/728110091/mcdonald%E2%80%99s-around-the-world--menu-items-you-may-not-know-so-well/ |archivedate=2012-07-01 }}</ref> Peruvian locations also serve Pollo Crujiente (\"crunchy chicken\"), which is fried chicken served in a bucket, and [[Inca Kola]]. Now, McDonald's offers \"Peruvian Foods\" and blackberry Sundae.\n\n===Venezuela===\nIn Venezuela, McDonald's offers arepas, [[empanadas]] for breakfast; these are traditional breakfast foods. Venezuelan locations have also served fried [[Cassava|yuca]] sticks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m3190/is_15_39/ai_n13649042/pg_3/ |title=Studying McDonald's abroad: overseas branches merge regional preferences, corporate directives |publisher=Findarticles.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref>\n\n===Dominican Republic===\nIn DR,McDonald's sells the same food as the US and Canada. It sells hamburgers, fries, nuggets (chicken flavored), and soda.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[24 hour McDelivery|McDelivery]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n; Videos\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AT-E_eMiwgk|title=Why McDonald's Failed In Iceland|publisher=[[CNBC]]|date=2019-02-19}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l9pthhpd7So|title=Why McDonald\u2019s Flopped In Vietnam|publisher=[[CNBC]]|date=2018-09-18}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kpHeXMbIy2s|title=Why Is McDonald's Struggling In The Philippines? Jollibee|publisher=[[CNBC]]|date=2018-11-20}}\n{{McDonald's}}\n\n[[Category:Lists by country]]\n[[Category:McDonald's foods| International]]\n", "name_user": "2601:2c6:4600:3440:d1b6:d2a1:1924:5146", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eFrance)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_availability_of_McDonald%27s_products"}
{"title_page": "American Airlines", "text_new": "{{About|the airline known as American Airlines|its parent company|American Airlines Group|a list of airlines of the United States|List of airlines of the United States}}\n{{short description|Major airline of the United States}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox airline\n| airline                  = American Airlines, Inc.\n| image                    = American Airlines logo 2013.svg\n| image_size               = 300px\n| alt                      = American Airlines logo\n| caption                  = \n| IATA                     = AA<ref name=\"chavprofile\">{{cite web | url=http://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/airline/AA | title=American Airlines | website=[[ch-aviation]] | accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref>\n| ICAO                     = AAL<ref name=\"chavprofile\" />\n| callsign                 = AMERICAN<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.faa.gov/documentLibrary/media/Order/7340_2F_Bsc_w_Chgs_1-3_Contractions.pdf | title=7340.2F with Change 1 and Change 2 and Change 3 | website=[[Federal Aviation Administration]] | date=October 15, 2015 | accessdate=December 27, 2016 | pages=3\u20131\u201318}}</ref>\n| founded                  = {{Start date and age|1926|4|15}} (earliest predecessor airline as American Airways, Inc.)<br />[[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], [[United States]]<ref name=\"foundation\">{{cite web |url=https://www.aa.com/i18n/customer-service/about-us/history-of-american-airlines.jsp|title=History of American Airlines |date=2015 |publisher=American Airlines Inc. |accessdate=June 30, 2015}}</ref>\n| commenced                = {{Start date|1936|6|25}}<ref name=\"foundation\" />\n| ceased                   = \n| aoc                      = AALA025A<ref name=faa_aoc>{{cite web |url=http://av-info.faa.gov/detail.asp?DSGN_CODE=AALA&OPER_FAR=121&OPER_NAME=AMERICAN+AIRLINES+INC+AND%2FOR+US+AIRWAYS+INC|title=Airline Certificate Information \u2013 Detail View |date=May 12, 2015 |website=av-info.faa.gov |publisher=Federal Aviation Administration |quote=Certificate Number AALA025A}}</ref>\n| hubs                     = *[[Charlotte Douglas International Airport|Charlotte]]\n*[[O'Hare International Airport|Chicago\u2013O'Hare]]\n*[[Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport|Dallas/Fort Worth]]\n*[[Los Angeles International Airport|Los Angeles]]\n*[[Miami International Airport|Miami]]\n*[[John F. Kennedy International Airport|New York\u2013JFK]]\n*[[LaGuardia Airport|New York\u2013LaGuardia]]\n*[[Philadelphia International Airport|Philadelphia]]\n*[[Phoenix Sky Harbor International Airport|Phoenix\u2013Sky Harbor]]\n*[[Ronald Reagan Washington National Airport|Washington\u2013National]]\n| frequent_flyer           = [[AAdvantage]]\n| alliance                 = [[Oneworld]]\n| fleet_size               = [[American Airlines fleet|945]] (mainline)<ref name=\"Fleet\">{{cite web|title=American Airlines Fleet Details and History|url=https://www.planespotters.net/airline/American-Airlines|website=Planespotters.net|date=September 4, 2019|accessdate=September 4, 2019}}</ref>\n| destinations             = [[American Airlines destinations|350]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aa.com/i18n/customer-service/about-us/american-airlines-group.jsp |title=About us |publisher=American Airlines |accessdate=November 29, 2017}}</ref>\n| parent                   = [[American Airlines Group]]\n| traded_as                = {{NASDAQ|AAL}}\n| ISIN                     = \n| headquarters             = [[Fort Worth, Texas]], [[United States]]\n| key_people               = *[[Doug Parker]] ([[Chairman]] & [[CEO]])\n*Robert Isom ([[President (corporate title)|President]])\n*Elise Eberwein ([[Executive Vice President]], People and Communications)\n*Stephen Johnson ([[Executive Vice President]], Corporate Affairs)\n*Derek Kerr ([[Executive Vice President]] and [[CFO]])\n*Maya Leibman ([[Executive Vice President]] and [[Chief Information Officer]])<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aa.com/i18n/customer-service/about-us/leadership-bios/leadership-bios.jsp |title=Leadership bios |publisher=American Airlines |accessdate=August 7, 2017}}</ref>\n| revenue                  = See [[American Airlines Group|parent]]\n| operating_income         = See [[American Airlines Group|parent]]\n| net_income               = See [[American Airlines Group|parent]]\n| assets                   = See [[American Airlines Group|parent]]\n| equity                   = See [[American Airlines Group|parent]]\n| num_employees            = 128,900(2019) {{cn|date=February 2020}}\n| website                  = {{URL|www.aa.com}}\n| notes                    = \n}}\n\n'''American Airlines, Inc.''' ('''AA''') is a [[major airlines of the United States|major American airline]] headquartered in [[Fort Worth, Texas]], within the [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth metroplex]]. It is the [[World's largest airlines|world's largest airline]] when measured by fleet size, scheduled passengers carried, and revenue passenger mile. American, together with its regional partners, operates an extensive international and domestic network with almost 6,800 flights per day to nearly 350 destinations in more than 50 countries.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aa.com/i18n/customer-service/about-us/american-airlines-group.jsp|title=American Airlines Group \u2212 About us \u2212 American Airlines|last=|first=|date=|website=Aa.com|accessdate=February 22, 2018}}</ref> American Airlines is a founding member of the [[Oneworld]] alliance, the third-largest airline alliance in the world. Regional service is operated by independent and subsidiary carriers under the brand name [[American Eagle (airline brand)|American Eagle]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/american-air-signs-deal-contract-flying-skywest-165209289.html?_esi=1 |title=American Air signs deal to contract out some flying to SkyWest |work=The Associated|publisher=Yahoo! News |date=September 12, 2012 |accessdate=October 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAmerican Airlines and American Eagle operate out of ten hubs, with [[Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport|Dallas/Fort Worth]] being its largest; handling more than 200 million passengers annually with an average of more than 500,000 passengers daily. American operates its primary maintenance base in [[Tulsa International Airport|Tulsa]] in addition to the maintenance locations at its hubs. As of 2019, the company employs nearly 130,000 people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=1579389|title=Company Overview of American Airlines, Inc.|work=Bloomberg|accessdate=June 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{Main|History of American Airlines}}\n\n[[File:N834AA taking off from Sydney Airport July 2018.jpg|thumb|An American Airlines [[Boeing 787-9]] taking off from [[Sydney Airport]] in July 2018]]\n\nAmerican Airlines was started in 1930 via a union of more than eighty small airlines.<ref name=ap>{{cite news|last=Koenig|first=David|title=American Airlines parent seeks Ch. 11 protection|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5gqSFH2Ou81RHegJYXJtAeU9CkyhA?docId=c6952820f230470692fc37e00d9d2d36 |accessdate=December 7, 2011 |newspaper=Google News |date= November 29, 2011|agency=Associated Press|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111204004443/https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5gqSFH2Ou81RHegJYXJtAeU9CkyhA?docId=c6952820f230470692fc37e00d9d2d36|archivedate=December 4, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe two organizations from which American Airlines was originated were [[Robertson Aircraft Corporation]] and [[Colonial Air Transport]].  The former was first created in Missouri in 1921, with both being merged in 1929 into holding company [[The Aviation Corporation]].  This, in turn, was made in 1930 into an operating company and rebranded as American Airways.  In 1934, when new laws and attrition of mail contracts forced many airlines to reorganize, the corporation redid its routes into a connected system and was renamed American Airlines.  Between 1970 and 2000, the company grew into being an international carrier, purchasing [[Trans World Airlines]] in 2001.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://money.cnn.com/2001/01/10/deals/amr_twa/|title=TWA to be bought by American - Jan. 10, 2001|website=money.cnn.com|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref>\n\nAmerican had a direct role in the development of the [[DC-3]], which resulted from a marathon telephone call from American Airlines CEO [[C. R. Smith]] to Donald Douglas, when Smith persuaded a reluctant Douglas to design a sleeper aircraft based on the [[DC-2]] to replace American's [[Curtiss T-32 Condor II|Curtiss Condor II]] biplanes. (The existing DC-2's cabin was {{convert|66|in|m}} wide, too narrow for side-by-side berths.) Douglas agreed to go ahead with development only after Smith informed him of American's intention to purchase 20 aircraft. The prototype DST ([[Douglas Sleeper Transport]]) first flew on December 17, 1935, (the 32nd anniversary of the [[Wright Brothers]]' flight at Kitty Hawk). Its cabin was {{convert|92|in|m|abbr=on}} wide, and a version with 21 seats instead of the 14\u201316 sleeping berths of the DST was given the designation DC-3. There was no prototype DC-3; the first DC-3 built followed seven DSTs off the production line and was delivered to American Airlines.<ref>Pearcy, Arthur. ''Douglas DC-3 Survivors, Volume 1''. Bourne End, Bucks, UK: Aston Publications, 1987. {{ISBN|0-946627-13-4}}, p. 17</ref> American Airlines inaugurated passenger service on June 26, 1936, with simultaneous flights from [[Newark, New Jersey]], and [[Chicago]], Illinois.<ref>Holden, Henry. [http://www.dc3history.org/douglasdc3.html \"DC-3 History\"]. dc3history.org. Retrieved October 7, 2010.</ref>\n\nIn 2011, due to a downturn in the airline industry, American Airlines' parent company [[AMR Corporation]] filed for bankruptcy protection.  In 2013, American Airlines merged with [[US Airways]] but kept the American Airlines name, as it was the better-recognized brand internationally; the combination of the two airlines resulted in the creation of the largest airline in the United States, and ultimately the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/American-Airlines|title=American Airlines \u2013 American company|website=Britannica.com}}</ref>\n\n==Destinations and hubs==\n===Destinations===\n{{Main|List of American Airlines destinations}}\nAs of April 2020, American Airlines flies to [[List of American Airlines destinations|95 domestic destinations and 95 international destinations in 55 countries in five continents]], soon to be six when American launches their flight to Casablanca from Philadelphia in 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://aa.fltmaps.com/en|title=American Airlines Map|website=aa.fltmaps.com|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref>{{fv|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Hubs===\nAmerican currently operates ten hubs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.aa.com/multimedia/default.aspx#factsheets|title=Newsroom \u2013 Multimedia \u2013 American Airlines Group, Inc|website=news.aa.com}}</ref>\n* [[Charlotte Douglas International Airport|Charlotte]] \u2013 Inherited from the merger with [[US Airways]], Charlotte is American's hub for the Southeast and secondary hub to the Caribbean. It also serves as one of American's larger gateways to Europe.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite web|url=http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/clt |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224081146/http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/clt |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 24, 2015 |title=CLT :: American Airlines Newsroom |website=aa.com |df= }}</ref> About 42 million passengers fly through CLT on American every year, or about 115,000 people per day.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\" /> American has about 91% of the market share at CLT.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\" /> \n* [[O'Hare International Airport|Chicago\u2013O'Hare]] \u2013 American's hub for the Midwest.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{cite web|url=http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/ord |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224081511/http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/ord |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 24, 2015 |title=ORD :: American Airlines Newsroom |website=aa.com |df= }}</ref> About 28 million passengers fly on American through O'Hare every year, or about 77,000 people per day.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\" /> American has about 35% of the market share at O'Hare, making it the airport's second-largest airline after United.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\" /> \n* [[Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport|Dallas/Fort Worth]] \u2013 American's largest hub for the South.<ref name=\"hub.aa.com\">{{cite web|url=http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/dfw |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224081506/http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/dfw |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 24, 2015 |title=DFW :: American Airlines Newsroom |website=aa.com |df= }}</ref> American currently has about 84% of the market share and flies approximately 57 million passengers through DFW every year, which is about 156,000 people per day, making it the busiest airline at the airport.<ref name=\"hub.aa.com\" /> American's corporate headquarters are also in Fort Worth near the airport.<ref name=\"hub.aa.com\" /> DFW serves as American's primary gateway to Mexico, and secondary gateway to Latin America.<ref name=\"hub.aa.com\" /> <!-- DO NOT CHANGE, PER AMERICAN AIRLINES LARGEST MEXICAN GATEWAY IS DFW NOT PHOENIX, LARGEST LATIN AMERICAN GATEWAY IS MIAMI -->\n* [[Los Angeles International Airport|Los Angeles]] \u2013 American's hub for the West Coast and its transpacific gateway.<ref name=\"aa.com4\">{{cite web|url=http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/lax |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224081300/http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/lax |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 24, 2015 |title=LAX :: American Airlines Newsroom |website=aa.com |df= }}</ref> About 16.5 million passengers fly through LAX on American every year, or about 45,000 people per day.<ref name=\"aa.com4\" /> American has about 19% of the market share at LAX, making it the largest carrier at the airport.<ref name=\"aa.com4\" /> \n* [[Miami International Airport|Miami]] \u2013 American's primary Latin American hub.<ref name=\"aa.com2\">{{cite web|url=http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/mia |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224081305/http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/mia |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 24, 2015 |title=MIA :: American Airlines Newsroom |website=Hub.aa.com |accessdate=September 17, 2016 |df= }}</ref> About 30 million passengers fly through MIA every year on American, which is about 79,000 people per day.<ref name=\"aa.com2\" /> American has about 68% of the market share at Miami International, making it the largest airline at the airport.<ref name=\"aa.com2\" />\n* [[John F. Kennedy International Airport|New York\u2013JFK]] \u2013 American's secondary transatlantic hub.<ref name=\"aa.com5\">{{cite web|url=http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/jfk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150920003944/http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/jfk|url-status=dead|archive-date=September 20, 2015|title=JFK :: American Airlines Newsroom|website=aa.com}}</ref> About 7 million passengers fly through JFK on American every year, or about 19,000 people per day.<ref name=\"aa.com5\" /> American has about 12% of the market share at JFK, making it the third-largest carrier at the airport behind Delta and JetBlue.<ref name=\"aa.com5\" /> JFK also serves as a major connecting point for other [[Oneworld]] carriers in addition to their flights at the airport. \n* [[LaGuardia Airport|New York\u2013LaGuardia]] \u2013 American's second New York hub.<ref name=\"aa.com6\">{{cite web|url=http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/lga|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150920003951/http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/lga|url-status=dead|archive-date=September 20, 2015|title=LGA :: American Airlines Newsroom|website=aa.com}}</ref> About 8.5 million passengers fly through LGA on American every year, or about 23,000 people per day.<ref name=\"aa.com6\" /> The airport also serves as a base for [[American Airlines Shuttle]]. American has about 27% of the market share at LGA, and is the second-largest carrier behind Delta.<ref name=\"aa.com6\" />\n* [[Philadelphia International Airport|Philadelphia]] \u2013 Inherited from the merger with [[US Airways]], Philadelphia is American's primary transatlantic hub.<ref name=\"aa.com\">{{cite web|url=http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/phl |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224081516/http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/phl |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 24, 2015 |title=PHL :: American Airlines Newsroom |website=aa.com |df= }}</ref> American flies approximately 20.5 million passengers a year through PHL, which is about 56,000 people per day.<ref name=\"aa.com\" /> American has about 70% of the market share at PHL, making it the airport's largest airline.<ref name=\"aa.com\" />\n* [[Phoenix Sky Harbor International Airport|Phoenix\u2013Sky Harbor]] \u2013 Inherited from the merger with [[US Airways]],  Phoenix is American's western hub.<ref name=\"aa.com1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dallasnews.com/business/airline-industry/20130215-loss-of-a-corporate-headquarters-may-cost-phoenix-jobs-prestige.ece|title=Loss of a corporate headquarters may cost Phoenix jobs, prestige|website=Dallasnews.com|accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref> American flies approximately 20 million passengers a year through PHX, which is about 55,000 people per day.<ref name=\"aa.com1\" /> Currently American has about 46% of the market share at PHX, making it the airport's largest airline.<ref name=\"aa.com1\" />\n* [[Ronald Reagan Washington National Airport|Washington\u2013National]] \u2013 Inherited from the merger with [[US Airways]], Washington-National is American's hub for the capital of the United States. The airport also serves as a base for [[American Airlines Shuttle]].<ref name=\"aa.com3\">{{cite web|url=http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/2014-dca |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224081501/http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/2014-dca |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 24, 2015 |title=DCA :: American Airlines Newsroom |website=aa.com |df= }}</ref> About 12 million passengers fly through DCA on American every year, or about 33,000 people per day.<ref name=\"aa.com3\" /> American has about 49% of the market share at DCA, making it the largest carrier at the airport.<ref name=\"aa.com3\" />\n\n===Tulsa maintenance base===\n[[Tulsa International Airport]] houses American Airline's largest maintenance and repair operations facility and employs 5500 people with the majority as licensed aircraft and jet engine mechanics. The base performs maintenance and engineering work for the airline's fleet of [[Airbus A320]], [[Boeing 757]], [[Boeing 787]], [[Boeing 737]], and some [[Boeing 767]] planes.{{fact|date=March 2020}} \n\nAmerican plans to retire its fleet of 17 [[Boeing 767]] planes in May 2020 and 34 [[Boeing 757]] planes by post-summer 2021 due to the impact of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] on commercial air travel.{{fact|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Alliance and codeshare agreements==\nAmerican Airlines is a member of the [[Oneworld]] alliance and has [[codeshare agreement|codeshares]] with the following airlines:<ref name=\"CAPA AA profile\">{{cite web|url=http://centreforaviation.com/profiles/airlines/american-airlines-aa|title=Profile on American Airlines|website=CAPA|publisher=Centre for Aviation|access-date=October 28, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161028201006/http://centreforaviation.com/profiles/airlines/american-airlines-aa|archive-date=October 28, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n{{Div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Air Tahiti Nui]]\n* [[Alaska Airlines]]\n* [[British Airways]]\n* [[Cape Air]]\n* [[Caribbean Airlines]]\n* [[Cathay Dragon]]<ref>https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/285360/american-airlines-begins-cathay-dragon-codeshares-from-july-2019/</ref>\n* [[Cathay Pacific]]\n* [[China Southern Airlines]]\n* [[El Al]]\n* [[Fiji Airways]]\n* [[Finnair]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Liu |first1=Jim |title=Finnair adds American Airlines codeshare routes via Los Angeles in S19 |url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/281759/finnair-adds-american-airlines-codeshare-routes-via-los-angeles-in-s19/ |accessdate=November 30, 2018 |work=Routesonline |date=November 29, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Gol Transportes A\u00e9reos]] <ref>https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/289431/american-airlines-gol-begins-codeshare-service-from-mid-feb-2020/</ref>\n* [[Hainan Airlines]]\n* [[Hawaiian Airlines]]\n* [[Iberia (airline)|Iberia]]\n* [[Interjet]]\n* [[Japan Airlines]]\n* [[Jetstar Airways]]\n* [[Jetstar Japan]]\n* [[Korean Air]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/american-airlines-and-korean-air-announce-codeshare-agreement|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150302142451/http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/american-airlines-and-korean-air-announce-codeshare-agreement|url-status=dead|archive-date=March 2, 2015|title=American Airlines And Korean Air Announce Codeshare Agreement :: American Airlines Newsroom|website=Hub.aa.com|accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Malaysia Airlines]]\n* [[Qantas]]\n* [[Qatar Airways]]<ref>[https://onemileatatime.com/american-airlines-qatar-airways-partnership/ American Airlines & Qatar Airways Announce Strategic Partnership]</ref>\n* [[Royal Jordanian]]\n* [[Seaborne Airlines]]\n* [[SriLankan Airlines]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Joint ventures===\nIn addition to the above codeshares, American Airlines has entered into [[joint venture]]s with the following airlines:<ref name=\"AA-BA-IB\">{{cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704689804575535904042433736 | title= BA, Iberia, American Launch Venture, Add Routes | newspaper=The Wall Street Journal | date=October 7, 2010 | first=Mike |last= Esterl }}</ref><ref name=\"AMR-JAL\">{{cite news | url= https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704530204576235060492562894 | title= AMR, JAL Forge a Partnership | newspaper=The Wall Street Journal | date=April 1, 2011 | first=Timothy W. |last=Martin}}</ref><ref name=\"QF-AA\">{{cite news | url=http://www.ausbt.com.au/us-govt-greenlights-qantas-american-airlines-joint-venture | title= US govt greenlights Qantas & American Airlines joint venture | first=John |last=Walton | newspaper=Australian Business Traveller | date=November 11, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[British Airways]]\n* [[Finnair]]\n* [[Iberia (airline)|Iberia]]\n* [[Japan Airlines]]\n* [[Qantas]]\n\n== Fleet ==\n{{Main|American Airlines fleet}}\n[[File:Boeing 777-323(ER) American Airlines N718AN, LHR London, England (Heathrow Airport), United Kingdom PP1367675556.jpg|thumb|American Airlines [[Boeing 777-300ER]] landing at [[London Heathrow Airport]] in 2013.]]\nAs of November 2019, American Airlines operates 932 [[Airbus]], [[Boeing]], and [[Embraer]] aircraft. It is the largest commercial fleet in the world.<ref name=\"Fleet\"/>\n\nOver 80% of American's aircraft are narrow-bodies, mainly [[Airbus A320 series]] and the [[Boeing 737-800]]. It is the largest [[List of Airbus A320 family operators#Airline operators|A320 series aircraft operator]] in the world, as well as the largest operator of the [[A319]] and [[A321]] variants. It is the fourth-largest [[List of Boeing 737 operators#United States|operator of 737 family aircraft]] and second-largest operator of the 737-800 variant. It also currently operates the Boeing [[757-200]] and [[Embraer 190]], though these are slated for retirement and replacement by the [[Boeing 737 MAX|Boeing 737 MAX 8]] and the [[A320 family|Airbus A320 family]] in coming years.<ref name=\"Fleet\"/>\n\nAmerican's wide-body aircraft are a mix of Boeing and Airbus airliners. It is the third-largest [[List of Boeing 787 operators#Current airline operators|operator of the Boeing 787 series]] and the sixth-largest [[List of Boeing 777 operators#Orders and deliveries|operator of the Boeing 777 series]]. It also operates [[Boeing 767]] and [[Airbus A330]] aircraft, with most slated for retirement in favor of additional [[Boeing 787]] aircraft.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://theflight.info/american_airlines/ | title = American Airlines aircraft fleet | archive-url = https://archive.today/20181003141132/http://theflight.info/american_airlines/ | archive-date = October 3, 2018 | url-status=live | access-date = May 13, 2019 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nAmerican Airlines exclusively ordered Boeing aircraft throughout the 2000s.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ruiz |first1=Rebecca |title=Boeing Was 'Go, Go, Go' to Beat Airbus With the 737 Max |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/23/business/boeing-737-max-crash.html |accessdate=27 November 2019 |work=New York Times |date=23 March 2019}}</ref> This strategy shifted on July 20, 2011, when American announced the largest combined aircraft order in history for 460 narrow-body jets including 260 [[Airbus A320|Airbus 320 Series]].<ref>{{cite press release |url= http://news.aa.com/press-releases/press-release-details/2011/AMR-Corporation-Announces-Largest-Aircraft-Order-in-History-With-Boeing-and-Airbus/default.aspx |title= AMR Corporation Announces Largest Aircraft Order in History With Boeing and Airbus |publisher= American Airlines |date= July 20, 2011}}</ref> Additional Airbus aircraft joined the fleet in 2013 upon merger with US Airways, which operated Airbus aircraft almost exclusively.<ref>{{cite web |title=US Airways Fleet |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/US_Airways_fleet |website=wikipedia.org |accessdate=27 November 2019}}</ref>{{Circular reference|date=December 2019}}\n\n== Cabins ==\n{{multiple issues|section=yes\n|{{more citations needed section|date=August 2019}}\n{{third-party|section|date=August 2019}}\n{{unreliable sources section|date=August 2019}}\n}}\n{{multiple image\n|direction = vertical\n|align = right\n|width1 = 220\n|image1 = American A321T First Class (11424575675).jpg\n|caption1 =\n|width2 = 220\n|image2 = American A321T business class (11424746783).jpg\n|caption2 = First and business class seats on an [[Airbus 321|A321]] Transcontinental (top and bottom, respectively)\n}}\n\n;Flagship First\n\nFlagship First is American's international First Class product. It is offered only on the airline's Boeing 777-300ERs. The seats are fully lie-flat and offer direct aisle access in a 1-2-1 reverse herringbone configuration. As with the airline's other premium cabins, Flagship First offers wider food and beverage options, larger seats, and more amenities at certain airports, e.g., lounge access.<ref>{{cite web |title=Flagship First \u2013 International |url=https://www.aa.com/i18n/travel-info/experience/seats/flagship-first-international.jsp |website=American Airlines Website |accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n;Flagship Business\n\nFlagship Business is a premium cabin offered on some Boeing 757-200s and all Airbus A330-200s, Airbus A330-300s, Boeing 767-300ERs, Boeing 777-200ERs, Boeing 777-300ERs, Boeing 787-8s, and Boeing 787-9s. All Flagship Business seats are fully lie-flat.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aa.com/i18n/travel-info/experience/seats/flagship-business-international.jsp|title=Flagship Business - International|publisher=American Airlines|accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref>{{Better source|date=January 2019}} Only the Boeing 757-200 does not offer direct aisle access from each seat.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\n;\n;Transcontinental\nAmerican has dedicated 17 [[Airbus A321]]s (A321T) in its fleet for the specific use of flying transcontinental routes between [[John F. Kennedy International Airport|New York JFK]] and [[Los Angeles International Airport|Los Angeles]], New York JFK and [[San Francisco International Airport|San Francisco]], and [[Logan International Airport|Boston]] and Los Angeles. These aircraft offer two premium cabins, Flagship First and Flagship Business, which are unique among domestic mainline aircraft in American's fleet. Both cabins feature lie-flat seats; Flagship First also includes direct aisle access from each seat.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\n;Domestic First Class\n\nFirst Class is offered on all domestic mainline aircraft, as well as regional aircraft with more than 50 seats. When such aircraft are used on flights to international destinations including Canada, Mexico, Central America, and the Caribbean, the First Class cabin is branded as Business Class. Seats range from {{convert|19|-|21|in|cm}} in width and have {{convert|37|-|42|in|cm}} of pitch.<ref name=\"tripadvisor\">{{cite web|url=http://www.seatguru.com/airlines/American_Airlines/fleetinfo.php|title=American Airlines Planes and Seat Maps|website=Tripadvisor.com|accessdate=May 24, 2015}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=January 2019}} Dining options include free snacks, beverages, and alcohol on all flights, with three-course meals offered on flights {{convert|900|mi|km}} or longer (some routes under 900 miles also offer meal service).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aa.com/i18n/travelInformation/duringFlight/dining/premium-cabin.jsp|title=First and Business Class Dining|website=Aa.com|accessdate=May 24, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150520212859/http://www.aa.com/i18n/travelInformation/duringFlight/dining/premium-cabin.jsp|archivedate=May 20, 2015|df=}}</ref>{{Better source|date=January 2019}}\n\n;Premium Economy\n\nOn December 9, 2015, American announced a new Premium Economy cabin for most long-haul widebody aircraft. The cabin debuted on the airline's Boeing 787-9s in late 2016 and is also available on Boeing 777-200s and -300s, some Boeing 787-8s, and Airbus A330-200s. Premium Economy seats are wider than seats in Main Cabin (American's economy cabin) and provide more amenities: Premium Economy customers get two free checked bags, priority boarding, and enhanced food and drink service including free alcohol. This product made American Airlines the first U.S. carrier to offer a four-cabin aircraft.<ref name=\"upgrd.com\">{{cite web|url=http://upgrd.com/blogs/doublewidesfly/american-airlines-premium-economy-the-only-north-american-carrier-to-offer-a-4-cabin-aircraft.html|title=American Airlines Premium Economy \u2013 The Only North American Carrier to Offer a 4 Cabin Aircraft|website=upgrd.com}}</ref>{{Better source|date=January 2019}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.baggagecircle.com/knowledge-base/american-airlines-carry-on-baggage-policy-2020-2021/ |title=American Airlines Carry On Baggage Policy 2020-2021 |website=Baggage Circle |language=en |access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\n;Main Cabin Extra\n\nAmerican's economy plus product (not to be confused with premium economy), Main Cabin Extra, is available on most of the mainline fleet and [[American Eagle (airline brand)|American Eagle]] regional aircraft with more than 50 seats. Main Cabin Extra seats include greater pitch than is available in Main Cabin,<ref name=\"tripadvisor\" /> along with free alcoholic beverages.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aa.com/i18n/travel-info/experience/seats/main-cabin-extra.jsp|title=Main Cabin Extra|publisher=American Airlines|accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref>{{Better source|date=January 2019}} American retained Main Cabin Extra when the new Premium Economy product entered service in late 2016.<ref name=\"upgrd.com\" />{{Better source|date=January 2019}}\n\n;Main Cabin\n\nMain Cabin is American's economy product, and is found on all mainline and regional aircraft in its fleet. Seats range from {{convert|17|-|18.5|in|cm}} in width and have {{convert|30|-|32|in|cm}} of pitch.<ref>{{cite web|title=American Airlines planes and seat maps|url=https://www.seatguru.com/airlines/American_Airlines/fleetinfo.php|website=tripadvisor.com|accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=January 2019}}\n\nAmerican Airlines marketed increased legroom in economy class as \"More Room Throughout Coach\", also referred to as \"MRTC\", starting in February 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aa.com/i18n/customer-service/about-us/history-of-american-airlines.jsp |title=History of American Airlines \u2013 About us \u2013 American Airlines |publisher=American Airlines |date= |accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref>{{Better source|date=January 2019}} Two rows of economy class seats were removed on Boeing 737 and McDonnell Douglas MD-80 aircraft.<ref name=\"usatoday30.usatoday.com\">{{cite web|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/travel/news/2004-10-20-more-seats_x.htm |title=USATODAY.com \u2013 American Airlines squeezes passengers in tighter to make money |website=Usatoday30.usatoday.com |date=October 21, 2004 |accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref> Amid financial losses, this scheme was discontinued in 2004.<ref name=\"usatoday30.usatoday.com\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://business.time.com/2012/03/02/american-airlines-offering-more-legroom-for-a-price/|title=American Airlines Offering More Legroom \u2026 For a Price|first=Josh|last=Sanburn|website=Business.time.com}}</ref>\n\nOn some routes, American also offers [[Basic Economy]], the airline's lowest main cabin fare. Basic Economy is located in the main cabin but comes with restrictions. These restrictions include waiting until check-in for a seat assignment, no upgrades or refunds, and boarding in the last group.<ref>{{cite web|title=Basic Economy|url=https://www.aa.com/i18n/travel-info/experience/seats/basic-economy.jsp|website=American Airlines|publisher=American Airlines}}</ref>{{Better source|date=January 2019}}\n\nIn May 2017, American announced it would be adding more seats to some of its Boeing 737 MAX jetliners and reducing overall legroom in the basic economy class. The last three rows will lose {{convert|2|in|cm}}, going from the current {{convert|31|in|cm}} to {{convert|29|in|cm}}. The remainder of the economy cabin will have {{convert|30|in|cm}} of legroom.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ostrower |first=Jon |title=American Airlines is cutting more legroom in economy class |work=[[CNN]] Money |publisher=Cable News Network |date=May 3, 2017|url=https://money.cnn.com/2017/05/02/news/companies/american-airlines-legroom/index.html }}</ref>\n\n== Reward programs ==\n=== AAdvantage ===\n{{Main|AAdvantage}}\nAAdvantage is the [[frequent flyer program]] for American Airlines. It was launched on May 1, 1981, and it remains the largest frequent flyer program with over 67 million members as of 2011. Miles accumulated in the program allow members to redeem tickets, upgrade service class, or obtain free or discounted car rentals, hotel stays, merchandise, or other products and services through partners. The most active members, based on the amount and price of travel booked, are designated AAdvantage Gold, AAdvantage Platinum, AAdvantage Platinum Pro, and AAdvantage Executive Platinum elite members, with privileges such as separate check-in, priority upgrade, and standby processing, or free upgrades. They also receive similar privileges from AA's partner airlines, particularly those in [[oneworld]].<ref>[http://www.aa.com/aa/i18nForward.do?p=/AAdvantage/partners/airlines/oneWorld.jsp#elite oneworld Alliance] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081220083602/http://www.aa.com/aa/i18nForward.do?p=%2FAAdvantage%2Fpartners%2Fairlines%2FoneWorld.jsp#elite |date=December 20, 2008 }}. Aa.com (October 1, 2010). Retrieved on November 4, 2010.</ref>{{Better source|date=January 2019}}\n\nAAdvantage co-branded credit cards are also available and offer other benefits. The cards are issued by CitiCards, a subsidiary of [[Citigroup]], and [[Barclaycard]] in the United States, by [[Butterfield Bank]] and [[Scotiabank]] in the Caribbean, and by [[Banco Santander]] in Brazil.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\nAAdvantage allows one-way redemption, starting at 5,000 miles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aa.com/i18n/disclaimers/aadvantageAllPartnerChart.jsp|title=oneworld and Other Airline Award Chart|last=|first=|date=December 18, 2013|website=Aa.com|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20131218060310/http://www.aa.com/i18n/disclaimers/aadvantageAllPartnerChart.jsp|archivedate=December 18, 2013|url-status=dead|access-date=}}</ref>{{Better source|date=January 2019}}\n\n=== Admirals Club ===\nThe Admirals Club was conceived by AA president C.R. Smith as a marketing promotion shortly after he was made an honorary [[Texas Ranger Division|Texas Ranger]]. Inspired by the [[Kentucky colonel]]s and other [[Title of honor|honorary title]] designations, Smith decided to make particularly valued passengers \"admirals\" of the \"Flagship fleet\" (AA called its aircraft \"Flagships\" at the time).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Li |first1=Lucy |title=Ultimate Guide to Admirals Club |url=http://www.loungebuddy.com/admirals-club-ultimate-guide/ |website=LoungeBuddy |publisher=LoungeBuddy, Inc |accessdate=July 20, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906212847/http://www.loungebuddy.com/admirals-club-ultimate-guide/ |archivedate=September 6, 2015 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>{{Better source|date=January 2019}} The list of Admirals included many celebrities, politicians, and other VIPs, as well as more \"ordinary\" customers who had been particularly loyal to the airline.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\nThere was no physical Admirals Club until shortly after the opening of LaGuardia Airport. During the airport's construction, New York Mayor Fiorello LaGuardia had an upper-level lounge set aside for press conferences and business meetings. At one such press conference, he noted that the entire terminal was being offered for lease to airline tenants; after a reporter asked whether the lounge would be leased as well, LaGuardia replied that it would, and a vice president of AA immediately offered to lease the premises. The airline then procured a liquor license and began operating the lounge as the \"Admirals Club\" in 1939.{{citation needed|date=December 2013}}\n\nThe second Admirals Club opened at Washington National Airport. Because it was illegal to sell alcohol in Virginia at the time, the club contained refrigerators for the use of its members, so they could store their liquor at the airport.{{citation needed|date=December 2013}} For many years, membership in the Admirals Club (and most other airline lounges) was by the airline's invitation. After a passenger sued for discrimination,<ref name=\"timeac\">{{cite news|title=Toward Equality for VIPs |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,836046,00.html?iid=chix-sphere |work=TIME |date=July 15, 1966 |accessdate=January 26, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090114112519/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0%2C9171%2C836046%2C00.html?iid=chix-sphere |archivedate=January 14, 2009 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> the Club (and most other airline lounges) switched to a paid membership program.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\n=== Flagship Lounge ===\nThough affiliated with the Admirals Club and staffed by many of the same employees, the Flagship Lounge is a separate lounge specifically designed for customers flying in First Class and Business Class on international flights and transcontinental domestic flights, as well as AAdvantage Concierge Key, Executive Platinum, Platinum Pro, and Platinum, as well as Oneworld Emerald and Sapphire frequent flyers. As of May 2019, Flagship Lounges are located at five airports: New York\u2013JFK,<ref name=\"JFK\">{{cite web|url=http://fortune.com/go/luxury/american-airlines-flaship-lounge-jfk-airport/|last=Tkaczyk|first=Christopher |date=May 25, 2017|title=An Inside Look at the New American Airlines Flagship Lounge at JFK Airport|work=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]|accessdate=May 14, 2019}}</ref> Chicago-O'Hare,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/chicago/news/2017/09/13/american-airlines-rolls-out-flashy-flagship-lounge.html|last=Lazare |first=Lewis |date=September 13, 2017|title=American Airlines rolls out flashy Flagship Lounge at O'Hare Airport (Photos)|work=[[Chicago Business Journal]]|accessdate=May 14, 2019}}</ref> Miami International,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/business/fl-bz-mia-new-american-flagship-lounge-20171116-story.html|last=Satchell|first= Arlene|date=November 16, 2017|title=American's Flagship Lounge at MIA opens Tuesday for first-class, business travelers|work=[[Sun-Sentinel]]|accessdate=May 14, 2019}}</ref> Los Angeles,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/travel/news/article.cfm?c_id=7&objectid=12193870|last=Jurgens |first=Jane |date=January 23, 2019|title=Lounge Check: American Airlines Flagship Business Class lounge at LAX|work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|accessdate=May 14, 2019}}</ref> and Dallas/Fort Worth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/dallas/news/2019/05/14/american-airlines-flagship-lounge-dfw-airport.html?|last=Hoopfer |first=Evan |date=May 14, 2019|title=Shower in an airport? See inside American's swanky new DFW lounge|work=[[American City Business Journals#Dallas Business Journal|Dallas Business Journal]]|accessdate=May 14, 2019}}</ref> Flagship Lounges are planned for London-Heathrow and Philadelphia.<ref name=\"JFK\" />\n\n== Corporate affairs ==\n===Ownership and structure===\nAmerican Airlines, Inc. is publicly traded through its parent company, [[American Airlines Group]] Inc., under NASDAQ: AAL {{NASDAQ|AAL}}, with a market capitalization of about $12 billion as of 2019, and is included in the [[S&P 500 Index|S&P 500 index]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAmerican Eagle is a network of six regional carriers that operate under a codeshare and service agreement with American, operating flights to destinations in the United States, Canada, the Caribbean and Mexico.  Three of these carriers are independent and three are subsidiaries of American Airlines Group: [[Envoy Air|Envoy Air Inc.]], [[Piedmont Airlines|Piedmont Airlines, Inc.]], and [[PSA Airlines|PSA Airlines Inc.]]<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Headquarters ===\nAmerican Airlines is headquartered in [[Fort Worth, Texas]], adjacent to the [[Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport]].<ref>\"[https://americanairlines.gcs-web.com/node/33546/html Form 8-K].\" American Airlines. Retrieved May 18, 2018. [https://americanairlines.gcs-web.com/static-files/f88fecf5-c693-4bb3-a04e-c1daab4f8141 PDF version] \u2013 \"4333 Amon Carter Blvd., Fort Worth, Texas\"</ref> The headquarters is located in two office buildings in the CentrePort office complex and these buildings together have about {{convert|1400000|sqft|sqm}} of space. {{as of|2014}} over 4,300 employees work at this complex.<ref>\"[http://www.aa.com/i18n/amrcorp/corporateInformation/facts/americanairlinesgroup.jsp American Airlines Group Overview] [https://web.archive.org/web/20140410145206/http://www.aa.com/i18n/amrcorp/corporateInformation/facts/americanairlinesgroup.jsp Archived copy] (April 10, 2014).\" American Airlines. Retrieved on April 24, 2014.</ref>\n\nBefore it was headquartered in Texas, American Airlines was headquartered at 633 Third Avenue in the [[Murray Hill, Manhattan|Murray Hill]] area of [[Midtown Manhattan]], New York City.<ref>''World Airline Directory''. [[Flight International]]. March 20, 1975. \"[http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1975/1975%20-%200536.html 472].</ref><ref>\"[http://gonyc.about.com/od/manhattan/l/bl_gramercy.htm Flatiron / Gramercy / Murray Hill / Union Square: Manhattan Neighborhood Map].\" ''[[About.com]]''. Retrieved January 25, 2009.</ref> In 1979, American moved its headquarters to a site at [[Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport]], which affected up to 1,300 jobs. [[Mayor of New York City]] [[Ed Koch]] described the move as a \"betrayal\" of New York City.<ref>Sterba, James P. \"[https://www.nytimes.com/1978/11/16/archives/american-will-shift-headquarters-from-manhattan-to-dallas-airport.html American Will Shift Headquarters From Manhattan to Dallas Airport; Big Economies Predicted].\" ''[[The New York Times]]''. Thursday November 16, 1978. Page A1. Retrieved August 27, 2009.</ref> American moved to two leased office buildings in [[Grand Prairie, Texas]].<ref name=\"FortWorthHQFinished\">\"[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=9ZYTAAAAIBAJ&sjid=5gUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3054,25513&dq=american-airlines+new+headquarters American Airlines Finishes Moving into Headquarters Monday].\" ''[[Associated Press]]'' at ''[[Ocala Star-Banner]]''. January 16, 1983. 6A. ''[[Google News]]'' 4 of 62. Retrieved August 27, 2009.</ref><!--January 16, 1983 is a Sunday, so January 17 would be a Monday--> On January 17, 1983, the airline finished moving into a $150&nbsp;million (${{inflation|USD|150,000,000|1983|r=-6|fmt=c}} when adjusted for inflation), {{convert|550000|sqft|adj=on}} facility in Fort Worth; $147&nbsp;million (about ${{inflation|USD|147,000,000|1983|r=-6|fmt=c}} when adjusted for inflation) in Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport bonds financed the headquarters. The airline began leasing the facility from the airport, which owns the facility.<ref name=\"FortWorthHQFinished\" /> Following the merger of US Airways and American Airlines, US Airways consolidated the corporate headquarters of the new company in Fort Worth, leaving their current headquarters in Phoenix, AZ, which had also been the headquarters of the airline that brought US Airways out of bankruptcy, [[America West Airlines]].\n\nAs of 2015, American Airlines is the corporation with the largest presence in Fort Worth.<ref name=BrownSteveHQ>Brown, Steve. \"[http://www.dallasnews.com/business/airline-industry/20151022-american-airlines-will-build-new-headquarters-in-fort-worth1.ece American Airlines will build new headquarters in Fort Worth]\" ([https://web.archive.org/web/20151024145639/http://www.dallasnews.com/business/airline-industry/20151022-american-airlines-will-build-new-headquarters-in-fort-worth1.ece Archive]). ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]''. October 22, 2015. Retrieved on October 27, 2015. \"Robert Sturns, Fort Worth's economic development director, said the city was committed to keeping its largest corporate citizen.\"</ref>\n\nIn 2015, American announced that it would build a new headquarters in Fort Worth. Groundbreaking began in the spring of 2016 and occupancy completed in September 2019.<ref name=OwensWhitelyDouglas>Owens, Marjorie, Jason Whitely, and Jim Douglas. \"[http://www.wfaa.com/story/news/2015/10/22/american-to-build-new-headquarters-in-fort-worth/74395434/ American to build new headquarters in Fort Worth]\" ([https://web.archive.org/web/20151024221818/http://www.wfaa.com/story/news/2015/10/22/american-to-build-new-headquarters-in-fort-worth/74395434/ Archive]). ''[[WFAA]]''. October 22, 2015. Retrieved on October 24, 2015.</ref> The airline plans to house 5,000 new workers in the building.<ref name=BrownSteveHQ />\n\nIt will be located on a {{convert|41|acre|ha|adj=on}} property adjacent to the airline's flight academy and conference and training center, west of [[Texas State Highway 360]], {{convert|2|mi|km}}<ref name=OwensWhitelyDouglas /> west from the current headquarters. The airline will lease a total of {{convert|300|acre|ha}} from Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport and this area will include the headquarters.<ref name=BrownSteveHQ /> Construction of the new headquarters began after the demolition of the Sabre facility, previously on the site.<ref name=OwensWhitelyDouglas />\n\nThe airline considered developing a new headquarters in [[Irving, Texas]], on the old [[Texas Stadium]] site, before deciding to keep the headquarters in Fort Worth.<ref name=BrownSteveHQ />\n\n=== Corporate identity ===\n[[File:American Airlines logo.svg|thumb|American Airlines' fourth logo, used from 1967 to January 16, 2013]]\n\n==== Logo ====\nIn 1931, Goodrich Murphy, an American employee, designed the AA logo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.com/2015/05/tales-era-airlines-knew-good-design/|title=Tales From an Era When Airlines Knew Good Design |website=Wired.com |accessdate=May 22, 2015}}</ref> The logo was redesigned by [[Massimo Vignelli]] in 1967.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vignelli.com/home/identity/aa.html |title=Vignelli Associates About the AA Logo |website=Vignelli.com |accessdate=December 2, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201175513/http://vignelli.com/home/identity/aa.html |archive-date=December 1, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.logosdesigners.com/#massimo-vignelli|title=iconic logo designers|website=logosdesigners.com|accessdate=April 3, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100124021004/http://www.logosdesigners.com/#massimo-vignelli|archive-date=January 24, 2010|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> Thirty years later, in 1997, American Airlines was able to make its logo Internet-compatible by buying the domain AA.com. ''AA'' is also American's two-letter [[IATA]] [[airline codes|airline designator]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Current Airline Members |url=https://www.iata.org/about/members/Pages/airline-list.aspx?All=true |website=Iata.org |accessdate=February 5, 2019 |language=English}}</ref>\n\nOn January 17, 2013, American launched a new rebranding and marketing campaign with FutureBrand dubbed, \"A New American\". This included a new logo replacing the logo used since 1967. American Airlines calls the new logo the \"Flight Symbol, incorporating the eagle, star, and the letter \"A\" of the classic logo.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aa.com/newamerican?anchorLocation=HomePageHero1&reportedTitle=Becoming%20a%20new%20American&reportedPosition=0&url=undefined&_locale=en_US&repositoryName=undefined&repositoryId=undefined |title=Becoming a new American |website=Aa.com |date= |accessdate=March 6, 2013}}</ref>{{better source|date=January 2019}}\n\nAmerican Airlines faced difficulty obtaining copyright registration for their 2013 logo. On June 3, 2016, American Airlines sought to register it with the [[United States Copyright Office]],<ref name=\"US Copyright Office Ruling\">{{cite web|last1=Zaller Rowland|first1=Catherine|title=Re: Second Request for Reconsideration for Refusal to Register American Airlines Flight Symbol; Correspondence ID: 1-28H4ZFK; SR#: 1-3537494381|url=https://www.copyright.gov/rulings-filings/review-board/docs/american-airlines-flight-symbol.pdf|date=January 8, 2018|website=Copyright.gov|publisher=[[United States Copyright Office]]|accessdate=January 26, 2018}}</ref> but in October of that year, the Copyright Office ruled that the logo was ineligible for copyright protection, as it did not pass the [[threshold of originality]], and was thus in the [[public domain]].<ref name=\"US Copyright Office Ruling\" /> American requested that the Copyright Office reconsider, but on January 8, 2018, the Copyright Office affirmed its initial determination.<ref name=\"US Copyright Office Ruling\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=US Copyright Office Says What We're All Thinking: American Airlines Lacks Creativity \u2013 One Mile at a Time|url=http://onemileatatime.boardingarea.com/2018/01/25/american-airlines-copyright/|website=One Mile at a Time|date=January 25, 2018}}</ref> After American Airlines submitted additional materials, the Copyright Office reversed its decision on December 7, 2018, and ruled that the logo contained enough creativity to merit copyright protection.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.copyright.gov/rulings-filings/review-board/docs/american-airlines.pdf |title=Re: Registration Decision Regarding American Airlines Flight Symbol; Correspondence ID 1-28H4ZFK; SR 1-3537494381 |date=December 7, 2018 |publisher=[[United States Copyright Office]] |access-date=June 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Aircraft livery ====\nAmerican's early [[aircraft livery|liveries]] varied widely, but a common livery was adopted in the 1930s, featuring an [[eagle]] painted on the fuselage.<ref>{{ cite web | url = http://www.airlinesanddestinations.com/aircraft/american-airlines-unveils-new-logo-and-livery/ | title = American Airlines Unveils New Logo and Livery | website = Airlines and Destinations | date = January 17, 2013 | accessdate = July 26, 2017 }}</ref> The eagle became a symbol of the company and inspired the name of [[Envoy Air|American Eagle Airlines]]. Propeller aircraft featured an [[international orange]] lightning bolt running down the length of the fuselage, which was replaced by a simpler orange stripe with the introduction of jets.\"<ref>Boeing 707 Jet Airliner Non-Stop Service between New York City and Los Angeles\", ''Boeing Magazine'' 30 (1958), 66.</ref>\n\n[[File:American Airlines Astrojet N951AA.jpg|thumb|A Boeing 737 in the Astrojet livery]]\n\nIn the late 1960s, American commissioned designer [[Massimo Vignelli]] to develop a new livery. The original design called for a red, white, and blue stripe on the fuselage, and a simple \"AA\" logo, without an eagle, on the tail; instead, Vignelli created a highly stylized eagle, which remained the company's logo until January 16, 2013. In 1999, American painted a new [[Boeing 757]] (N679AN) in its 1959 international orange livery. One [[Boeing 777]] and one Boeing 757 were painted in standard livery with a pink ribbon on the sides and the tail, in support of [[Susan G. Komen for the Cure]]. One Boeing 757 is painted with a yellow ribbon on the tailfin on the aircraft and the side of the body says \"Flagship Freedom\". American Eagle, the airline's regional airline has the same special livery on ERJ-145 aircraft.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\n[[File:AA Flagship Freedom.JPG|thumb|left|AA \"Flagship Freedom\" [[Boeing 757-200]], labeled with a \"[[Yellow ribbon|yellow awareness ribbon]]\" symbol, representing support of the [[United States Armed Forces]] overseas operations.]]\nOn January 17, 2013, American unveiled a new livery.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/breaking/chi-american-airlines-livery-20130117,0,198977.story |title=American Airlines unveils new logo, livery |work=Chicago Tribune |date=January 17, 2013 |accessdate=January 17, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130217030650/http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/breaking/chi-american-airlines-livery-20130117,0,198977.story |archive-date=February 17, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Before then, American had been the only major U.S. airline to leave most of its aircraft surfaces unpainted. This was because C. R. Smith would not say he liked painted aircraft and refused to use any liveries that involved painting the entire plane. Robert \"Bob\" Crandall later justified the distinctive natural metal finish by noting that less paint reduced the aircraft's weight, thus saving on fuel costs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://industry.bnet.com/travel/1000148/paint-vs-bare-metal-on-airplanes/ |title=Delta, Air Canada Among Carriers Weighing Benefit of Paint Stripping |website=Industry.bnet.com |date=October 8, 2008 |accessdate=December 2, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:US Airways A319-112 LAS N717UW.jpg|thumb|Airbus A319 of US Airways wearing [[Carolina Panthers]] livery]]\n[[File:N921NN B737-823W American Al YVR 24JUL13 (9362686624).jpg|thumb|Boeing 737 aircraft N921NN, the final aircraft delivered to American in the polished aluminum livery, retained as a heritage aircraft.]]\n\nIn January 2013, American launched a new rebranding and marketing campaign dubbed, \"The New American\". In addition to a new logo, American Airlines introduced a new livery for its fleet. The airline calls the new livery and branding \"a clean and modern update\".<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> The current design features an abstract American flag on the tail, along with a silver-painted fuselage, as a throw-back to the old livery. The new design was painted by [[Leading Edge Aviation Services]] in [[California]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Ahles |first=Andrea |url=http://www.star-telegram.com/2013/01/17/4556563/american-airlines-shows-off-new.html |title=Star-Telegram 18 January 2013: \"American Airlines shows off new look for new era\" |website=Star-telegram.com |date=January 18, 2013 |accessdate=January 29, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130310095631/http://www.star-telegram.com/2013/01/17/4556563/american-airlines-shows-off-new.html |archivedate=March 10, 2013 }}</ref> Doug Parker, the incoming CEO indicated that the new livery could be short-lived, stating that \"maybe we need to do something slightly different than that ... The only reason this is an issue now is because they just did it right in the middle, which kind of makes it confusing, so that gives us an opportunity, actually, to decide if we are going to do something different because we have so many airplanes to paint\".<ref>King, Eric. (March 28, 2013) [http://www.nbcdfw.com/news/business/American-Airlines-New-Livery-Soon-Could-Become-Its-Old-Look-200532901.html American Airline's New Livery Soon Could Become Its Old Look | NBC 5 Dallas-Fort Worth]. Nbcdfw.com. Retrieved on July 18, 2013.</ref> The current logo and livery have had mixed criticism, with ''[[Design Shack]]'' editor Joshua Johnson writing that they 'boldly and proudly communicate the concepts of American pride and freedom wrapped into a shape that instantly makes you think about an airplane',<ref name=\"designshackliverypraise\">{{cite web |last1=Johnson |first1=Joshua |title=Check Out the New American Airlines Logo |url=https://designshack.net/articles/graphics/check-out-the-new-american-airlines-logo/ |website=Design Shack |accessdate=June 11, 2019 |date=January 23, 2013}}</ref> and ''[http://www.askthepilot.com/ AskThePilot.com]'' author Patrick Smith describing the logo as 'a linoleum knife poking through a shower curtain'.<ref name=\"patricksmithcriticism\">{{cite web |last1=Smith |first1=Patrick |title=The New American Airlines Livery |url=http://www.askthepilot.com/american-to-keep-new-livery/ |website=AskThePilot.com |accessdate=June 11, 2019 |date=January 6, 2014}}</ref> Later in January 2013, [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] asked the designer of the 1968 American Airlines logo ([[Massimo Vignelli]]) on his opinion over the rebranding.<ref name=\"vignelliqna\">{{cite news |last1=Mayo |first1=Keenan |title=Q&A: Original American Airlines Designer Massimo Vignelli on the Redesigned Logo |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-01-18/q-and-a-original-american-airlines-designer-massimo-vignelli-on-the-redesigned-logo |accessdate=August 7, 2019 |work=Bloomberg.com |publisher=Bloomberg L.P. |date=January 19, 2013 |format=Web}}</ref>\n\nIn the end, American let their employees decide the new livery's fate. On an internal website for employees, American posted two options, one the new livery and one a modified version of the old livery. All of the [[American Airlines Group]] employees (including US Airways and other affiliates) were able to vote.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.dallasnews.com/business/airlines/2013/12/16/doug-parker-to-let-american-airlines-employees-decide-whether-to-keep-the-new-aa-tail | title = Doug Parker to let American Airlines employees decide whether to keep the new AA tail | website = [[Dallas News]] | last = Maxon | first = Terry | date = December 2013 | accessdate = July 26, 2017 }}</ref> American ultimately decided to keep the new look. Parker announced that American would keep a US Airways and America West heritage aircraft in the fleet, with plans to add a heritage TWA aircraft and a heritage American plane with the old livery.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.nbcdfw.com/news/business/American-Airlines-Employees-Vote-to-Keep-New-Livery-238487381.html | title = American Airlines Employees Vote to Keep New Livery | website = [[NBC]] | last = Heinz | first = Frank | date = January 2, 2014 | accessdate = July 26, 2017 }}</ref> As of September 2019, American has heritage aircraft for Piedmont, PSA, America West, US Airways, Reno Air, TWA, and AirCal in their fleet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apex.aero/2015/12/03/heritage-livery-flies-again-american-airlines-retro-rollout|title=[PHOTOS] Heritage Livery Flies Again in American Airlines' Retro Rollout|date=2015-12-03|website=APEX {{!}} Airline Passenger Experience|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref> They also have two AA branded heritage 737-800 aircraft, an AstroJet N905NN,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://airlinegeeks.com/2017/06/05/photos-american-rolls-out-new-astrojet-themed-boeing-737-800/|title=Photos: American Rolls out New AstroJet-Themed Boeing 737-800|last=Ewing|first=Ryan|date=2017-06-05|website=AirlineGeeks.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref> and the polished aluminum livery used from 1967 to 2013, N921NN.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://airlinegeeks.com/2017/12/14/american-quietly-adds-new-polished-aluminum-retro-livery-to-a-boeing-737-800/|title=American Quietly Adds Polished Aluminum Retro Livery to a Boeing 737-800|last=Ewing|first=Ryan|date=2017-12-14|website=AirlineGeeks.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref>\n\n=== Worker relations ===\nThe main representatives of key groups of employees are:\n* The [[Allied Pilots Association]] is an in-house union which represents the nearly 15,000 American Airlines pilots; it was created in 1963 after the pilots left the [[Air Line Pilots Association]] (ALPA).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alliedpilots.org/Public/AboutAPA/Background/background.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=February 5, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160204003305/https://www.alliedpilots.org/Public/AboutAPA/Background/background.asp |archivedate=February 4, 2016 |df= }}</ref> However the majority of American Eagle pilots are ALPA members.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.alpa.org/en/about-alpa/our-pilot-groups/pilot-groups/envoy|title=Envoy Air \u2013 ALPA|website=alpa.org|access-date=October 26, 2016}}</ref>\n* The [[Association of Professional Flight Attendants]] represents American Airlines flight attendants, including former USAirways flight attendants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dallasnews.com/business/airline-industry/20141218-american-airlines-flight-attendants-to-get-bigger-pay-raises-after-all.ece|title=American Airlines flight attendants to get bigger pay raises after all|website=Dallasnews.com|accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref>\n* Flight attendants at wholly owned Regional Carriers (Envoy, Piedmont and PSA) are all represented by [http://www.afacwa.org/ Association of Flight Attendants \u2013 Communications Workers of America] (AFA-CWA). US Airways flight attendants were active members of AFA-CWA before the merger, and they are honorary lifetime members. AFA-CWA is the largest flight attendant union in the industry.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n* The [[Transport Workers Union of America|Transport Workers Union-International Association of Machinists alliance]] (TWU-IAM) represents the majority of American Airlines employed fleet service agents, mechanics and other ground workers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.star-telegram.com/news/business/aviation/sky-talk-blog/article36302475.html|title=American CEO says contract proposals to ground workers to have \"double-digit\" pay increases|website=Star-telegram.com|accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref>\n* American's customer service and gate employees belong to the [[Communications Workers of America]]/[[International Brotherhood of Teamsters]] Passenger Service Association.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviationblog.dallasnews.com/2015/11/american-airlines-gate-agents-approve-a-new-labor-contract.html/|title=American Airlines customer service and gate agents approve new labor contract|last =Jean|first =Sheryl|website=Airline Biz Blog}}</ref>\n\n== Concerns and conflicts ==\n=== Environmental violations ===\nBetween October 1993 to July 1998, American Airlines was repeatedly cited for using high-sulfur fuel in motor vehicles at 10 major airports around the country, a violation of the [[Clean Air Act (United States)|Clean Air Act]].<ref name=\"epa\">{{cite web|title=American Airlines Will Make Clean Air Improvements at Logan Airport Reports to EPA the Use of Illegal High Sulfur Fuel in Motor Vehicles|url=http://epa.gov/NE/pr/1999/072099b.html |website=[[United States Environmental Protection Agency]]|date=July 19, 1999|accessdate=January 25, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070707175156/http://epa.gov/ne/pr/1999/072099b.html|archivedate=July 7, 2007}}</ref>\n\n=== Lifetime AAirpass ===\nSince 1981, as a means of creating revenue in a period of loss-making, American Airlines had offered a [[AAirpass|lifetime pass]] of unlimited travel, for the initial cost of $250,000. This entitled the pass holder to fly anywhere in the world. 28 were sold. However, after some time, the airline realised they were making losses on the tickets, with the ticketholders costing them up to $1 million each. Ticketholders were booking large amounts of flights, and some ticketholders flying interstate for lunch or flying to London multiple times a month. AA raised the cost of the lifetime pass to $3 million, and then finally stopped offering it in 2003. AA then used litigation to cancel two of the lifetime offers, saying the passes \"had been terminated due to fraudulent activity\".<ref name=\"pass\">{{cite web|title='Free'quent flier has wings clipped after American Airlines takes away his unlimited pass|url=https://nypost.com/2012/05/13/freequent-flier-has-wings-clipped-after-american-airlines-takes-away-his-unlimited-pass/ |publisher=New York Post|date=May 13, 2012|accessdate=October 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Cabin fume events ===\n* In 1988, on American Airlines Flight 132's approach into Nashville, flight attendants notified the cockpit that there was smoke in the cabin. The flight crew in the cockpit ignored the warning, as on a prior flight, a [[fume event]] had occurred due to a problem with the [[auxiliary power unit]]. However, the smoke on Flight 132 was caused by improperly packaged hazardous materials. According to the [[National Transportation Safety Board|NTSB]] inquiry, the cockpit crew persistently refused to acknowledge that there was a serious threat to the aircraft or the passengers, even after they were told that floor was becoming soft and passengers had to be reseated. As a result, the aircraft was not evacuated immediately on landing, exposing the crew and passengers to the threat of smoke and fire longer than necessary.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/a02a/6b1ff0725d682e3ab0fa55681a1db46af4ad.pdf|title=Chute, Rebecca D., and Earl L. Winter. \"Cockpit-cabin communication: II. Shall we tell the pilots?.\" The International Journal of Aviation Psychology 6.3 (1996): 211-231.|website=Pdfs.semanticscholar.org|accessdate=February 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://flightsafety.org/asw/jul12/asw_jul12_p32-35.pdf|title=Cross, Jamie. \"Sources of friction.\" AeroSafety world 7.online (2012): 32-35.|website=Flightsafety.org|accessdate=February 23, 2019}}</ref>\n* On April 11, 2007, toxic smoke and oil fumes leaked into the aircraft cabin as American Airlines Flight 843 taxied to the gate. A flight attendant who was present in the cabin subsequently filed a lawsuit against Boeing, stating that she was diagnosed with neurotoxic disorder due to her exposure to the fumes, which caused her to experience memory loss, tremors, and severe headaches. She settled with the company in 2011.<ref>[http://www.nbcnews.com/id/44777304/ns/travel-news/t/boeing-suit-settlement-stirs-jetliner-air-safety-debate/#.XFqZYVUzaUk Boeing suit settlement stirs jetliner air safety debate], NBC news, October 6, 2011</ref>\n* In 2009, Mike Holland, deputy chairman for radiation and environmental issues at the [[Allied Pilots Association]] and an American Airlines pilot, said that the pilot union had started alerting pilots of the danger of contaminated [[bleed air]], including contacting crew members that the union thinks were exposed to contamination based on maintenance records and pilot logs.<ref>[https://zembla.bnnvara.nl/pdf/wsj_fume_events.pdf Nassauer, Sarah. \"Up in the Air: New Worries About 'Fume Events' on Planes.\"] The Wall Street Journal (2009).</ref>\n* In a January 2017 incident on American Airlines Flight 1896, seven flight attendants were hospitalized after a strange odor was detected in the cabin. The Airbus A330 involved subsequently underwent a \"thorough maintenance inspection,\" having been involved in three fume events in three months.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/news/fume-incident-hospitalises-american-airlines-crew-and-raises-questions-over-safety-of-cabin-air/ 'Fume event' hospitalises American Airlines crew in latest incident concerning cabin air], Telegraph, January 4, 2017</ref><ref>[https://abcnews.go.com/US/american-airlines-jet-suffers-fume-incident-months-flight/story?id=44535862 American Airlines Jet Has 3rd Fume Incident in 3 Months, 7 Flight Attendants Transported to Hospital and Released], ABC news, January 3, 2017</ref>\n* In August 2018, American Airlines flight attendants picketed in front of the Fort Worth company headquarters over a change in sick day policy, complaining that exposure to ill passengers, toxic uniforms, toxic cabin air, radiation exposure, and other issues were causing them to be sick.<ref>[https://www.businessinsider.com/american-airlines-flight-attendants-protest-sick-policy-toxic-uniform-2018-8 American Airlines flight attendants are gearing up for battle over the company's 'punitive' new attendance policy], Business Insider, August 31, 2018</ref><ref>[https://www.bizjournals.com/chicago/news/2018/08/29/american-airlines-flight-attendants-to-picket.html American Airlines flight attendants to picket headquarters Thursday], August 29, 2018, Chicago Business Journal</ref>\n* In January 2019, two pilots and three flight attendants on Flight 1897 from Philadelphia to Fort Lauderdale were hospitalized following complaints of a strange odor.<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/flights/2019/01/10/american-airlines-crew-sickened-philadelphia-florida-flight/2537776002/ American Airlines pilots, flight attendants fall ill on Philadelphia to Florida flight], USA Today, January 11, 2019</ref><ref>[https://www.foxnews.com/travel/american-airlines-staffers-florida-airport-odor Five American Airlines staffers hospitalized after noticing 'odor' on plane], FOX News, January 10, 2019</ref>\n\n=== Discrimination complaints ===\nOn October 24, 2017, the [[NAACP]] issued a travel advisory for American Airlines urging [[African Americans]] to \"exercise caution\" when traveling with the airline. The NAACP issued the advisory after four incidents. In one incident, a black woman was moved from First Class to coach while her white traveling companion was allowed to remain in First Class. In another incident, a black man was forced to give up his seats after being confronted by two unruly white passengers.<ref name=\"PBS20171025\">[https://www.pbs.org/newshour/nation/the-naacp-issues-travel-advisory-for-american-airlines-warning-black-passengers-of-disturbing-incidents The NAACP issues travel advisory for American Airlines, warning black passengers of 'disturbing incidents'], PBS, October 25, 2017</ref> According to the NAACP, while they did receive complaints on other airlines, most of their complaints in the year prior to their advisory were on American Airlines.<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2017/10/25/naacp-most-complaints-american-airlines-what-can-brands-learn/800300001/ NAACP: Most complaints about American Airlines. What can brands learn?], USA Today, October 25, 2017</ref> In July 2018, the NAACP lifted their travel advisory saying that American has made improvements to mitigate discrimination and unsafe treatment of African Americans.<ref name=\"PBS20180717\">[https://www.pbs.org/newshour/nation/naacp-lifts-travel-advisory-against-american-airlines NAACP lifts travel advisory against American Airlines], PBS, July 17, 2018</ref>\n\n== Accidents and incidents ==\n{{Main|List of American Airlines accidents and incidents}}\nAs of March 2019, the airline has had almost sixty aircraft [[hull loss]]es, beginning with the crash of an American Airways [[Ford Trimotor|Ford 5-AT-C Trimotor]] in August 1931.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/operator/airline.php?var=9366 |title=American Airways safety occurrences |website=[[Aviation Safety Network]] |publisher=[[Flight Safety Foundation]] |access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref><ref name=ASNAA>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/operator/airline.php?var=6516 |title=American Airlines safety occurrences |website=[[Aviation Safety Network]] |publisher=[[Flight Safety Foundation]] |access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref> Of these most were propeller driven aircraft, including three [[Lockheed L-188 Electra]] turboprop aircraft (of which one, the crash in 1959 of [[American Airlines Flight 320|Flight 320]], resulted in fatalities).<ref name=ASNAA /> The two accidents with the highest fatalities in both the airline's and U.S. aviation history were [[American Airlines Flight 191|Flight 191]] in 1979 and [[American Airlines Flight 587|Flight 587]] in 2001.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aviation-safety.net/database/country/country.php?id=N|title=Aviation Safety Network > ASN Aviation Safety Database > Geographical regions > United States of America air safety profile|last=Ranter|first=Harro|website=aviation-safety.net|access-date=2019-07-26}}</ref>\n\nOn December 20, 1995, [[American Airlines Flight 965|Flight 965]] crashed into a mountain in Buga, Colombia, killing 151 out of the 155 passengers and all eight crew members. The aircraft was a Boeing 757-223 (registration N651AA). It was on approach to Cali, Colombia when it veered off course and crashed into the terrain.\n\nTwo aircraft were hijacked and destroyed in the [[September 11 attacks]]: [[American Airlines Flight 11|Flight 11]] crashed into the north facade of the [[One World Trade Center|North Tower]] of the [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]], and [[Flight 77]] crashed into [[the Pentagon]]; both were bound for [[Los Angeles International Airport|LAX]] from [[Boston Logan International Airport]] and [[Washington Dulles International Airport]] respectively.<ref>{{cite book|editor=Paul Joseph|title=The SAGE Encyclopedia of War: Social Science Perspectives|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=idw0DQAAQBAJ&pg=PA1533|year=2016|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=978-1-4833-5988-5|page=1533}}</ref>\n\nOther accidents include the [[American Airlines Flight 383 (2016)|Flight 383]] engine failure and fire in 2016. There were two training flight accidents in which the crew were killed and six that resulted in no fatalities.<ref name=ASNAA /> Another four jet aircraft have been written off due to incidents while they were parked between flights or while undergoing maintenance.<ref name=ASNAA />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[AAirpass]]\n* [[Air transportation in the United States]]\n* [[List of airlines of the United States]]\n* [[List of airports in the United States]]\n*[[U.S. Airways]] which has merged with American Airlines\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin|33em}}\n* {{Cite book |first=John M. |last=Capozzi |title=A Spirit of Greatness |publisher=JMC |year=2001 |isbn=978-0-9656410-3-6 |url=https://archive.org/details/spiritofgreatnes00john }}\n* {{Cite book |first=Don |last=Bedwell |title=Silverbird: The American Airlines Story |publisher=Airways |year=1999 |isbn=978-0-9653993-6-4 }}\n* {{Cite book |first=Al |last=Casey |title=Casey's Law |publisher=Arcade |year=1997 |isbn=978-1-55970-307-9 }}\n* {{Cite book |first=Simon |last=Forty |title=ABC American Airlines |publisher=Ian Allan |year=1997 |isbn=978-1-882663-21-7 }}\n* {{Cite book |first=Dan |last=Reed |title=The American Eagle: The Ascent of Bob Crandall and American Airlines |publisher=St. Martin's |year=1993 |isbn=978-0-312-08696-1 |url=https://archive.org/details/americaneagleasc00reed }}\n* {{Cite book |first=Robert J. |last=Serling |title=Eagle |publisher=St. Martin's |year=1985 |isbn=978-0-312-22453-0 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/eaglehistoryofam0000serl }}\n* {{Cite book |title=International Directory of Company Histories |publisher=St. James Press }}\n* Hieger, Linda H. (2010) ''With Wings of Silver and Gold'' {{ISBN|978-1-60458-271-0}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikivoyage|Air travel in the United States}}\n{{Sister project links|wikt=no|b=no|q=no|s=no|v=no|species=no|voy=American Airlines}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.aa.com/|mobile=https://mobile.aa.com/}}\n** \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20090826204620/http://www.aa.com/aa/i18nForward.do?p=%2Furls%2Fsocial.jsp&anchorLocation=Homepage_Bottom&url=%2Faa%2Fi18nForward.do&_locale=en_US&repositoryName=PromotionContentRepository&repositoryId=16122773&reportedTitle=AA+On+Twitter&flash=false American Airlines is Social]\" \u2013 Links to official Facebook, Google+ and Twitter\n* [https://www.aavacations.com/ Official American Airlines Vacations website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20040414093042/http://americanwaymag.com/ ''American Way'' inflight magazine]\n* [http://timetableimages.com/ttimages/aa.htm Timetableimages.com] has many timetables from the 1930s until 1967, showing where American flew, how often, how long it took and how much it cost.\n* {{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/interview-doug-parker-chief-executive-american-ai-445433/ |title= Interview: Doug Parker, chief executive, American Airlines |date= February 20, 2018 |last= Russell |first= Edward |work= Flightglobal}}\n\n{{American Airlines}}\n{{Airlines of the United States}}\n{{Navboxes\n|list =\n{{American Airlines Group}}\n{{Oneworld}}\n{{Airlines for America}}\n{{IATA members|northam}}\n{{Legacy carrier}}}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:American Airlines| ]]\n[[Category:Airlines based in Texas]]\n[[Category:Airlines established in 1934]]\n[[Category:1934 establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:Airlines of the United States]]\n[[Category:Airlines for America members]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Fort Worth, Texas]]\n[[Category:IATA members]]\n[[Category:OpenTravel Alliance]]\n[[Category:American Airlines Group]]\n[[Category:Aviation in Arizona]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the airline known as American Airlines|its parent company|American Airlines Group|a list of airlines of the United States|List of airlines of the United States}}\n{{short description|Major airline of the United States}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox airline\n| airline                  = American Airlines, Inc.\n| image                    = American Airlines logo 2013.svg\n| image_size               = 300px\n| alt                      = American Airlines logo\n| caption                  = \n| IATA                     = AA<ref name=\"chavprofile\">{{cite web | url=http://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/airline/AA | title=American Airlines | website=[[ch-aviation]] | accessdate=December 27, 2016}}</ref>\n| ICAO                     = AAL<ref name=\"chavprofile\" />\n| callsign                 = AMERICAN<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.faa.gov/documentLibrary/media/Order/7340_2F_Bsc_w_Chgs_1-3_Contractions.pdf | title=7340.2F with Change 1 and Change 2 and Change 3 | website=[[Federal Aviation Administration]] | date=October 15, 2015 | accessdate=December 27, 2016 | pages=3\u20131\u201318}}</ref>\n| founded                  = {{Start date and age|1926|4|15}} (earliest predecessor airline as American Airways, Inc.)<br />[[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], [[United States]]<ref name=\"foundation\">{{cite web |url=https://www.aa.com/i18n/customer-service/about-us/history-of-american-airlines.jsp|title=History of American Airlines |date=2015 |publisher=American Airlines Inc. |accessdate=June 30, 2015}}</ref>\n| commenced                = {{Start date|1936|6|25}}<ref name=\"foundation\" />\n| ceased                   = \n| aoc                      = AALA025A<ref name=faa_aoc>{{cite web |url=http://av-info.faa.gov/detail.asp?DSGN_CODE=AALA&OPER_FAR=121&OPER_NAME=AMERICAN+AIRLINES+INC+AND%2FOR+US+AIRWAYS+INC|title=Airline Certificate Information \u2013 Detail View |date=May 12, 2015 |website=av-info.faa.gov |publisher=Federal Aviation Administration |quote=Certificate Number AALA025A}}</ref>\n| hubs                     = *[[Charlotte Douglas International Airport|Charlotte]]\n*[[O'Hare International Airport|Chicago\u2013O'Hare]]\n*[[Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport|Dallas/Fort Worth]]\n*[[Los Angeles International Airport|Los Angeles]]\n*[[Miami International Airport|Miami]]\n*[[John F. Kennedy International Airport|New York\u2013JFK]]\n*[[LaGuardia Airport|New York\u2013LaGuardia]]\n*[[Philadelphia International Airport|Philadelphia]]\n*[[Phoenix Sky Harbor International Airport|Phoenix\u2013Sky Harbor]]\n*[[Ronald Reagan Washington National Airport|Washington\u2013National]]\n| frequent_flyer           = [[AAdvantage]]\n| alliance                 = [[Oneworld]]\n| fleet_size               = [[American Airlines fleet|945]] (mainline)<ref name=\"Fleet\">{{cite web|title=American Airlines Fleet Details and History|url=https://www.planespotters.net/airline/American-Airlines|website=Planespotters.net|date=September 4, 2019|accessdate=September 4, 2019}}</ref>\n| destinations             = [[American Airlines destinations|350]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aa.com/i18n/customer-service/about-us/american-airlines-group.jsp |title=About us |publisher=American Airlines |accessdate=November 29, 2017}}</ref>\n| parent                   = [[American Airlines Group]]\n| traded_as                = {{NASDAQ|AAL}}\n| ISIN                     = \n| headquarters             = [[Fort Worth, Texas]], [[United States]]\n| key_people               = *[[Doug Parker]] ([[Chairman]] & [[CEO]])\n*Robert Isom ([[President (corporate title)|President]])\n*Elise Eberwein ([[Executive Vice President]], People and Communications)\n*Stephen Johnson ([[Executive Vice President]], Corporate Affairs)\n*Derek Kerr ([[Executive Vice President]] and [[CFO]])\n*Maya Leibman ([[Executive Vice President]] and [[Chief Information Officer]])<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aa.com/i18n/customer-service/about-us/leadership-bios/leadership-bios.jsp |title=Leadership bios |publisher=American Airlines |accessdate=August 7, 2017}}</ref>\n| revenue                  = See [[American Airlines Group|parent]]\n| operating_income         = See [[American Airlines Group|parent]]\n| net_income               = See [[American Airlines Group|parent]]\n| assets                   = See [[American Airlines Group|parent]]\n| equity                   = See [[American Airlines Group|parent]]\n| num_employees            = 128,900(2019) {{cn|date=February 2020}}\n| website                  = {{URL|www.aa.com}}\n| notes                    = \n}}\n\n'''American Airlines, Inc.''' ('''AA''') is a [[major airlines of the United States|major American airline]] headquartered in [[Fort Worth, Texas]], within the [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth metroplex]]. It is the [[World's largest airlines|world's largest airline]] when measured by fleet size, scheduled passengers carried, and revenue passenger mile. American, together with its regional partners, operates an extensive international and domestic network with almost 6,800 flights per day to nearly 350 destinations in more than 50 countries.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aa.com/i18n/customer-service/about-us/american-airlines-group.jsp|title=American Airlines Group \u2212 About us \u2212 American Airlines|last=|first=|date=|website=Aa.com|accessdate=February 22, 2018}}</ref> American Airlines is a founding member of the [[Oneworld]] alliance, the third-largest airline alliance in the world. Regional service is operated by independent and subsidiary carriers under the brand name [[American Eagle (airline brand)|American Eagle]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/american-air-signs-deal-contract-flying-skywest-165209289.html?_esi=1 |title=American Air signs deal to contract out some flying to SkyWest |work=The Associated|publisher=Yahoo! News |date=September 12, 2012 |accessdate=October 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAmerican Airlines and American Eagle operate out of ten hubs, with [[Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport|Dallas/Fort Worth]] being its largest; handling more than 200 million passengers annually with an average of more than 500,000 passengers daily. American operates its primary maintenance base in [[Tulsa International Airport|Tulsa]] in addition to the maintenance locations at its hubs. As of 2019, the company employs nearly 130,000 people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=1579389|title=Company Overview of American Airlines, Inc.|work=Bloomberg|accessdate=June 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{Main|History of American Airlines}}\n\n[[File:N834AA taking off from Sydney Airport July 2018.jpg|thumb|An American Airlines [[Boeing 787-9]] taking off from [[Sydney Airport]] in July 2018]]\n\nAmerican Airlines was started in 1930 via a union of more than eighty small airlines.<ref name=ap>{{cite news|last=Koenig|first=David|title=American Airlines parent seeks Ch. 11 protection|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5gqSFH2Ou81RHegJYXJtAeU9CkyhA?docId=c6952820f230470692fc37e00d9d2d36 |accessdate=December 7, 2011 |newspaper=Google News |date= November 29, 2011|agency=Associated Press|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111204004443/https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5gqSFH2Ou81RHegJYXJtAeU9CkyhA?docId=c6952820f230470692fc37e00d9d2d36|archivedate=December 4, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe two organizations from which American Airlines was originated were [[Robertson Aircraft Corporation]] and [[Colonial Air Transport]].  The former was first created in Missouri in 1921, with both being merged in 1929 into holding company [[The Aviation Corporation]].  This, in turn, was made in 1930 into an operating company and rebranded as American Airways.  In 1934, when new laws and attrition of mail contracts forced many airlines to reorganize, the corporation redid its routes into a connected system and was renamed American Airlines.  Between 1970 and 2000, the company grew into being an international carrier, purchasing [[Trans World Airlines]] in 2001.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://money.cnn.com/2001/01/10/deals/amr_twa/|title=TWA to be bought by American - Jan. 10, 2001|website=money.cnn.com|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref>\n\nAmerican had a direct role in the development of the [[DC-3]], which resulted from a marathon telephone call from American Airlines CEO [[C. R. Smith]] to Donald Douglas, when Smith persuaded a reluctant Douglas to design a sleeper aircraft based on the [[DC-2]] to replace American's [[Curtiss T-32 Condor II|Curtiss Condor II]] biplanes. (The existing DC-2's cabin was {{convert|66|in|m}} wide, too narrow for side-by-side berths.) Douglas agreed to go ahead with development only after Smith informed him of American's intention to purchase 20 aircraft. The prototype DST ([[Douglas Sleeper Transport]]) first flew on December 17, 1935, (the 32nd anniversary of the [[Wright Brothers]]' flight at Kitty Hawk). Its cabin was {{convert|92|in|m|abbr=on}} wide, and a version with 21 seats instead of the 14\u201316 sleeping berths of the DST was given the designation DC-3. There was no prototype DC-3; the first DC-3 built followed seven DSTs off the production line and was delivered to American Airlines.<ref>Pearcy, Arthur. ''Douglas DC-3 Survivors, Volume 1''. Bourne End, Bucks, UK: Aston Publications, 1987. {{ISBN|0-946627-13-4}}, p. 17</ref> American Airlines inaugurated passenger service on June 26, 1936, with simultaneous flights from [[Newark, New Jersey]], and [[Chicago]], Illinois.<ref>Holden, Henry. [http://www.dc3history.org/douglasdc3.html \"DC-3 History\"]. dc3history.org. Retrieved October 7, 2010.</ref>\n\nIn 2011, due to a downturn in the airline industry, American Airlines' parent company [[AMR Corporation]] filed for bankruptcy protection.  In 2013, American Airlines merged with [[US Airways]] but kept the American Airlines name, as it was the better-recognized brand internationally; the combination of the two airlines resulted in the creation of the largest airline in the United States, and ultimately the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/American-Airlines|title=American Airlines \u2013 American company|website=Britannica.com}}</ref>\n\n==Destinations and hubs==\n===Destinations===\n{{Main|List of American Airlines destinations}}\nAs of April 2020, American Airlines flies to [[List of American Airlines destinations|95 domestic destinations and 95 international destinations in 55 countries in five continents]], soon to be six when American launches their flight to Casablanca from Philadelphia in 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://aa.fltmaps.com/en|title=American Airlines Map|website=aa.fltmaps.com|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref>{{fv|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Hubs===\nAmerican currently operates ten hubs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.aa.com/multimedia/default.aspx#factsheets|title=Newsroom \u2013 Multimedia \u2013 American Airlines Group, Inc|website=news.aa.com}}</ref>\n* [[Charlotte Douglas International Airport|Charlotte]] \u2013 Inherited from the merger with [[US Airways]], Charlotte is American's hub for the Southeast and secondary hub to the Caribbean. It also serves as one of American's larger gateways to Europe.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite web|url=http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/clt |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224081146/http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/clt |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 24, 2015 |title=CLT :: American Airlines Newsroom |website=aa.com |df= }}</ref> About 42 million passengers fly through CLT on American every year, or about 115,000 people per day.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\" /> American has about 91% of the market share at CLT.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\" /> \n* [[O'Hare International Airport|Chicago\u2013O'Hare]] \u2013 American's hub for the Midwest.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{cite web|url=http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/ord |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224081511/http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/ord |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 24, 2015 |title=ORD :: American Airlines Newsroom |website=aa.com |df= }}</ref> About 28 million passengers fly on American through O'Hare every year, or about 77,000 people per day.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\" /> American has about 35% of the market share at O'Hare, making it the airport's second-largest airline after United.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\" /> \n* [[Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport|Dallas/Fort Worth]] \u2013 American's largest hub for the South.<ref name=\"hub.aa.com\">{{cite web|url=http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/dfw |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224081506/http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/dfw |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 24, 2015 |title=DFW :: American Airlines Newsroom |website=aa.com |df= }}</ref> American currently has about 84% of the market share and flies approximately 57 million passengers through DFW every year, which is about 156,000 people per day, making it the busiest airline at the airport.<ref name=\"hub.aa.com\" /> American's corporate headquarters are also in Fort Worth near the airport.<ref name=\"hub.aa.com\" /> DFW serves as American's primary gateway to Mexico, and secondary gateway to Latin America.<ref name=\"hub.aa.com\" /> <!-- DO NOT CHANGE, PER AMERICAN AIRLINES LARGEST MEXICAN GATEWAY IS DFW NOT PHOENIX, LARGEST LATIN AMERICAN GATEWAY IS MIAMI -->\n* [[Los Angeles International Airport|Los Angeles]] \u2013 American's hub for the West Coast and its transpacific gateway.<ref name=\"aa.com4\">{{cite web|url=http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/lax |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224081300/http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/lax |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 24, 2015 |title=LAX :: American Airlines Newsroom |website=aa.com |df= }}</ref> About 16.5 million passengers fly through LAX on American every year, or about 45,000 people per day.<ref name=\"aa.com4\" /> American has about 19% of the market share at LAX, making it the largest carrier at the airport.<ref name=\"aa.com4\" /> \n* [[Miami International Airport|Miami]] \u2013 American's primary Latin American hub.<ref name=\"aa.com2\">{{cite web|url=http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/mia |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224081305/http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/mia |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 24, 2015 |title=MIA :: American Airlines Newsroom |website=Hub.aa.com |accessdate=September 17, 2016 |df= }}</ref> About 30 million passengers fly through MIA every year on American, which is about 79,000 people per day.<ref name=\"aa.com2\" /> American has about 68% of the market share at Miami International, making it the largest airline at the airport.<ref name=\"aa.com2\" />\n* [[John F. Kennedy International Airport|New York\u2013JFK]] \u2013 American's secondary transatlantic hub.<ref name=\"aa.com5\">{{cite web|url=http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/jfk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150920003944/http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/jfk|url-status=dead|archive-date=September 20, 2015|title=JFK :: American Airlines Newsroom|website=aa.com}}</ref> About 7 million passengers fly through JFK on American every year, or about 19,000 people per day.<ref name=\"aa.com5\" /> American has about 12% of the market share at JFK, making it the third-largest carrier at the airport behind Delta and JetBlue.<ref name=\"aa.com5\" /> JFK also serves as a major connecting point for other [[Oneworld]] carriers. \n* [[LaGuardia Airport|New York\u2013LaGuardia]] \u2013 American's second New York hub.<ref name=\"aa.com6\">{{cite web|url=http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/lga|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150920003951/http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/lga|url-status=dead|archive-date=September 20, 2015|title=LGA :: American Airlines Newsroom|website=aa.com}}</ref> About 8.5 million passengers fly through LGA on American every year, or about 23,000 people per day.<ref name=\"aa.com6\" /> The airport also serves as a base for [[American Airlines Shuttle]]. American has about 27% of the market share at LGA, and is the second-largest carrier behind Delta.<ref name=\"aa.com6\" />\n* [[Philadelphia International Airport|Philadelphia]] \u2013 Inherited from the merger with [[US Airways]], Philadelphia is American's primary transatlantic hub.<ref name=\"aa.com\">{{cite web|url=http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/phl |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224081516/http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/phl |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 24, 2015 |title=PHL :: American Airlines Newsroom |website=aa.com |df= }}</ref> American flies approximately 20.5 million passengers a year through PHL, which is about 56,000 people per day.<ref name=\"aa.com\" /> American has about 70% of the market share at PHL, making it the airport's largest airline.<ref name=\"aa.com\" />\n* [[Phoenix Sky Harbor International Airport|Phoenix\u2013Sky Harbor]] \u2013 Inherited from the merger with [[US Airways]],  Phoenix is American's western hub.<ref name=\"aa.com1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dallasnews.com/business/airline-industry/20130215-loss-of-a-corporate-headquarters-may-cost-phoenix-jobs-prestige.ece|title=Loss of a corporate headquarters may cost Phoenix jobs, prestige|website=Dallasnews.com|accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref> American flies approximately 20 million passengers a year through PHX, which is about 55,000 people per day.<ref name=\"aa.com1\" /> Currently American has about 46% of the market share at PHX, making it the airport's largest airline.<ref name=\"aa.com1\" />\n* [[Ronald Reagan Washington National Airport|Washington\u2013National]] \u2013 Inherited from the merger with [[US Airways]], Washington-National is American's hub for the capital of the United States. The airport also serves as a base for [[American Airlines Shuttle]].<ref name=\"aa.com3\">{{cite web|url=http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/2014-dca |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224081501/http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/factsheet/2014-dca |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 24, 2015 |title=DCA :: American Airlines Newsroom |website=aa.com |df= }}</ref> About 12 million passengers fly through DCA on American every year, or about 33,000 people per day.<ref name=\"aa.com3\" /> American has about 49% of the market share at DCA, making it the largest carrier at the airport.<ref name=\"aa.com3\" />\n\n===Tulsa maintenance base===\n[[Tulsa International Airport]] houses American Airline's largest maintenance and repair operations facility and employs 5500 people with the majority as licensed aircraft and jet engine mechanics. The base performs maintenance and engineering work for the airline's fleet of [[Airbus A320]], [[Boeing 757]], [[Boeing 787]], [[Boeing 737]], and some [[Boeing 767]] planes.{{fact|date=March 2020}} \n\nAmerican plans to retire its fleet of 17 [[Boeing 767]] planes in May 2020 and 34 [[Boeing 757]] planes by post-summer 2021 due to the impact of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] on commercial air travel.{{fact|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Alliance and codeshare agreements==\nAmerican Airlines is a member of the [[Oneworld]] alliance and has [[codeshare agreement|codeshares]] with the following airlines:<ref name=\"CAPA AA profile\">{{cite web|url=http://centreforaviation.com/profiles/airlines/american-airlines-aa|title=Profile on American Airlines|website=CAPA|publisher=Centre for Aviation|access-date=October 28, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161028201006/http://centreforaviation.com/profiles/airlines/american-airlines-aa|archive-date=October 28, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n{{Div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Air Tahiti Nui]]\n* [[Alaska Airlines]]\n* [[British Airways]]\n* [[Cape Air]]\n* [[Caribbean Airlines]]\n* [[Cathay Dragon]]<ref>https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/285360/american-airlines-begins-cathay-dragon-codeshares-from-july-2019/</ref>\n* [[Cathay Pacific]]\n* [[China Southern Airlines]]\n* [[El Al]]\n* [[Fiji Airways]]\n* [[Finnair]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Liu |first1=Jim |title=Finnair adds American Airlines codeshare routes via Los Angeles in S19 |url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/281759/finnair-adds-american-airlines-codeshare-routes-via-los-angeles-in-s19/ |accessdate=November 30, 2018 |work=Routesonline |date=November 29, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Gol Transportes A\u00e9reos]] <ref>https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/289431/american-airlines-gol-begins-codeshare-service-from-mid-feb-2020/</ref>\n* [[Hainan Airlines]]\n* [[Hawaiian Airlines]]\n* [[Iberia (airline)|Iberia]]\n* [[Interjet]]\n* [[Japan Airlines]]\n* [[Jetstar Airways]]\n* [[Jetstar Japan]]\n* [[Korean Air]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/american-airlines-and-korean-air-announce-codeshare-agreement|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150302142451/http://hub.aa.com/en/nr/american-airlines-and-korean-air-announce-codeshare-agreement|url-status=dead|archive-date=March 2, 2015|title=American Airlines And Korean Air Announce Codeshare Agreement :: American Airlines Newsroom|website=Hub.aa.com|accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Malaysia Airlines]]\n* [[Qantas]]\n* [[Qatar Airways]]<ref>[https://onemileatatime.com/american-airlines-qatar-airways-partnership/ American Airlines & Qatar Airways Announce Strategic Partnership]</ref>\n* [[Royal Jordanian]]\n* [[Seaborne Airlines]]\n* [[SriLankan Airlines]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Joint ventures===\nIn addition to the above codeshares, American Airlines has entered into [[joint venture]]s with the following airlines:<ref name=\"AA-BA-IB\">{{cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704689804575535904042433736 | title= BA, Iberia, American Launch Venture, Add Routes | newspaper=The Wall Street Journal | date=October 7, 2010 | first=Mike |last= Esterl }}</ref><ref name=\"AMR-JAL\">{{cite news | url= https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704530204576235060492562894 | title= AMR, JAL Forge a Partnership | newspaper=The Wall Street Journal | date=April 1, 2011 | first=Timothy W. |last=Martin}}</ref><ref name=\"QF-AA\">{{cite news | url=http://www.ausbt.com.au/us-govt-greenlights-qantas-american-airlines-joint-venture | title= US govt greenlights Qantas & American Airlines joint venture | first=John |last=Walton | newspaper=Australian Business Traveller | date=November 11, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[British Airways]]\n* [[Finnair]]\n* [[Iberia (airline)|Iberia]]\n* [[Japan Airlines]]\n* [[Qantas]]\n\n== Fleet ==\n{{Main|American Airlines fleet}}\n[[File:Boeing 777-323(ER) American Airlines N718AN, LHR London, England (Heathrow Airport), United Kingdom PP1367675556.jpg|thumb|American Airlines [[Boeing 777-300ER]] landing at [[London Heathrow Airport]] in 2013.]]\nAs of November 2019, American Airlines operates 932 [[Airbus]], [[Boeing]], and [[Embraer]] aircraft. It is the largest commercial fleet in the world.<ref name=\"Fleet\"/>\n\nOver 80% of American's aircraft are narrow-bodies, mainly [[Airbus A320 series]] and the [[Boeing 737-800]]. It is the largest [[List of Airbus A320 family operators#Airline operators|A320 series aircraft operator]] in the world, as well as the largest operator of the [[A319]] and [[A321]] variants. It is the fourth-largest [[List of Boeing 737 operators#United States|operator of 737 family aircraft]] and second-largest operator of the 737-800 variant. It also currently operates the Boeing [[757-200]] and [[Embraer 190]], though these are slated for retirement and replacement by the [[Boeing 737 MAX|Boeing 737 MAX 8]] and the [[A320 family|Airbus A320 family]] in coming years.<ref name=\"Fleet\"/>\n\nAmerican's wide-body aircraft are a mix of Boeing and Airbus airliners. It is the third-largest [[List of Boeing 787 operators#Current airline operators|operator of the Boeing 787 series]] and the sixth-largest [[List of Boeing 777 operators#Orders and deliveries|operator of the Boeing 777 series]]. It also operates [[Boeing 767]] and [[Airbus A330]] aircraft, with most slated for retirement in favor of additional [[Boeing 787]] aircraft.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://theflight.info/american_airlines/ | title = American Airlines aircraft fleet | archive-url = https://archive.today/20181003141132/http://theflight.info/american_airlines/ | archive-date = October 3, 2018 | url-status=live | access-date = May 13, 2019 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nAmerican Airlines exclusively ordered Boeing aircraft throughout the 2000s.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ruiz |first1=Rebecca |title=Boeing Was 'Go, Go, Go' to Beat Airbus With the 737 Max |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/23/business/boeing-737-max-crash.html |accessdate=27 November 2019 |work=New York Times |date=23 March 2019}}</ref> This strategy shifted on July 20, 2011, when American announced the largest combined aircraft order in history for 460 narrow-body jets including 260 [[Airbus A320|Airbus 320 Series]].<ref>{{cite press release |url= http://news.aa.com/press-releases/press-release-details/2011/AMR-Corporation-Announces-Largest-Aircraft-Order-in-History-With-Boeing-and-Airbus/default.aspx |title= AMR Corporation Announces Largest Aircraft Order in History With Boeing and Airbus |publisher= American Airlines |date= July 20, 2011}}</ref> Additional Airbus aircraft joined the fleet in 2013 upon merger with US Airways, which operated Airbus aircraft almost exclusively.<ref>{{cite web |title=US Airways Fleet |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/US_Airways_fleet |website=wikipedia.org |accessdate=27 November 2019}}</ref>{{Circular reference|date=December 2019}}\n\n== Cabins ==\n{{multiple issues|section=yes\n|{{more citations needed section|date=August 2019}}\n{{third-party|section|date=August 2019}}\n{{unreliable sources section|date=August 2019}}\n}}\n{{multiple image\n|direction = vertical\n|align = right\n|width1 = 220\n|image1 = American A321T First Class (11424575675).jpg\n|caption1 =\n|width2 = 220\n|image2 = American A321T business class (11424746783).jpg\n|caption2 = First and business class seats on an [[Airbus 321|A321]] Transcontinental (top and bottom, respectively)\n}}\n\n;Flagship First\n\nFlagship First is American's international First Class product. It is offered only on the airline's Boeing 777-300ERs. The seats are fully lie-flat and offer direct aisle access in a 1-2-1 reverse herringbone configuration. As with the airline's other premium cabins, Flagship First offers wider food and beverage options, larger seats, and more amenities at certain airports, e.g., lounge access.<ref>{{cite web |title=Flagship First \u2013 International |url=https://www.aa.com/i18n/travel-info/experience/seats/flagship-first-international.jsp |website=American Airlines Website |accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n;Flagship Business\n\nFlagship Business is a premium cabin offered on some Boeing 757-200s and all Airbus A330-200s, Airbus A330-300s, Boeing 767-300ERs, Boeing 777-200ERs, Boeing 777-300ERs, Boeing 787-8s, and Boeing 787-9s. All Flagship Business seats are fully lie-flat.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aa.com/i18n/travel-info/experience/seats/flagship-business-international.jsp|title=Flagship Business - International|publisher=American Airlines|accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref>{{Better source|date=January 2019}} Only the Boeing 757-200 does not offer direct aisle access from each seat.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\n;\n;Transcontinental\nAmerican has dedicated 17 [[Airbus A321]]s (A321T) in its fleet for the specific use of flying transcontinental routes between [[John F. Kennedy International Airport|New York JFK]] and [[Los Angeles International Airport|Los Angeles]], New York JFK and [[San Francisco International Airport|San Francisco]], and [[Logan International Airport|Boston]] and Los Angeles. These aircraft offer two premium cabins, Flagship First and Flagship Business, which are unique among domestic mainline aircraft in American's fleet. Both cabins feature lie-flat seats; Flagship First also includes direct aisle access from each seat.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\n;Domestic First Class\n\nFirst Class is offered on all domestic mainline aircraft, as well as regional aircraft with more than 50 seats. When such aircraft are used on flights to international destinations including Canada, Mexico, Central America, and the Caribbean, the First Class cabin is branded as Business Class. Seats range from {{convert|19|-|21|in|cm}} in width and have {{convert|37|-|42|in|cm}} of pitch.<ref name=\"tripadvisor\">{{cite web|url=http://www.seatguru.com/airlines/American_Airlines/fleetinfo.php|title=American Airlines Planes and Seat Maps|website=Tripadvisor.com|accessdate=May 24, 2015}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=January 2019}} Dining options include free snacks, beverages, and alcohol on all flights, with three-course meals offered on flights {{convert|900|mi|km}} or longer (some routes under 900 miles also offer meal service).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aa.com/i18n/travelInformation/duringFlight/dining/premium-cabin.jsp|title=First and Business Class Dining|website=Aa.com|accessdate=May 24, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150520212859/http://www.aa.com/i18n/travelInformation/duringFlight/dining/premium-cabin.jsp|archivedate=May 20, 2015|df=}}</ref>{{Better source|date=January 2019}}\n\n;Premium Economy\n\nOn December 9, 2015, American announced a new Premium Economy cabin for most long-haul widebody aircraft. The cabin debuted on the airline's Boeing 787-9s in late 2016 and is also available on Boeing 777-200s and -300s, some Boeing 787-8s, and Airbus A330-200s. Premium Economy seats are wider than seats in Main Cabin (American's economy cabin) and provide more amenities: Premium Economy customers get two free checked bags, priority boarding, and enhanced food and drink service including free alcohol. This product made American Airlines the first U.S. carrier to offer a four-cabin aircraft.<ref name=\"upgrd.com\">{{cite web|url=http://upgrd.com/blogs/doublewidesfly/american-airlines-premium-economy-the-only-north-american-carrier-to-offer-a-4-cabin-aircraft.html|title=American Airlines Premium Economy \u2013 The Only North American Carrier to Offer a 4 Cabin Aircraft|website=upgrd.com}}</ref>{{Better source|date=January 2019}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.baggagecircle.com/knowledge-base/american-airlines-carry-on-baggage-policy-2020-2021/ |title=American Airlines Carry On Baggage Policy 2020-2021 |website=Baggage Circle |language=en |access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\n;Main Cabin Extra\n\nAmerican's economy plus product (not to be confused with premium economy), Main Cabin Extra, is available on most of the mainline fleet and [[American Eagle (airline brand)|American Eagle]] regional aircraft with more than 50 seats. Main Cabin Extra seats include greater pitch than is available in Main Cabin,<ref name=\"tripadvisor\" /> along with free alcoholic beverages.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aa.com/i18n/travel-info/experience/seats/main-cabin-extra.jsp|title=Main Cabin Extra|publisher=American Airlines|accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref>{{Better source|date=January 2019}} American retained Main Cabin Extra when the new Premium Economy product entered service in late 2016.<ref name=\"upgrd.com\" />{{Better source|date=January 2019}}\n\n;Main Cabin\n\nMain Cabin is American's economy product, and is found on all mainline and regional aircraft in its fleet. Seats range from {{convert|17|-|18.5|in|cm}} in width and have {{convert|30|-|32|in|cm}} of pitch.<ref>{{cite web|title=American Airlines planes and seat maps|url=https://www.seatguru.com/airlines/American_Airlines/fleetinfo.php|website=tripadvisor.com|accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=January 2019}}\n\nAmerican Airlines marketed increased legroom in economy class as \"More Room Throughout Coach\", also referred to as \"MRTC\", starting in February 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aa.com/i18n/customer-service/about-us/history-of-american-airlines.jsp |title=History of American Airlines \u2013 About us \u2013 American Airlines |publisher=American Airlines |date= |accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref>{{Better source|date=January 2019}} Two rows of economy class seats were removed on Boeing 737 and McDonnell Douglas MD-80 aircraft.<ref name=\"usatoday30.usatoday.com\">{{cite web|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/travel/news/2004-10-20-more-seats_x.htm |title=USATODAY.com \u2013 American Airlines squeezes passengers in tighter to make money |website=Usatoday30.usatoday.com |date=October 21, 2004 |accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref> Amid financial losses, this scheme was discontinued in 2004.<ref name=\"usatoday30.usatoday.com\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://business.time.com/2012/03/02/american-airlines-offering-more-legroom-for-a-price/|title=American Airlines Offering More Legroom \u2026 For a Price|first=Josh|last=Sanburn|website=Business.time.com}}</ref>\n\nOn some routes, American also offers [[Basic Economy]], the airline's lowest main cabin fare. Basic Economy is located in the main cabin but comes with restrictions. These restrictions include waiting until check-in for a seat assignment, no upgrades or refunds, and boarding in the last group.<ref>{{cite web|title=Basic Economy|url=https://www.aa.com/i18n/travel-info/experience/seats/basic-economy.jsp|website=American Airlines|publisher=American Airlines}}</ref>{{Better source|date=January 2019}}\n\nIn May 2017, American announced it would be adding more seats to some of its Boeing 737 MAX jetliners and reducing overall legroom in the basic economy class. The last three rows will lose {{convert|2|in|cm}}, going from the current {{convert|31|in|cm}} to {{convert|29|in|cm}}. The remainder of the economy cabin will have {{convert|30|in|cm}} of legroom.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ostrower |first=Jon |title=American Airlines is cutting more legroom in economy class |work=[[CNN]] Money |publisher=Cable News Network |date=May 3, 2017|url=https://money.cnn.com/2017/05/02/news/companies/american-airlines-legroom/index.html }}</ref>\n\n== Reward programs ==\n=== AAdvantage ===\n{{Main|AAdvantage}}\nAAdvantage is the [[frequent flyer program]] for American Airlines. It was launched on May 1, 1981, and it remains the largest frequent flyer program with over 67 million members as of 2011. Miles accumulated in the program allow members to redeem tickets, upgrade service class, or obtain free or discounted car rentals, hotel stays, merchandise, or other products and services through partners. The most active members, based on the amount and price of travel booked, are designated AAdvantage Gold, AAdvantage Platinum, AAdvantage Platinum Pro, and AAdvantage Executive Platinum elite members, with privileges such as separate check-in, priority upgrade, and standby processing, or free upgrades. They also receive similar privileges from AA's partner airlines, particularly those in [[oneworld]].<ref>[http://www.aa.com/aa/i18nForward.do?p=/AAdvantage/partners/airlines/oneWorld.jsp#elite oneworld Alliance] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081220083602/http://www.aa.com/aa/i18nForward.do?p=%2FAAdvantage%2Fpartners%2Fairlines%2FoneWorld.jsp#elite |date=December 20, 2008 }}. Aa.com (October 1, 2010). Retrieved on November 4, 2010.</ref>{{Better source|date=January 2019}}\n\nAAdvantage co-branded credit cards are also available and offer other benefits. The cards are issued by CitiCards, a subsidiary of [[Citigroup]], and [[Barclaycard]] in the United States, by [[Butterfield Bank]] and [[Scotiabank]] in the Caribbean, and by [[Banco Santander]] in Brazil.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\nAAdvantage allows one-way redemption, starting at 5,000 miles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aa.com/i18n/disclaimers/aadvantageAllPartnerChart.jsp|title=oneworld and Other Airline Award Chart|last=|first=|date=December 18, 2013|website=Aa.com|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20131218060310/http://www.aa.com/i18n/disclaimers/aadvantageAllPartnerChart.jsp|archivedate=December 18, 2013|url-status=dead|access-date=}}</ref>{{Better source|date=January 2019}}\n\n=== Admirals Club ===\nThe Admirals Club was conceived by AA president C.R. Smith as a marketing promotion shortly after he was made an honorary [[Texas Ranger Division|Texas Ranger]]. Inspired by the [[Kentucky colonel]]s and other [[Title of honor|honorary title]] designations, Smith decided to make particularly valued passengers \"admirals\" of the \"Flagship fleet\" (AA called its aircraft \"Flagships\" at the time).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Li |first1=Lucy |title=Ultimate Guide to Admirals Club |url=http://www.loungebuddy.com/admirals-club-ultimate-guide/ |website=LoungeBuddy |publisher=LoungeBuddy, Inc |accessdate=July 20, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906212847/http://www.loungebuddy.com/admirals-club-ultimate-guide/ |archivedate=September 6, 2015 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>{{Better source|date=January 2019}} The list of Admirals included many celebrities, politicians, and other VIPs, as well as more \"ordinary\" customers who had been particularly loyal to the airline.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\nThere was no physical Admirals Club until shortly after the opening of LaGuardia Airport. During the airport's construction, New York Mayor Fiorello LaGuardia had an upper-level lounge set aside for press conferences and business meetings. At one such press conference, he noted that the entire terminal was being offered for lease to airline tenants; after a reporter asked whether the lounge would be leased as well, LaGuardia replied that it would, and a vice president of AA immediately offered to lease the premises. The airline then procured a liquor license and began operating the lounge as the \"Admirals Club\" in 1939.{{citation needed|date=December 2013}}\n\nThe second Admirals Club opened at Washington National Airport. Because it was illegal to sell alcohol in Virginia at the time, the club contained refrigerators for the use of its members, so they could store their liquor at the airport.{{citation needed|date=December 2013}} For many years, membership in the Admirals Club (and most other airline lounges) was by the airline's invitation. After a passenger sued for discrimination,<ref name=\"timeac\">{{cite news|title=Toward Equality for VIPs |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,836046,00.html?iid=chix-sphere |work=TIME |date=July 15, 1966 |accessdate=January 26, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090114112519/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0%2C9171%2C836046%2C00.html?iid=chix-sphere |archivedate=January 14, 2009 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> the Club (and most other airline lounges) switched to a paid membership program.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\n=== Flagship Lounge ===\nThough affiliated with the Admirals Club and staffed by many of the same employees, the Flagship Lounge is a separate lounge specifically designed for customers flying in First Class and Business Class on international flights and transcontinental domestic flights, as well as AAdvantage Concierge Key, Executive Platinum, Platinum Pro, and Platinum, as well as Oneworld Emerald and Sapphire frequent flyers. As of May 2019, Flagship Lounges are located at five airports: New York\u2013JFK,<ref name=\"JFK\">{{cite web|url=http://fortune.com/go/luxury/american-airlines-flaship-lounge-jfk-airport/|last=Tkaczyk|first=Christopher |date=May 25, 2017|title=An Inside Look at the New American Airlines Flagship Lounge at JFK Airport|work=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]|accessdate=May 14, 2019}}</ref> Chicago-O'Hare,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/chicago/news/2017/09/13/american-airlines-rolls-out-flashy-flagship-lounge.html|last=Lazare |first=Lewis |date=September 13, 2017|title=American Airlines rolls out flashy Flagship Lounge at O'Hare Airport (Photos)|work=[[Chicago Business Journal]]|accessdate=May 14, 2019}}</ref> Miami International,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/business/fl-bz-mia-new-american-flagship-lounge-20171116-story.html|last=Satchell|first= Arlene|date=November 16, 2017|title=American's Flagship Lounge at MIA opens Tuesday for first-class, business travelers|work=[[Sun-Sentinel]]|accessdate=May 14, 2019}}</ref> Los Angeles,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/travel/news/article.cfm?c_id=7&objectid=12193870|last=Jurgens |first=Jane |date=January 23, 2019|title=Lounge Check: American Airlines Flagship Business Class lounge at LAX|work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|accessdate=May 14, 2019}}</ref> and Dallas/Fort Worth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/dallas/news/2019/05/14/american-airlines-flagship-lounge-dfw-airport.html?|last=Hoopfer |first=Evan |date=May 14, 2019|title=Shower in an airport? See inside American's swanky new DFW lounge|work=[[American City Business Journals#Dallas Business Journal|Dallas Business Journal]]|accessdate=May 14, 2019}}</ref> Flagship Lounges are planned for London-Heathrow and Philadelphia.<ref name=\"JFK\" />\n\n== Corporate affairs ==\n===Ownership and structure===\nAmerican Airlines, Inc. is publicly traded through its parent company, [[American Airlines Group]] Inc., under NASDAQ: AAL {{NASDAQ|AAL}}, with a market capitalization of about $12 billion as of 2019, and is included in the [[S&P 500 Index|S&P 500 index]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAmerican Eagle is a network of six regional carriers that operate under a codeshare and service agreement with American, operating flights to destinations in the United States, Canada, the Caribbean and Mexico.  Three of these carriers are independent and three are subsidiaries of American Airlines Group: [[Envoy Air|Envoy Air Inc.]], [[Piedmont Airlines|Piedmont Airlines, Inc.]], and [[PSA Airlines|PSA Airlines Inc.]]<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Headquarters ===\nAmerican Airlines is headquartered in [[Fort Worth, Texas]], adjacent to the [[Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport]].<ref>\"[https://americanairlines.gcs-web.com/node/33546/html Form 8-K].\" American Airlines. Retrieved May 18, 2018. [https://americanairlines.gcs-web.com/static-files/f88fecf5-c693-4bb3-a04e-c1daab4f8141 PDF version] \u2013 \"4333 Amon Carter Blvd., Fort Worth, Texas\"</ref> The headquarters is located in two office buildings in the CentrePort office complex and these buildings together have about {{convert|1400000|sqft|sqm}} of space. {{as of|2014}} over 4,300 employees work at this complex.<ref>\"[http://www.aa.com/i18n/amrcorp/corporateInformation/facts/americanairlinesgroup.jsp American Airlines Group Overview] [https://web.archive.org/web/20140410145206/http://www.aa.com/i18n/amrcorp/corporateInformation/facts/americanairlinesgroup.jsp Archived copy] (April 10, 2014).\" American Airlines. Retrieved on April 24, 2014.</ref>\n\nBefore it was headquartered in Texas, American Airlines was headquartered at 633 Third Avenue in the [[Murray Hill, Manhattan|Murray Hill]] area of [[Midtown Manhattan]], New York City.<ref>''World Airline Directory''. [[Flight International]]. March 20, 1975. \"[http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1975/1975%20-%200536.html 472].</ref><ref>\"[http://gonyc.about.com/od/manhattan/l/bl_gramercy.htm Flatiron / Gramercy / Murray Hill / Union Square: Manhattan Neighborhood Map].\" ''[[About.com]]''. Retrieved January 25, 2009.</ref> In 1979, American moved its headquarters to a site at [[Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport]], which affected up to 1,300 jobs. [[Mayor of New York City]] [[Ed Koch]] described the move as a \"betrayal\" of New York City.<ref>Sterba, James P. \"[https://www.nytimes.com/1978/11/16/archives/american-will-shift-headquarters-from-manhattan-to-dallas-airport.html American Will Shift Headquarters From Manhattan to Dallas Airport; Big Economies Predicted].\" ''[[The New York Times]]''. Thursday November 16, 1978. Page A1. Retrieved August 27, 2009.</ref> American moved to two leased office buildings in [[Grand Prairie, Texas]].<ref name=\"FortWorthHQFinished\">\"[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=9ZYTAAAAIBAJ&sjid=5gUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3054,25513&dq=american-airlines+new+headquarters American Airlines Finishes Moving into Headquarters Monday].\" ''[[Associated Press]]'' at ''[[Ocala Star-Banner]]''. January 16, 1983. 6A. ''[[Google News]]'' 4 of 62. Retrieved August 27, 2009.</ref><!--January 16, 1983 is a Sunday, so January 17 would be a Monday--> On January 17, 1983, the airline finished moving into a $150&nbsp;million (${{inflation|USD|150,000,000|1983|r=-6|fmt=c}} when adjusted for inflation), {{convert|550000|sqft|adj=on}} facility in Fort Worth; $147&nbsp;million (about ${{inflation|USD|147,000,000|1983|r=-6|fmt=c}} when adjusted for inflation) in Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport bonds financed the headquarters. The airline began leasing the facility from the airport, which owns the facility.<ref name=\"FortWorthHQFinished\" /> Following the merger of US Airways and American Airlines, US Airways consolidated the corporate headquarters of the new company in Fort Worth, leaving their current headquarters in Phoenix, AZ, which had also been the headquarters of the airline that brought US Airways out of bankruptcy, [[America West Airlines]].\n\nAs of 2015, American Airlines is the corporation with the largest presence in Fort Worth.<ref name=BrownSteveHQ>Brown, Steve. \"[http://www.dallasnews.com/business/airline-industry/20151022-american-airlines-will-build-new-headquarters-in-fort-worth1.ece American Airlines will build new headquarters in Fort Worth]\" ([https://web.archive.org/web/20151024145639/http://www.dallasnews.com/business/airline-industry/20151022-american-airlines-will-build-new-headquarters-in-fort-worth1.ece Archive]). ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]''. October 22, 2015. Retrieved on October 27, 2015. \"Robert Sturns, Fort Worth's economic development director, said the city was committed to keeping its largest corporate citizen.\"</ref>\n\nIn 2015, American announced that it would build a new headquarters in Fort Worth. Groundbreaking began in the spring of 2016 and occupancy completed in September 2019.<ref name=OwensWhitelyDouglas>Owens, Marjorie, Jason Whitely, and Jim Douglas. \"[http://www.wfaa.com/story/news/2015/10/22/american-to-build-new-headquarters-in-fort-worth/74395434/ American to build new headquarters in Fort Worth]\" ([https://web.archive.org/web/20151024221818/http://www.wfaa.com/story/news/2015/10/22/american-to-build-new-headquarters-in-fort-worth/74395434/ Archive]). ''[[WFAA]]''. October 22, 2015. Retrieved on October 24, 2015.</ref> The airline plans to house 5,000 new workers in the building.<ref name=BrownSteveHQ />\n\nIt will be located on a {{convert|41|acre|ha|adj=on}} property adjacent to the airline's flight academy and conference and training center, west of [[Texas State Highway 360]], {{convert|2|mi|km}}<ref name=OwensWhitelyDouglas /> west from the current headquarters. The airline will lease a total of {{convert|300|acre|ha}} from Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport and this area will include the headquarters.<ref name=BrownSteveHQ /> Construction of the new headquarters began after the demolition of the Sabre facility, previously on the site.<ref name=OwensWhitelyDouglas />\n\nThe airline considered developing a new headquarters in [[Irving, Texas]], on the old [[Texas Stadium]] site, before deciding to keep the headquarters in Fort Worth.<ref name=BrownSteveHQ />\n\n=== Corporate identity ===\n[[File:American Airlines logo.svg|thumb|American Airlines' fourth logo, used from 1967 to January 16, 2013]]\n\n==== Logo ====\nIn 1931, Goodrich Murphy, an American employee, designed the AA logo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.com/2015/05/tales-era-airlines-knew-good-design/|title=Tales From an Era When Airlines Knew Good Design |website=Wired.com |accessdate=May 22, 2015}}</ref> The logo was redesigned by [[Massimo Vignelli]] in 1967.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vignelli.com/home/identity/aa.html |title=Vignelli Associates About the AA Logo |website=Vignelli.com |accessdate=December 2, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201175513/http://vignelli.com/home/identity/aa.html |archive-date=December 1, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.logosdesigners.com/#massimo-vignelli|title=iconic logo designers|website=logosdesigners.com|accessdate=April 3, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100124021004/http://www.logosdesigners.com/#massimo-vignelli|archive-date=January 24, 2010|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> Thirty years later, in 1997, American Airlines was able to make its logo Internet-compatible by buying the domain AA.com. ''AA'' is also American's two-letter [[IATA]] [[airline codes|airline designator]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Current Airline Members |url=https://www.iata.org/about/members/Pages/airline-list.aspx?All=true |website=Iata.org |accessdate=February 5, 2019 |language=English}}</ref>\n\nOn January 17, 2013, American launched a new rebranding and marketing campaign with FutureBrand dubbed, \"A New American\". This included a new logo replacing the logo used since 1967. American Airlines calls the new logo the \"Flight Symbol, incorporating the eagle, star, and the letter \"A\" of the classic logo.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aa.com/newamerican?anchorLocation=HomePageHero1&reportedTitle=Becoming%20a%20new%20American&reportedPosition=0&url=undefined&_locale=en_US&repositoryName=undefined&repositoryId=undefined |title=Becoming a new American |website=Aa.com |date= |accessdate=March 6, 2013}}</ref>{{better source|date=January 2019}}\n\nAmerican Airlines faced difficulty obtaining copyright registration for their 2013 logo. On June 3, 2016, American Airlines sought to register it with the [[United States Copyright Office]],<ref name=\"US Copyright Office Ruling\">{{cite web|last1=Zaller Rowland|first1=Catherine|title=Re: Second Request for Reconsideration for Refusal to Register American Airlines Flight Symbol; Correspondence ID: 1-28H4ZFK; SR#: 1-3537494381|url=https://www.copyright.gov/rulings-filings/review-board/docs/american-airlines-flight-symbol.pdf|date=January 8, 2018|website=Copyright.gov|publisher=[[United States Copyright Office]]|accessdate=January 26, 2018}}</ref> but in October of that year, the Copyright Office ruled that the logo was ineligible for copyright protection, as it did not pass the [[threshold of originality]], and was thus in the [[public domain]].<ref name=\"US Copyright Office Ruling\" /> American requested that the Copyright Office reconsider, but on January 8, 2018, the Copyright Office affirmed its initial determination.<ref name=\"US Copyright Office Ruling\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=US Copyright Office Says What We're All Thinking: American Airlines Lacks Creativity \u2013 One Mile at a Time|url=http://onemileatatime.boardingarea.com/2018/01/25/american-airlines-copyright/|website=One Mile at a Time|date=January 25, 2018}}</ref> After American Airlines submitted additional materials, the Copyright Office reversed its decision on December 7, 2018, and ruled that the logo contained enough creativity to merit copyright protection.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.copyright.gov/rulings-filings/review-board/docs/american-airlines.pdf |title=Re: Registration Decision Regarding American Airlines Flight Symbol; Correspondence ID 1-28H4ZFK; SR 1-3537494381 |date=December 7, 2018 |publisher=[[United States Copyright Office]] |access-date=June 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Aircraft livery ====\nAmerican's early [[aircraft livery|liveries]] varied widely, but a common livery was adopted in the 1930s, featuring an [[eagle]] painted on the fuselage.<ref>{{ cite web | url = http://www.airlinesanddestinations.com/aircraft/american-airlines-unveils-new-logo-and-livery/ | title = American Airlines Unveils New Logo and Livery | website = Airlines and Destinations | date = January 17, 2013 | accessdate = July 26, 2017 }}</ref> The eagle became a symbol of the company and inspired the name of [[Envoy Air|American Eagle Airlines]]. Propeller aircraft featured an [[international orange]] lightning bolt running down the length of the fuselage, which was replaced by a simpler orange stripe with the introduction of jets.\"<ref>Boeing 707 Jet Airliner Non-Stop Service between New York City and Los Angeles\", ''Boeing Magazine'' 30 (1958), 66.</ref>\n\n[[File:American Airlines Astrojet N951AA.jpg|thumb|A Boeing 737 in the Astrojet livery]]\n\nIn the late 1960s, American commissioned designer [[Massimo Vignelli]] to develop a new livery. The original design called for a red, white, and blue stripe on the fuselage, and a simple \"AA\" logo, without an eagle, on the tail; instead, Vignelli created a highly stylized eagle, which remained the company's logo until January 16, 2013. In 1999, American painted a new [[Boeing 757]] (N679AN) in its 1959 international orange livery. One [[Boeing 777]] and one Boeing 757 were painted in standard livery with a pink ribbon on the sides and the tail, in support of [[Susan G. Komen for the Cure]]. One Boeing 757 is painted with a yellow ribbon on the tailfin on the aircraft and the side of the body says \"Flagship Freedom\". American Eagle, the airline's regional airline has the same special livery on ERJ-145 aircraft.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\n[[File:AA Flagship Freedom.JPG|thumb|left|AA \"Flagship Freedom\" [[Boeing 757-200]], labeled with a \"[[Yellow ribbon|yellow awareness ribbon]]\" symbol, representing support of the [[United States Armed Forces]] overseas operations.]]\nOn January 17, 2013, American unveiled a new livery.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/breaking/chi-american-airlines-livery-20130117,0,198977.story |title=American Airlines unveils new logo, livery |work=Chicago Tribune |date=January 17, 2013 |accessdate=January 17, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130217030650/http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/breaking/chi-american-airlines-livery-20130117,0,198977.story |archive-date=February 17, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Before then, American had been the only major U.S. airline to leave most of its aircraft surfaces unpainted. This was because C. R. Smith would not say he liked painted aircraft and refused to use any liveries that involved painting the entire plane. Robert \"Bob\" Crandall later justified the distinctive natural metal finish by noting that less paint reduced the aircraft's weight, thus saving on fuel costs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://industry.bnet.com/travel/1000148/paint-vs-bare-metal-on-airplanes/ |title=Delta, Air Canada Among Carriers Weighing Benefit of Paint Stripping |website=Industry.bnet.com |date=October 8, 2008 |accessdate=December 2, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:US Airways A319-112 LAS N717UW.jpg|thumb|Airbus A319 of US Airways wearing [[Carolina Panthers]] livery]]\n[[File:N921NN B737-823W American Al YVR 24JUL13 (9362686624).jpg|thumb|Boeing 737 aircraft N921NN, the final aircraft delivered to American in the polished aluminum livery, retained as a heritage aircraft.]]\n\nIn January 2013, American launched a new rebranding and marketing campaign dubbed, \"The New American\". In addition to a new logo, American Airlines introduced a new livery for its fleet. The airline calls the new livery and branding \"a clean and modern update\".<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> The current design features an abstract American flag on the tail, along with a silver-painted fuselage, as a throw-back to the old livery. The new design was painted by [[Leading Edge Aviation Services]] in [[California]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Ahles |first=Andrea |url=http://www.star-telegram.com/2013/01/17/4556563/american-airlines-shows-off-new.html |title=Star-Telegram 18 January 2013: \"American Airlines shows off new look for new era\" |website=Star-telegram.com |date=January 18, 2013 |accessdate=January 29, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130310095631/http://www.star-telegram.com/2013/01/17/4556563/american-airlines-shows-off-new.html |archivedate=March 10, 2013 }}</ref> Doug Parker, the incoming CEO indicated that the new livery could be short-lived, stating that \"maybe we need to do something slightly different than that ... The only reason this is an issue now is because they just did it right in the middle, which kind of makes it confusing, so that gives us an opportunity, actually, to decide if we are going to do something different because we have so many airplanes to paint\".<ref>King, Eric. (March 28, 2013) [http://www.nbcdfw.com/news/business/American-Airlines-New-Livery-Soon-Could-Become-Its-Old-Look-200532901.html American Airline's New Livery Soon Could Become Its Old Look | NBC 5 Dallas-Fort Worth]. Nbcdfw.com. Retrieved on July 18, 2013.</ref> The current logo and livery have had mixed criticism, with ''[[Design Shack]]'' editor Joshua Johnson writing that they 'boldly and proudly communicate the concepts of American pride and freedom wrapped into a shape that instantly makes you think about an airplane',<ref name=\"designshackliverypraise\">{{cite web |last1=Johnson |first1=Joshua |title=Check Out the New American Airlines Logo |url=https://designshack.net/articles/graphics/check-out-the-new-american-airlines-logo/ |website=Design Shack |accessdate=June 11, 2019 |date=January 23, 2013}}</ref> and ''[http://www.askthepilot.com/ AskThePilot.com]'' author Patrick Smith describing the logo as 'a linoleum knife poking through a shower curtain'.<ref name=\"patricksmithcriticism\">{{cite web |last1=Smith |first1=Patrick |title=The New American Airlines Livery |url=http://www.askthepilot.com/american-to-keep-new-livery/ |website=AskThePilot.com |accessdate=June 11, 2019 |date=January 6, 2014}}</ref> Later in January 2013, [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] asked the designer of the 1968 American Airlines logo ([[Massimo Vignelli]]) on his opinion over the rebranding.<ref name=\"vignelliqna\">{{cite news |last1=Mayo |first1=Keenan |title=Q&A: Original American Airlines Designer Massimo Vignelli on the Redesigned Logo |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-01-18/q-and-a-original-american-airlines-designer-massimo-vignelli-on-the-redesigned-logo |accessdate=August 7, 2019 |work=Bloomberg.com |publisher=Bloomberg L.P. |date=January 19, 2013 |format=Web}}</ref>\n\nIn the end, American let their employees decide the new livery's fate. On an internal website for employees, American posted two options, one the new livery and one a modified version of the old livery. All of the [[American Airlines Group]] employees (including US Airways and other affiliates) were able to vote.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.dallasnews.com/business/airlines/2013/12/16/doug-parker-to-let-american-airlines-employees-decide-whether-to-keep-the-new-aa-tail | title = Doug Parker to let American Airlines employees decide whether to keep the new AA tail | website = [[Dallas News]] | last = Maxon | first = Terry | date = December 2013 | accessdate = July 26, 2017 }}</ref> American ultimately decided to keep the new look. Parker announced that American would keep a US Airways and America West heritage aircraft in the fleet, with plans to add a heritage TWA aircraft and a heritage American plane with the old livery.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.nbcdfw.com/news/business/American-Airlines-Employees-Vote-to-Keep-New-Livery-238487381.html | title = American Airlines Employees Vote to Keep New Livery | website = [[NBC]] | last = Heinz | first = Frank | date = January 2, 2014 | accessdate = July 26, 2017 }}</ref> As of September 2019, American has heritage aircraft for Piedmont, PSA, America West, US Airways, Reno Air, TWA, and AirCal in their fleet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apex.aero/2015/12/03/heritage-livery-flies-again-american-airlines-retro-rollout|title=[PHOTOS] Heritage Livery Flies Again in American Airlines' Retro Rollout|date=2015-12-03|website=APEX {{!}} Airline Passenger Experience|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref> They also have two AA branded heritage 737-800 aircraft, an AstroJet N905NN,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://airlinegeeks.com/2017/06/05/photos-american-rolls-out-new-astrojet-themed-boeing-737-800/|title=Photos: American Rolls out New AstroJet-Themed Boeing 737-800|last=Ewing|first=Ryan|date=2017-06-05|website=AirlineGeeks.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref> and the polished aluminum livery used from 1967 to 2013, N921NN.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://airlinegeeks.com/2017/12/14/american-quietly-adds-new-polished-aluminum-retro-livery-to-a-boeing-737-800/|title=American Quietly Adds Polished Aluminum Retro Livery to a Boeing 737-800|last=Ewing|first=Ryan|date=2017-12-14|website=AirlineGeeks.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref>\n\n=== Worker relations ===\nThe main representatives of key groups of employees are:\n* The [[Allied Pilots Association]] is an in-house union which represents the nearly 15,000 American Airlines pilots; it was created in 1963 after the pilots left the [[Air Line Pilots Association]] (ALPA).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alliedpilots.org/Public/AboutAPA/Background/background.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=February 5, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160204003305/https://www.alliedpilots.org/Public/AboutAPA/Background/background.asp |archivedate=February 4, 2016 |df= }}</ref> However the majority of American Eagle pilots are ALPA members.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.alpa.org/en/about-alpa/our-pilot-groups/pilot-groups/envoy|title=Envoy Air \u2013 ALPA|website=alpa.org|access-date=October 26, 2016}}</ref>\n* The [[Association of Professional Flight Attendants]] represents American Airlines flight attendants, including former USAirways flight attendants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dallasnews.com/business/airline-industry/20141218-american-airlines-flight-attendants-to-get-bigger-pay-raises-after-all.ece|title=American Airlines flight attendants to get bigger pay raises after all|website=Dallasnews.com|accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref>\n* Flight attendants at wholly owned Regional Carriers (Envoy, Piedmont and PSA) are all represented by [http://www.afacwa.org/ Association of Flight Attendants \u2013 Communications Workers of America] (AFA-CWA). US Airways flight attendants were active members of AFA-CWA before the merger, and they are honorary lifetime members. AFA-CWA is the largest flight attendant union in the industry.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n* The [[Transport Workers Union of America|Transport Workers Union-International Association of Machinists alliance]] (TWU-IAM) represents the majority of American Airlines employed fleet service agents, mechanics and other ground workers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.star-telegram.com/news/business/aviation/sky-talk-blog/article36302475.html|title=American CEO says contract proposals to ground workers to have \"double-digit\" pay increases|website=Star-telegram.com|accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref>\n* American's customer service and gate employees belong to the [[Communications Workers of America]]/[[International Brotherhood of Teamsters]] Passenger Service Association.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviationblog.dallasnews.com/2015/11/american-airlines-gate-agents-approve-a-new-labor-contract.html/|title=American Airlines customer service and gate agents approve new labor contract|last =Jean|first =Sheryl|website=Airline Biz Blog}}</ref>\n\n== Concerns and conflicts ==\n=== Environmental violations ===\nBetween October 1993 to July 1998, American Airlines was repeatedly cited for using high-sulfur fuel in motor vehicles at 10 major airports around the country, a violation of the [[Clean Air Act (United States)|Clean Air Act]].<ref name=\"epa\">{{cite web|title=American Airlines Will Make Clean Air Improvements at Logan Airport Reports to EPA the Use of Illegal High Sulfur Fuel in Motor Vehicles|url=http://epa.gov/NE/pr/1999/072099b.html |website=[[United States Environmental Protection Agency]]|date=July 19, 1999|accessdate=January 25, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070707175156/http://epa.gov/ne/pr/1999/072099b.html|archivedate=July 7, 2007}}</ref>\n\n=== Lifetime AAirpass ===\nSince 1981, as a means of creating revenue in a period of loss-making, American Airlines had offered a [[AAirpass|lifetime pass]] of unlimited travel, for the initial cost of $250,000. This entitled the pass holder to fly anywhere in the world. 28 were sold. However, after some time, the airline realised they were making losses on the tickets, with the ticketholders costing them up to $1 million each. Ticketholders were booking large amounts of flights, and some ticketholders flying interstate for lunch or flying to London multiple times a month. AA raised the cost of the lifetime pass to $3 million, and then finally stopped offering it in 2003. AA then used litigation to cancel two of the lifetime offers, saying the passes \"had been terminated due to fraudulent activity\".<ref name=\"pass\">{{cite web|title='Free'quent flier has wings clipped after American Airlines takes away his unlimited pass|url=https://nypost.com/2012/05/13/freequent-flier-has-wings-clipped-after-american-airlines-takes-away-his-unlimited-pass/ |publisher=New York Post|date=May 13, 2012|accessdate=October 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Cabin fume events ===\n* In 1988, on American Airlines Flight 132's approach into Nashville, flight attendants notified the cockpit that there was smoke in the cabin. The flight crew in the cockpit ignored the warning, as on a prior flight, a [[fume event]] had occurred due to a problem with the [[auxiliary power unit]]. However, the smoke on Flight 132 was caused by improperly packaged hazardous materials. According to the [[National Transportation Safety Board|NTSB]] inquiry, the cockpit crew persistently refused to acknowledge that there was a serious threat to the aircraft or the passengers, even after they were told that floor was becoming soft and passengers had to be reseated. As a result, the aircraft was not evacuated immediately on landing, exposing the crew and passengers to the threat of smoke and fire longer than necessary.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/a02a/6b1ff0725d682e3ab0fa55681a1db46af4ad.pdf|title=Chute, Rebecca D., and Earl L. Winter. \"Cockpit-cabin communication: II. Shall we tell the pilots?.\" The International Journal of Aviation Psychology 6.3 (1996): 211-231.|website=Pdfs.semanticscholar.org|accessdate=February 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://flightsafety.org/asw/jul12/asw_jul12_p32-35.pdf|title=Cross, Jamie. \"Sources of friction.\" AeroSafety world 7.online (2012): 32-35.|website=Flightsafety.org|accessdate=February 23, 2019}}</ref>\n* On April 11, 2007, toxic smoke and oil fumes leaked into the aircraft cabin as American Airlines Flight 843 taxied to the gate. A flight attendant who was present in the cabin subsequently filed a lawsuit against Boeing, stating that she was diagnosed with neurotoxic disorder due to her exposure to the fumes, which caused her to experience memory loss, tremors, and severe headaches. She settled with the company in 2011.<ref>[http://www.nbcnews.com/id/44777304/ns/travel-news/t/boeing-suit-settlement-stirs-jetliner-air-safety-debate/#.XFqZYVUzaUk Boeing suit settlement stirs jetliner air safety debate], NBC news, October 6, 2011</ref>\n* In 2009, Mike Holland, deputy chairman for radiation and environmental issues at the [[Allied Pilots Association]] and an American Airlines pilot, said that the pilot union had started alerting pilots of the danger of contaminated [[bleed air]], including contacting crew members that the union thinks were exposed to contamination based on maintenance records and pilot logs.<ref>[https://zembla.bnnvara.nl/pdf/wsj_fume_events.pdf Nassauer, Sarah. \"Up in the Air: New Worries About 'Fume Events' on Planes.\"] The Wall Street Journal (2009).</ref>\n* In a January 2017 incident on American Airlines Flight 1896, seven flight attendants were hospitalized after a strange odor was detected in the cabin. The Airbus A330 involved subsequently underwent a \"thorough maintenance inspection,\" having been involved in three fume events in three months.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/news/fume-incident-hospitalises-american-airlines-crew-and-raises-questions-over-safety-of-cabin-air/ 'Fume event' hospitalises American Airlines crew in latest incident concerning cabin air], Telegraph, January 4, 2017</ref><ref>[https://abcnews.go.com/US/american-airlines-jet-suffers-fume-incident-months-flight/story?id=44535862 American Airlines Jet Has 3rd Fume Incident in 3 Months, 7 Flight Attendants Transported to Hospital and Released], ABC news, January 3, 2017</ref>\n* In August 2018, American Airlines flight attendants picketed in front of the Fort Worth company headquarters over a change in sick day policy, complaining that exposure to ill passengers, toxic uniforms, toxic cabin air, radiation exposure, and other issues were causing them to be sick.<ref>[https://www.businessinsider.com/american-airlines-flight-attendants-protest-sick-policy-toxic-uniform-2018-8 American Airlines flight attendants are gearing up for battle over the company's 'punitive' new attendance policy], Business Insider, August 31, 2018</ref><ref>[https://www.bizjournals.com/chicago/news/2018/08/29/american-airlines-flight-attendants-to-picket.html American Airlines flight attendants to picket headquarters Thursday], August 29, 2018, Chicago Business Journal</ref>\n* In January 2019, two pilots and three flight attendants on Flight 1897 from Philadelphia to Fort Lauderdale were hospitalized following complaints of a strange odor.<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/flights/2019/01/10/american-airlines-crew-sickened-philadelphia-florida-flight/2537776002/ American Airlines pilots, flight attendants fall ill on Philadelphia to Florida flight], USA Today, January 11, 2019</ref><ref>[https://www.foxnews.com/travel/american-airlines-staffers-florida-airport-odor Five American Airlines staffers hospitalized after noticing 'odor' on plane], FOX News, January 10, 2019</ref>\n\n=== Discrimination complaints ===\nOn October 24, 2017, the [[NAACP]] issued a travel advisory for American Airlines urging [[African Americans]] to \"exercise caution\" when traveling with the airline. The NAACP issued the advisory after four incidents. In one incident, a black woman was moved from First Class to coach while her white traveling companion was allowed to remain in First Class. In another incident, a black man was forced to give up his seats after being confronted by two unruly white passengers.<ref name=\"PBS20171025\">[https://www.pbs.org/newshour/nation/the-naacp-issues-travel-advisory-for-american-airlines-warning-black-passengers-of-disturbing-incidents The NAACP issues travel advisory for American Airlines, warning black passengers of 'disturbing incidents'], PBS, October 25, 2017</ref> According to the NAACP, while they did receive complaints on other airlines, most of their complaints in the year prior to their advisory were on American Airlines.<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2017/10/25/naacp-most-complaints-american-airlines-what-can-brands-learn/800300001/ NAACP: Most complaints about American Airlines. What can brands learn?], USA Today, October 25, 2017</ref> In July 2018, the NAACP lifted their travel advisory saying that American has made improvements to mitigate discrimination and unsafe treatment of African Americans.<ref name=\"PBS20180717\">[https://www.pbs.org/newshour/nation/naacp-lifts-travel-advisory-against-american-airlines NAACP lifts travel advisory against American Airlines], PBS, July 17, 2018</ref>\n\n== Accidents and incidents ==\n{{Main|List of American Airlines accidents and incidents}}\nAs of March 2019, the airline has had almost sixty aircraft [[hull loss]]es, beginning with the crash of an American Airways [[Ford Trimotor|Ford 5-AT-C Trimotor]] in August 1931.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/operator/airline.php?var=9366 |title=American Airways safety occurrences |website=[[Aviation Safety Network]] |publisher=[[Flight Safety Foundation]] |access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref><ref name=ASNAA>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/operator/airline.php?var=6516 |title=American Airlines safety occurrences |website=[[Aviation Safety Network]] |publisher=[[Flight Safety Foundation]] |access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref> Of these most were propeller driven aircraft, including three [[Lockheed L-188 Electra]] turboprop aircraft (of which one, the crash in 1959 of [[American Airlines Flight 320|Flight 320]], resulted in fatalities).<ref name=ASNAA /> The two accidents with the highest fatalities in both the airline's and U.S. aviation history were [[American Airlines Flight 191|Flight 191]] in 1979 and [[American Airlines Flight 587|Flight 587]] in 2001.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aviation-safety.net/database/country/country.php?id=N|title=Aviation Safety Network > ASN Aviation Safety Database > Geographical regions > United States of America air safety profile|last=Ranter|first=Harro|website=aviation-safety.net|access-date=2019-07-26}}</ref>\n\nOn December 20, 1995, [[American Airlines Flight 965|Flight 965]] crashed into a mountain in Buga, Colombia, killing 151 out of the 155 passengers and all eight crew members. The aircraft was a Boeing 757-223 (registration N651AA). It was on approach to Cali, Colombia when it veered off course and crashed into the terrain.\n\nTwo aircraft were hijacked and destroyed in the [[September 11 attacks]]: [[American Airlines Flight 11|Flight 11]] crashed into the north facade of the [[One World Trade Center|North Tower]] of the [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]], and [[Flight 77]] crashed into [[the Pentagon]]; both were bound for [[Los Angeles International Airport|LAX]] from [[Boston Logan International Airport]] and [[Washington Dulles International Airport]] respectively.<ref>{{cite book|editor=Paul Joseph|title=The SAGE Encyclopedia of War: Social Science Perspectives|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=idw0DQAAQBAJ&pg=PA1533|year=2016|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=978-1-4833-5988-5|page=1533}}</ref>\n\nOther accidents include the [[American Airlines Flight 383 (2016)|Flight 383]] engine failure and fire in 2016. There were two training flight accidents in which the crew were killed and six that resulted in no fatalities.<ref name=ASNAA /> Another four jet aircraft have been written off due to incidents while they were parked between flights or while undergoing maintenance.<ref name=ASNAA />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[AAirpass]]\n* [[Air transportation in the United States]]\n* [[List of airlines of the United States]]\n* [[List of airports in the United States]]\n*[[U.S. Airways]] which has merged with American Airlines\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin|33em}}\n* {{Cite book |first=John M. |last=Capozzi |title=A Spirit of Greatness |publisher=JMC |year=2001 |isbn=978-0-9656410-3-6 |url=https://archive.org/details/spiritofgreatnes00john }}\n* {{Cite book |first=Don |last=Bedwell |title=Silverbird: The American Airlines Story |publisher=Airways |year=1999 |isbn=978-0-9653993-6-4 }}\n* {{Cite book |first=Al |last=Casey |title=Casey's Law |publisher=Arcade |year=1997 |isbn=978-1-55970-307-9 }}\n* {{Cite book |first=Simon |last=Forty |title=ABC American Airlines |publisher=Ian Allan |year=1997 |isbn=978-1-882663-21-7 }}\n* {{Cite book |first=Dan |last=Reed |title=The American Eagle: The Ascent of Bob Crandall and American Airlines |publisher=St. Martin's |year=1993 |isbn=978-0-312-08696-1 |url=https://archive.org/details/americaneagleasc00reed }}\n* {{Cite book |first=Robert J. |last=Serling |title=Eagle |publisher=St. Martin's |year=1985 |isbn=978-0-312-22453-0 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/eaglehistoryofam0000serl }}\n* {{Cite book |title=International Directory of Company Histories |publisher=St. James Press }}\n* Hieger, Linda H. (2010) ''With Wings of Silver and Gold'' {{ISBN|978-1-60458-271-0}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikivoyage|Air travel in the United States}}\n{{Sister project links|wikt=no|b=no|q=no|s=no|v=no|species=no|voy=American Airlines}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.aa.com/|mobile=https://mobile.aa.com/}}\n** \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20090826204620/http://www.aa.com/aa/i18nForward.do?p=%2Furls%2Fsocial.jsp&anchorLocation=Homepage_Bottom&url=%2Faa%2Fi18nForward.do&_locale=en_US&repositoryName=PromotionContentRepository&repositoryId=16122773&reportedTitle=AA+On+Twitter&flash=false American Airlines is Social]\" \u2013 Links to official Facebook, Google+ and Twitter\n* [https://www.aavacations.com/ Official American Airlines Vacations website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20040414093042/http://americanwaymag.com/ ''American Way'' inflight magazine]\n* [http://timetableimages.com/ttimages/aa.htm Timetableimages.com] has many timetables from the 1930s until 1967, showing where American flew, how often, how long it took and how much it cost.\n* {{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/interview-doug-parker-chief-executive-american-ai-445433/ |title= Interview: Doug Parker, chief executive, American Airlines |date= February 20, 2018 |last= Russell |first= Edward |work= Flightglobal}}\n\n{{American Airlines}}\n{{Airlines of the United States}}\n{{Navbo